Introduction

This document contains information on how to set up leandc application. Configuration of leandc application consists of several XML files and contents of these files are described in this document.

leandc application is distributed as a compiled binary file that can be executed on a 32bit or 64bit Linux Operating System.
Application installer contains separate binary files for the following CPU architectures:
> Intel x86
> ARM926EJ-S

Application can be used on any hardware with these processors. List of hardwares that application have been tested on is summarized in the table below.

Table 1.2 Supported hardware
Model Processor CPU Architecture
Londelec LEIODC-X32 Freescale i.MX287 ARM926EJ-S (32bit)
Advantech ARK-2120F Intel Atom D2550 x64 (64bit)
Advantech ARK-3360F Intel Atom N450 x64 (64bit)
Advantech UNO-1172AH Intel Atom D510 x64 (64bit)
Advantech UNO-1372G-J Intel Celeron J1900 x64 (64bit)
Advantech UNO-2484G Intel Core i3-6100U x64 (64bit)
Advantech ARK-3202F Intel Atom N270 x86 (32bit)
Advantech UNO-1150G AMD Geode LX800 x86 (32bit)

2. System configuration

Configuration file leandc.xml

XML configuration file leandc.xml contains main settings of the leandc application and it is the first file loaded on startup. The name of the file is fixed and it must be stored in the default application directory /home/leandc/app . If leandc.xml file is not found on startup, application terminates with an error message indicating the cause.

leandc.xml configuration file consists of a root node MainConfig which has 3 mandatory groups VersionControl; HardwareCfg and CommunicationCfg and 4 optional groups TraceCfg; ClientFilterCfg; SupervisionCfg and InternalCfg, please see the sample below.

<MainConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/main" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4.00" date="2022-05-31" time="10:08:09"/>
  <HardwareCfg>
    <UART Index="1" COM="1" Baudrate="9600" DataBits="8" Parity="E" … />
           …
  </HardwareCfg>
  <CommunicationCfg>
    <IEC101ma Index="10" HWIndex="100" XMLpath="IEC101ma_test.xml" LinkAddr="1"/>
           …
  </CommunicationCfg>
  <TraceCfg>
    <SYSLOGFILE LogFlags="0x00" Mode="0" HourLimit="0" Logfile="Syslog/syslog"/>
           …
  </TraceCfg>
  <ClientFilterCfg>
    <IPv4 FilterID="1" ClientIPaddr="10.19.0.21" Mask="32"/>
           …
  </ClientFilterCfg>
  <SupervisionCfg>
    <MONRAW SrcHWIndex="11" DstHWIndex="10" SrvHWIndex="9"/>
           …
  </SupervisionCfg>
  <InternalCfg>
    <PLC Index="99" XMLpath="myplc.xml"/>
  </InternalCfg>
</MainConfig>

HardwareCfg group

HardwareCfg group contains definitions of physical interfaces such as serial ports and network sockets. The following elements are available to define physical interfaces (e.g. Serial ports) or sockets (e.g. TCP server) required for communication: UART; TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT and UDP. Attributes of these elements contain interface’s settings. HardwareCfg group can have multiple child elements as shown in the sample below.

<HardwareCfg>
     <UART Index="1" Devpath="/dev/ttyUSB0" Baudrate="9600" … />
     <UART Index="2" Devpath="/dev/ttyUSB1" Baudrate="9600" … />
     <TCPSERVER Index="33" ServerIPaddr="127.0.0.1" Port="2404" … />
     <TCPCLIENT Index="44" ServerIPaddr="127.0.0.1" Port="2404" … />
     <UDP Index="55" RemoteIPaddr="127.0.0.1" RemotePort="64950" … />
</HardwareCfg>

Important

There must be one and only one HardwareCfg group in the root node MainConfig.
Hardware interfaces defined in the HardwareCfg group must be arranged in the following order:
UART
TCPSERVER
TCPCLIENT
UDP

UART

This node contains settings of a serial port. Please see sample UART node and all its attributes in the table below.

<UART Index="1" COM="3" Devpath="/dev/ttyUSB0" Baudrate="9600" DataBits="8" Parity="E" StopBits="1" Timeout="3" TxDelay="0.5" MaxTxDelay="4" MaxStations="5" Interface="RS232" CtrlRdTimer="0.5" Watchdog="0" Test="Echo" Name="COM1"/>
Table 2.1 UART attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the hardware node. It is used as a reference to link a communication protocol instance to this node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.

COM

*

 0…16 n/a Serial port number. Number of the inbuilt serial port when running leandc application on a supported hardware. Please refer to Table 2.2 below for a list of currently supported hardwares. If you are running leandc application on a hardware that is not supported or want to use a serial port other than inbuilt (e.g. USB to Serial adapter), please use COM=”0” and specify path of the UART device in Devpath attribute. Devpath attribute has higher priority and value of COM will be ignored if Devpath is used.
Devpath Max 100 chars n/a Path of the UART device in the Linux Operating System. All serial ports can normally be found in ‘/dev’ directory. On standard hardwares inbuilt serial ports have names ‘/dev/ttyS0’; ‘/dev/ttyS1’ and USB to Serial adapter ports ‘/dev/ttyUSB0’; ‘/dev/ttyUSB0’; etc Attribute is case sensitive, observe the case of path when specifying. Attribute is optional, path of the UART device will be resolved automatically from COM number, if omitted.
Baudrate 300…115200bps 115200 UART baudrate, currently supported values 300; 600; 1200; 2400; 4800; 9600; 19200; 38400; 57600 and 115200 bits per second.
DataBits 7 or 8 8 bits UART data bit count 7 or 8. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Parity N; E or O Even UART parity, currently supported N = None; E = Even; O = Odd
StopBits 1 or 2 1 bit UART stop bit count 1 or 2. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Timeout 0.01…42949 n/a
Receive timeout in seconds. Functionality depends on the linked communication protocol instance:
> Serial Master instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101/3, Modbus, Spabus) - new outgoing message will be sent if no reply is received from outstation within a configured number of seconds.
> Serial Slave instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) - incoming message will be discarded if not all bytes have been received within a configured number of seconds.
TxDelay 0.00001…42949 n/a Transmit delay in seconds. Time interval in seconds between received and sent message. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be calculated based on a configured baudrate. The default value is calculated as ‘TxDelay = 44 / baudrate’ e.g. for a baudrate of 9600 the TxDelay is 4.583msec.
MaxTxDelay 0 or 0.1…42949 0 Dynamic (maximal) transmit delay in seconds. Time interval in seconds between received and sent message in case serial port is used to communicate to only one outstation. Transmit delay is automatically adjusted depending on a number of outstations being communicated to via the serial port. Disabled stations are excluded from dynamic transmit delay calculation. Default value 0 disables dynamic transmit delay feature and TxDelay value is used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, TxDelay value value will be used if omitted.
MaxStations 1…64 8 Maximal number of stations for a dynamic transmit delay. If a number of outstations exceed the configured value, automatic transmit delay adjustment is disabled and TxDelay value is used. Disabled stations are excluded from dynamic transmit delay calculation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Interface
RS232
RS485
RS422
 RS232 Type of physical interface. Only applies if hardware supports UART interface selection by software. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value RS232 will be used if omitted.
CtrlRdTimer 0 or 0.00001…42949 0 sec UART control line (e.g. DSR, RI pin) reading interval in seconds. UART control lines must be stable for at least 8 consequtive read cycles at a configured interval before state change is reported. Default value 0 disables UART control line reading. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Watchdog 0 or 5…65535 0 min UART watchdog timer in minutes. System will reboot if this UART hasn’t received anything within a configured number of minutes. Default value 0 disables watchdog. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Test Echo n/a Attribute enables port testing mode. UART will echo any data received if this attribute is used. There is no need to disable communication protocol or supervision instances linked to UART when testing. Any testing data received will also be recorded to a communication logfile, if logging is enabled for this hardware node. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

* Supported hardwares on which COM attribute can be used are listed in the Table 2.2 below:

Table 2.2 Supported hardwares and serial port numbers
Hardware COM = 1 COM = 2 COM = 3 COM = 4 COM = 5 COM = 6 COM = 7 COM = 8
UNO-1150G (LEANDC-2/3(4)) /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyAP0 /dev/ttyAP1 /dev/ttyS1 (LEANDC-2/4 only) n/a n/a n/a n/a
ARK-3202F (LEANDC-2/5) /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyS1 variable variable variable n/a n/a n/a
LEIODC-x /dev/ttyAPP0 /dev/ttyAPP1 /dev/ttyAPP2 /dev/ttyAPP3 (internal) n/a n/a n/a n/a
ARK-2120F (LEANDC-3/6) /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyS1 variable variable variable variable n/a n/a
ARK-3360F /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyS1 variable variable variable variable n/a n/a
UNO-2484F (LEANDC-4/8) /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyS1 /dev/ttyS2 /dev/ttyS3 /dev/ttyS4 /dev/ttyS5 /dev/ttyS6 /dev/ttyS7
UNO-1372G (LEANDC-4/4) /dev/ttyS0 /dev/ttyS1 /dev/ttyS2 /dev/ttyS4 n/a n/a n/a n/a

TCPSERVER

This node contains settings of a TCP server socket. TCP server socket is used to accept connections from remote hosts. Please see sample TCPSERVER node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TCPSERVER Index="1" ServerIPaddr="127.0.0.1" Port="2404" Timeout="2" TxDelay="0.1" IdleTimeout="10" Name="LAN1"/>
Table 2.3 TCPSERVER attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the hardware node. It is used as a reference to link a communication protocol instance to this node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
ServerIPaddr 0.0.0.0 … 255.255.255.254 0.0.0.0
Server IPv4 address. Ethernet interface with this IP address must exist in the Operating System. Remote TCP clients will be able to connect only through Ethernet interface with this address.
IP address 0.0.0.0 can be used to bind a TCPSERVER socket to any interface available in the Operating System. This will allow TCP clients to connect through any Ethernet interface.
Port 1…65534 n/a TCP port number. Unlimited number of incoming TCP connection requests will be accepted on this port as long as there is a communication protocol or supervision instance available to handle the new connection. (default port for IEC60870-5-104 is 2404)
Timeout 0.01…42949 2 sec
Receive timeout in seconds. Functionality depends on the linked communication protocol instance:
> Serial Master instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101/3, Modbus, Spabus) - new outgoing message will be sent if no reply is received from outstation within a configured number of seconds.
> Serial Slave instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) - incoming message will be discarded if not all bytes (possibly arriving in multiple TCP segments) have been received within a configured number of seconds.
> IEC61850 instance - connection will be closed if not all TCP segments of a TPKT message have been received within a configured number of seconds.
> Not used for any other communication protocol instances.
Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TxDelay 0.00001…42949 0.1 sec Transmit delay in seconds, only used if a serial communication instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) is linked. Time interval in seconds between received and sent message. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
IdleTimeout 5…232 - 1 120 sec Receive idle timeout, only used if a serial communication instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) or supervision instance is linked. TCP socket will be closed if no data is received from the remote host within a configured number of seconds. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

TCPCLIENT

This node contains settings of a TCP client socket. TCP client socket is used to connect to a remote host. Please see sample TCPCLIENT node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TCPCLIENT Index="1" ServerIPaddr="127.0.0.1" Port="2404" ConnectTimeout="5" Timeout="2" TxDelay="0.1" IdleTimeout="10" Keepalive="20" Name="LAN1"/>
Table 2.4 TCPCLIENT attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the hardware node. It is used as a reference to link a communication protocol instance to this node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
ServerIPaddr 0.0.0.0 … 255.255.255.254 127.0.0.1 test only Server IPv4 address. TCP connection will established to this remote address. (default localhost address 127.0.0.1 - for testing purposes only)
Port 1…65534 n/a TCP port number. TCP connection will be established to this remote port. (default port for IEC60870-5-104 is 2404)
ConnectTimeout 1…232 - 1 5 sec TCP socket reconnection timeout in seconds. Connection request (SYN) message will be sent after this timeout which starts when existing connection fails. If it is impossible to connect to a remote Server, connection request (SYN) messages will be sent at these intervals. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Timeout 0.01…42949 2 sec
Receive timeout in seconds. Functionality depends on the linked communication protocol instance:
> Serial Master instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101/3, Modbus, Spabus) - new outgoing message will be sent if no reply is received from outstation within a configured number of seconds.
> Serial Slave instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) - incoming message will be discarded if not all bytes (possibly arriving in multiple TCP segments) have been received within a configured number of seconds.
> IEC61850 Client instance - connection will be closed if not all TCP segments of a TPKT message have been received within a configured number of seconds.
> Not used for any other communication protocol instances.
Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TxDelay 0.00001…42949 0.1 sec Transmit delay in seconds, only used if a serial communication instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) is linked. Time interval in seconds between received and sent message. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
IdleTimeout 5…232 - 1 120 sec Receive idle timeout, only used if a serial communication instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) or supervision instance is linked. TCP socket will be closed if no data is received from the remote host within a configured number of seconds. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Keepalive 0…232 - 1 0 sec Keepalive message seding interval normally used for IEC61850 Client instance. TCP Socket will be closed if the remote host fails to reply to a keepalive message within configured number of seconds. (default is 20 seconds for IEC61850 Client instance) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

UDP

This node contains settings of a UDP socket. UDP is used to send/receive packets to/from remote host without establishing a connection between the source and the destination. Please see sample UDP node and all its attributes in the table below.

<UDP Index="1" RemoteIPaddr="127.0.0.1" RemotePort="64950" LocalIPaddr="0.0.0.0" LocalPort="64950" ConnectTimeout="5" Timeout="2" TxDelay="0.1" IdleTimeout="10" Name="LAN1"/>
Table 2.5 UDP attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the hardware node. It is used as a reference to link a communication protocol instance to this node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
RemoteIPaddr 0.0.0.0 … 255.255.255.254 127.0.0.1 test only Remote IPv4 address. UDP messages will be sent to this remote address. (default localhost address 127.0.0.1 - for testing purposes only)
RemotePort 1…65534 n/a Remote UDP port number. UDP messages will be sent to this remote port. (default port for supervision instances is 64950)
LocalIPaddr 0.0.0.0 … 255.255.255.254 0.0.0.0
Local IPv4 address. Ethernet interface with this IP address must exist in the Operating System. UDP messages will be received only through Ethernet interface with this address.
IP address 0.0.0.0 can be used to listen for UDP messages on any interface available in the Operating System. This allows leandc application to receive UDP messages through any Ethernet interface. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
LocalPort 1…65534 same as RemotePort Local UDP port number. UDP messages will be accepted on this port. (default port number is equal to the RemotePort) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
ConnectTimeout 1…232 - 1 5 sec Reconnection timeout in seconds. Communication will be suspended for a configured number of seconds if last sent UDP message was rejected. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Timeout 0.01…42949 2 sec
Receive timeout in seconds. Functionality depends on the linked communication protocol instance:
> Serial Master instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101/3, Modbus, Spabus) - new outgoing message will be sent if no reply is received from outstation within a configured number of seconds.
> Serial Slave instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) - incoming message will be discarded if not all bytes (possibly arriving in multiple UDP datagrams) have been received within a configured number of seconds.
> Not used for any other communication protocol instances.
Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TxDelay 0.00001…42949 0.1 sec Transmit delay in seconds, only used if a serial communication instance (e.g. IEC60870-5-101) is linked. Time interval in seconds between received and sent message. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
IdleTimeout 5…232 - 1 120 sec Receive idle timeout, only used if OVERRIDE supervision instance is linked. TCP socket used for service commands will be closed if no data is received from a remote host within a configured number of seconds. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

CommunicationCfg group

CommunicationCfg group is used to initialize communication protocol instances and link them to physical hardware interfaces. leandc application is able to receive data from downstream outstations using various communication protocols, process the received information and report it upstream to SCADA our any other data acquisition entity. Every logical communication link to outstation or upstream station has a definition ‘communication protocol instance’ within this manual. It represents communication channel for receiving or sending the data. Communication protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group, please refer to the sample below containing 4 different communication protocols (instances).

<CommunicationCfg>
     <IEC101ma Index="10" HWIndex="2" XMLpath="IEC101ma_test.xml" CommsFlags="0x10"/>
     <IEC101sl Index="5" HWIndex="1" XMLpath="IEC101sl_test.xml"/>
     <IEC104sl Index="12" HWIndex="3" XMLpath="IEC104ma_test.xml" FilterID="2"/>
     <IEC104Rsl Index="13" HWIndex="3" RedundantToIndex="12" FilterID="3"/>
</CommunicationCfg>

Important

There must be one and only one CommunicationCfg group in the root node MainConfig.
Communication protocol instances defined in the CommunicationCfg group must be arranged in the following order:
Modbusma
Spabusma
IEC61850cl
IEC101ma
IEC101sl
IEC103ma
IEC104ma
IEC104sl
IEC104Rsl
IEC104Csl

Every communication protocol instance has a unique element and settings are described in the following sections.

Modbusma

General settings of the Modbus Master communication protocol instance. Please see sample Modbusma node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Modbusma Index="10" HWIndex="2" XMLpath="BCDI16_test.xml" Address="5" CommsFlags="0x80" Name="IO device"/>
Table 2.6 Modbusma instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the communication protocol instance. It is used to reference protocol instance from other configuration files e.g. IO object tables (please see DI.Device; AI.Device; DO.Device; AO.Device attributes of the Slave protocol instance). Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link the communication protocol instance to a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index; TCPSERVER.Index; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the protocol instance. Multiple Modbusma instances can share the same hardware node.
XMLpath Max 100 chars XML configuration file name and path. This file contains IO object table and communication protocol settings. Path may be omitted if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying. The same XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances if the settings and IO object tables are identical.
Address 0…247 or 255 Device address of outstation. The range of addresses for Modbus RTU/ASCII stations is 1…247. Address 255 can be used only for Modbus TCP station that doesn’t have a device address (also known as Unit Identifier in the context of Modbus TCP). Address 0 is Broadcast address and can’t be used for Modbus RTU/ASCII stations. However address 0 can be used for Modbus TCP station.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Settings specific to the communication protocol and IO object tables are defined in a separate XML file specified in XMLpath attribute. Contents of this XML file are described in the section Modbus Master.

Spabusma

General settings of the Spabus Master communication protocol instance. Please see sample Spabusma node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Spabusma Index="10" HWIndex="2" XMLpath="IED1.xml" Address="5" CommsFlags="0x80" Name="Protection IED"/>
Table 2.7 Spabusma instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the communication protocol instance. It is used to reference protocol instance from other configuration files e.g. IO object tables (please see DI.Device; AI.Device; DO.Device; AO.Device attributes of the Slave protocol instance). Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link the communication protocol instance to a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the protocol instance. Multiple Spabusma instances can share the same hardware node.
XMLpath Max 100 chars XML configuration file name and path. This file contains IO object table and communication protocol settings. Path may be omitted if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying. The same XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances if the settings and IO object tables are identical.
Address 1…899 SPA device address. Address of the connected SPA Slave station (e.g. IED) must be the same.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Settings specific to the communication protocol and IO object tables are defined in a separate XML file specified in XMLpath attribute. Contents of this XML file are described in the section Spabus Master.

IEC61850cl

General settings of the IEC61850 client communication protocol instance. Please see sample IEC61850cl node and all its attributes in the table below.

<IEC61850cl Index="20" HWIndex="2" XMLpath="REF_IO.xml" SCLpath="REF.cid" IEDname="IED1" CommsFlags="0x10" Name="IED"/>
Table 2.8 IEC61850cl instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the communication protocol instance. It is used to reference protocol instance from other configuration files e.g. IO object tables (please see DI.Device; AI.Device; DO.Device; AO.Device attributes of the Slave protocol instance). Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link the communication protocol instance to a hardware node. Use value of the TCPCLIENT.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the protocol instance.
XMLpath Max 100 chars XML configuration file name and path. This file contains IO object table and communication protocol settings. Path may be omitted if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying. The same XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances if the settings and IO object tables are identical.
SCLpath Max 100 chars IED CID or SCD file name and path. This file contains communication capabilites and settings of the IED. It is normaly exported from the IED configuration tool. Path may be omitted if the file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying.
IEDname Max 64 chars IED name as specified in the SCL file. Attribute is mandatory if SCL file contains more than one IED. Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the IED name when specifying.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Settings specific to the communication protocol and IO object tables are defined in a separate XML file specified in XMLpath attribute. Contents of this XML file are described in the section IEC61850 Client.

IEC101ma

General settings of the IEC60870-5-101 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Please see sample IEC101ma node and all its attributes in the table below.

<IEC101ma Index="10" HWIndex="2" XMLpath="IEC101ma_test.xml" LinkAddr="5" ASDUAddr="5" CommsFlags="0x80" Name="Radio Comms"/>
Table 2.9 IEC101ma instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the communication protocol instance. It is used to reference protocol instance from other configuration files e.g. IO object tables (please see DI.Device; AI.Device; DO.Device; AO.Device attributes of the Slave protocol instance). Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link the communication protocol instance to a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index; TCPSERVER.Index; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the protocol instance. Multiple IEC101ma instances can share the same hardware node.
XMLpath Max 100 chars XML configuration file name and path. This file contains IO object table and communication protocol settings. Path may be omitted if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying. The same XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances if the settings and IO object tables are identical.
LinkAddr 1…254 or 1…65534 Link layer address of the communication protocol instance. Address of the connected IEC60870-5-101 Slave station must be the same. Size of the link layer address may be 1 or 2 bytes as set by the LinkSettings.LinkAddrSize attribute. Please note value 255 (if link layer address size is 1 byte) or 65535 (if link layer address size is 2 bytes) is Broadcast address and can’t be used.
ASDUAddr 1…254 or 1…65534 Common address of ASDU (CAA). Connected IEC60870-5-101 Slave station may have 1 or more ASDUs. Multiple IEC101ma nodes must be created in case peer station has multiple ASDUs, one for each ASDU. All of these IEC101ma nodes will have the same LinkAddr and unique ASDUAddr. Size of the common ASDU address may be 1 or 2 bytes as set by the ASDUSettings.CAASize attribute. Please note value 255 (if ASDU address size is 1 byte) or 65535 (if ASDU address size is 2 bytes) is Broadcast address and can’t be used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the LinkAddr will be used if omitted.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Settings specific to the communication protocol and IO object tables are defined in a separate XML file specified in XMLpath attribute. Contents of this XML file are described in the section IEC60870-5-101 Master.

IEC104Rsl

There is an option to use multiple redundant connections for communication between leandc application and controlling (Master) stations ensuring a failure of a single communication channel will not disrupt the exchange of data. This option is currently available for IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) instances and can be enabled by creating a so-called redundancy group. Redundancy group is a set of communication protocol instances working together and allowing several controlling stations (Masters) to receive the same data over single/multiple communication channels. Only one controlling station (Master) within a redundancy group is in a ‘Started connection’ state which means only this station is sending/receiving data. Other controlling stations (Masters) are in a ‘Stopped connection’ state, they only monitor availability of the communication channel, but do not send/receive data.

In order to explain how to set up a redundancy group 2 terms ‘Main’ (IEC104sl) and ‘Redundant’ (IEC104Rsl) communication protocol instance are used throughout this manual. There is no functional difference between ‘Main’ and ‘Redundant’ communication protocol instance as far as the communication standard is concerned. These terms are only used to differentiate communication instances in leandc application configuration.

IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) redundancy group is enabled as follows: any IEC104sl communication protocol instance can be chosen as ‘Main’ and redundancy is automatically enabled if one or more IEC104Rsl instances are linked to the ‘Main’ instance. It is possible to link up to 15 ‘Redundant’ instances to the same ‘Main’ instance, thus creating a redundancy group of 16. This would allow up to 16 controlling (Master) stations to connect to leandc application.

No IO object tables are required for ‘Redundant’ communication protocol instance, because it is always linked to a ‘Main’ instance which has IO object tables. An identical set of IO objects is shared by all instances within a redundancy group. Please see sample IEC104Rsl node and all its attributes in the table below.

<IEC104Rsl Index="13" HWIndex="3" RedundantToIndex="12" FilterID="0" CommsFlags="0x80" Name="SCADA"/>
Table 2.14 IEC104Rsl instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the communication protocol instance. It is used to reference protocol instance from other configuration files e.g. logger configuration XML file. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link the communication protocol instance to a hardware node. Use value of the TCPSERVER.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the protocol instance. Multiple IEC104Rsl instances can share the same hardware node.
RedundantToIndex 1…254 Link ‘Redundant’ instance to ‘Main’ instance. Use value of the IEC104sl.Index attribute.
FilterID 1…255 Identifier of a predefined filter to allow only certain TCP client IP addresses to establish connection to this protocol instance. Please refer to the Table 2.20 for filter settings. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, clients from any IP address will be able to connect if attribute omitted.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Example redundancy group of 4 instances shown below. This will enable up to 4 controlling (Master) stations to connect.

<CommunicationCfg>
         <IEC104sl Index="12" HWIndex="3" XMLpath="IEC104ma_test.xml" Name="SCADA1"/>
         <IEC104Rsl Index="13" HWIndex="3" RedundantToIndex="12" Name="SCADA2"/>
         <IEC104Rsl Index="14" HWIndex="3" RedundantToIndex="12" Name="SCADA3"/>
         <IEC104Rsl Index="15" HWIndex="3" RedundantToIndex="12" Name="SCADA4"/>
</CommunicationCfg>

IEC104Csl

There is an option to clone IEC60870-5-104 stations which have multiple ASDUs, i.e. multiple IEC104sl nodes with the same StationID attributes and unique ASDUAddr attributes. Cloned IEC60870-5-104 station will have identical number of ASDUs and can be linked to different hardware node.

Please see sample IEC104Csl node and all its attributes in the table below.

<IEC104Csl Index="13" HWIndex="3" CloneFromIndex="12" StationID="5" FilterID="0" CommsFlags="0x80" Name="SCADA"/>
Table 2.15 IEC104Csl instance
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Base index of the first cloned node. If the source IEC60870-5-104 Slave station has multiple ASDUs, all of those will be cloned and indexes will be initialized sequentially. Remember to leave a gap for the sequence of indexes to be created automatically after base index value specified. Number of index values created will be the number ASDUs source IEC60870-5-104 Slave station has.
HWIndex 1…254 Hardware Index is used to link cloned communication protocol instance(s) to a hardware node. Use value of the TCPSERVER.Index attribute as a hardware index in order to link the cloned protocol instance(s). Multiple IEC104Csl instances can share the same hardware node.
CloneFromIndex 1…254 Source IEC104sl node to be cloned. Use value of the IEC104sl.Index attribute.
StationID 1…254 Station identifier. It is possible to create more than 1 ASDU for our IEC60870-5-104 Slave station. Multiple IEC104sl nodes must be created in this case, one for each ASDU. All of those IEC104sl nodes will have the same StationID and unique ASDUAddr. If the IEC60870-5-104 Slave station with multiple ASDUs is being cloned, new identifier can be specified in this attribute. Station identifier is unique per hardware node so it is possible to have multiple stations with the same StationID as long as they are linked to different hardware nodes. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, cloned station will create its own unique station identifier if attribute omitted.
FilterID 1…255 Identifier of a predefined filter to allow only certain TCP client IP addresses to establish connection to this protocol instance. Please refer to the Table 2.20 for filter settings. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, clients from any IP address will be able to connect if attribute omitted.
CommsFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Initialization settings of the protocol instance. See Table 2.16 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default system settings will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

CommsFlags attribute

Communication flags contain initialization settings of communication protocol instances. For example, outstation polling can be permanently disabled on leandc startup and enabled by user manually issuing a service command.

Table 2.16 Communication Flags attribute
Bits Value Description
CommsFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Communication initialization flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Reject new incoming connection to our TCP server socket if a remote TCP client is already connected (default value).
xxxx.1xxx Always accept new incoming connection to our TCP server socket. This means terminating an exisiting ongoing connection in order to accept the new connection request.
Bit 4* xxx0.xxxx Protocol instance starts data exchange on leandc startup (default value)
xxx1.xxxx Protocol instance doesn’t start data exchange on leandc startup. Data exchange will not start automatically, service command (DO.Index=”-4”) can be used to start data exchange at any time. Please see Table 5.13 for more information on service commands.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Protocol instance is enabled on leandc startup. Communication will start automatically (default value)
1xxx.xxxx Protocol instance is disabled on leandc startup. Commnication will not start automatically, service command (DO.Index=”-3”) can be used to enable communication at any time. Please see Table 5.13 for more information on service commands.
Bits 0…2;5;6 Any Bits reserved for future use

Tip

* This bit only applies to the following protocol instances and is used after TCP connection to the station is established:
IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) sends or doesn’t send [STARTDT_act] automatically to the outstation on leandc startup;
IEC61850 Client sends or doesn’t send Association Request to the IED on leandc startup;

TraceCfg group

Generic diagnostic information and error messages can be recorded to a system logfile. TraceCfg group and its child element SYSLOGFILE contains settings to enable the system-wide logfile. Settings contains common settings that apply to all logfiles. TraceCfg may contain only one SYSLOGFILE and one Settings element as shown in the sample below.

<TraceCfg>
     <SYSLOGFILE LogFlags="0" Logfile="Syslog/syslog" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC"/>
     <Settings CleanOlder="60" MinFreespace="5.5"/>
</TraceCfg>

SYSLOGFILE

This element contains settings of a system-wide logfile. Please see sample SYSLOGFILE node and all its attributes in the table below.

<SYSLOGFILE LogFlags="0" Logfile="Syslog/syslog" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC"/>
Table 2.17 SYSLOGFILE attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Select type of system messages to be logged. See Table 2.18 for description. Logfile will not be created if the value is 0.
Logfile Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.log’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.log’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (default value ‘Syslog/syslog’ where ‘Syslog’ is the name of the directory and ‘syslog’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Logfile initialization settings. See Table 14.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0…12 0 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 0 – only 1 logfile a day will be created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of the recorded information based on the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

Tip

* There are few samples on how files are created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings in section Logfile samples.

Table 2.18 System logfile flags
Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported Logfile will not be created if the value is 0.
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Error message recording to logfile disabled
xxxx.xxx1 Error message recording to logfile enabled
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Warning message recording to logfile disabled
xxxx.xx1x Warning message recording to logfile enabled
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Information message recording to logfile disabled
xxxx.x1xx Information message recording to logfile enabled
Bits 3…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Settings

This element contains common settings that apply to all logfiles. Please see sample Settings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Settings CleanOlder="60" MinFreespace="5.5"/>
Table 2.19 Log Settings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
CleanOlder 0…255 60 days Remove logfiles which are older than specified number of days. Value 0 disables automatic cleanup functionality. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
MinFreespace 0…100 2% Minimal hard drive free space required to record logfiles in percent. Logfiles will not be recoreded if available space is less than specified percentage. Value 0 disables free space checking and logfiles are recorded until hard drive is full. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

ClientFilterCfg group

ClientFilterCfg group and its child element IPv4 are used to create filters for remote ‘Client’ IP address which are allowed to connect to our TCP Server sockets. Please see sample IPv4 node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ClientFilterCfg>
     <IPv4 FilterID="1" ClientIPaddr="192.168.2.14" Mask="32" Name="Only specified IP address"/>
     <IPv4 FilterID="1" ClientIPaddr="192.168.2.55" Mask="32" Name="Only specified IP address"/>
     <IPv4 FilterID="2" ClientIPaddr="192.168.5.0" Mask="24" Name="IP address range"/>
</ClientFilterCfg>

There are 3 IPv4 filters configured in the example above. Please note 2 IPv4 nodes have the same filter identifier “1”. This will allow clients from either IP address 192.168.2.14 or 192.168.2.55 to connect.

Table 2.20 IPv4 Client filter attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
FilterID 1…255 n/a Filter identifier. More than one filter may have the same identifier which enables to define multiple addresses or address ranges. In order to apply the filter, use this identifier in communication protocol instance attributes IEC104sl.FilterID; IEC104Rsl.FilterID or IEC104Csl.FilterID.
ClientIPaddr 0.0.0.0 … 255.255.255.255 n/a IPv4 TCP client IP address allowed to connect. It is possible to define a network subnet and all IP addresses of the subnet will be able to connect. Please refer to Mask attribute for network subnet configuration. (address 0.0.0.0 can be used to allow connection from any IP address)
Mask 0…32 32 Network mask is used in conjunction with ClientIPaddr attribute in order to create a network subnet. All IP addresses of the subnet will be able to connect. Network mask attribute is a decimal notation of the subnet mask, sometimes called network prefix, refer to Table 2.21 for more information. (Mask 0 will allow connection from any IP address; mask 32 will allow connection only from one IP address specified in ClientIPaddr attribute)
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Network subnets created by various Mask attribute values are summarized in the table below. It is assumed user has a good understanding of network addressing fundamentals. Please refer to external sources (e.g. http://www.subnet-calculator.com) for additional information on network addressing and subnet definition.

IP address Subnet Mask Network Address Broadcast Address

Error message Binary Subnet Mask

Table columns are defined as follows:
Column 1 contains Mask attribute values;
Column 2 contains subnet mask in dotted decimal notation;
Columns 3…6 show network mask in binary notation (just for reference);
Column 7 contains range of client IP address allowed to connect.

Table is designed as a guidance of how network subnets are created based on sample IP address 192.168.1.1 specified in the ClientIPaddr attribute.

3 224.0.0.0 1110 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 192.0.0.0 to 223.255.255.255
…
24 255.255.255.0 1111 1111 1111 1111 1111 1111 0000 0000 192.168.1.0 to 192.168.1.255
