SupervisionCfg group

SupervisionCfg group is used to enable real-time monitoring of the serial port or socket traffic and also provides serial server functionality. Real-time traffic monitoring and serial server functionality has designated supervision instances which are configured under SupervisionCfg group, please refer to the sample below containing 4 different supervision instances.

<SupervisionCfg>
  <MONRAW SrcHWIndex="1" DstHWIndex="51" Name="Raw monitoring instance"/>
  <MONCOMP SrcHWIndex="2" DstHWIndex="52" SrvHWIndex="53" Name="Compatible mon instance"/>
  <REDIRECT SrcHWIndex="4" DstHWIndex="61" Name="UART redirect instance"/>
  <OVERRIDE SrcHWIndex="3" DstHWIndex="62" SrvHWIndex="63" Name="UART override instance"/>
</SupervisionCfg>

Every supervision instance has a unique element and its configuration is described in the following sections.

Important

Supervision instances must be listed under SupervisionCfg group in the following order:
MONRAW
MONCOMP
REDIRECT
OVERRIDE

MONRAW

Traffic through any serial port can be captured and sent to a remote destination for a real time monitoring. Remote traffic monitoring can be enabled using so called ‘raw monitoring’ supervision instance which requires only 1 destination socket to send the captured data. Raw monitoring mode will be active as long as there is a traffic through the monitored port and remote destination is reachable. Please see sample MONRAW element all available attributes below.

<MONRAW SrcHWIndex="1" DstHWIndex="51" Name="Raw monitoring instance"/>
Table 2.22 MONRAW attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1…254 Source index of the serial port to be monitored. Any UART node can be used as a source for traffic monitoring. Please note serial port must not be linked to any other SupervisionCfg node.
DstHWIndex 1…254 Destination index of the hardware node to send captured traffic. Any of TCPSERVER or UDP nodes can be used to send captured traffic as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

UDP socket is recommended as a destination for sending the captured traffic.
Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950.

MONCOMP

Traffic through any serial port can be captured and sent to a remote destination for a real time monitoring. Remote traffic monitoring can be enabled using so called ‘compatible monitoring’ supervision instance which requires 2 sockets for its operation. The 1st socket is destination to send the captured data and the 2nd socket is used for service commands. Captured data will be sent only if both remote sockets are active/reachable. This mode is compatible with Moxa serial server driver, please refer to the latest NPort_installation manual for more information. Please see sample MONCOMP element and all available attributes below.

<MONCOMP SrcHWIndex="2" DstHWIndex="52" SrvHWIndex="53" Name="Compatible monitoring instance"/>
Table 2.23 MONCOMP attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1…254 Source index of the serial port node to be monitored. Any UART node can be used as a source for traffic monitoring. Please note serial port must not be linked to any other SupervisionCfg node.
DstHWIndex 1…254 Destination index of the hardware node to send captured traffic. Any of TCPSERVER or UDP nodes can be used to send the captured traffic as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
SrvHWIndex 1…254 Index of the hardware node for receiving service commands. Any of TCPSERVER nodes can be used as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout attribute will be used to check activity of the service socket. The service TCPSERVER socket will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds and also the destination socket is disconnected/unreachable.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950 and service node (SrvHWIndex) is 64966.

REDIRECT

Serial server functionality allows to send data from one serial port to another over the network transparently as if these serial ports where connected together with a direct cable. In order to permanently enable serial server functionality so called REDIRECT supervision instance can be used. It requires only 1 destination socket to send the redirected data. Serial data will be redirected as long as remote destination is reachable. Please see sample REDIRECT element and all available attributes below.

<REDIRECT SrcHWIndex="4" DstHWIndex="61" SrvHWIndex="53" Name="UART redirect"/>
Table 2.24 REDIRECT attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1…254 Index of the UART node to be redirected. Data received through this serial port will be redirected to a destination hardware node and data received from a destination hardware node will be redirected to this serial port. No communication protocol instances must be linked to UART node in order to use it for redirection. Also serial port must not be linked to any other SupervisionCfg node.
DstHWIndex 1…254 Destination index of the hardware node to redirect the data. Any of TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as destination. Data received from a destination hardware node will be redirected to the serial port.
SrvHWIndex 1…254 Index of the hardware node for receiving service commands. Any of TCPSERVER nodes can be used as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout and TCPCLIENT.IdleTimeout attributes will be used to check activity of the destination socket. The destination TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds. This means there has to be an ongoing communication to prevent TCP sockets from being automatically disconnected. This doesn’t apply to UDP socket.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950.

OVERRIDE

Serial server functionality allows to send data from one serial port to another over the network transparently as if these serial ports where connected together with a direct cable. OVERRIDE instance provides an option to temporary override normal operation of the serial port and enable serial server functionality that allows to send data from a remote host over the network to this serial port. It becomes useful in situations where serial server functionality is required only for a short period of time and serial port has to be returned to a normal operation when it is no longer needed. This can be used to e.g. poll or configure any serial device and automatically resume normal operation afterwards. OVERRIDE supervision instance requires 2 sockets for operation. The 1st socket is a destination for the redirected serial data and the 2nd socket is used for service commands. Serial server functionality will be automatically enabled only if both sockets are active/reachable. This mode is compatible with Moxa serial server driver, please refer to the latest NPort_installation manual for more information. Please see sample OVERRIDE element and all available attributes below.

<OVERRIDE SrcHWIndex="3" DstHWIndex="62" SrvHWIndex="63" Name="UART override (temporary)"/>
Table 2.25 OVERRIDE attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
SrcHWIndex 1…254 Index of the UART node to be temporarily overridden. Data received through this serial port will be temporarily redirected to a destination hardware node and data received from a destination hardware node will be temporarily redirected to this serial port. Please note serial port must not be linked to any other SupervisionCfg node.
DstHWIndex 1…254 Destination index of the hardware node to temporarily redirect the serial port data. Any of TCPSERVER; TCPCLIENT or UDP nodes can be used as destination. Data received from a destination hardware node will be temporarily redirected to the serial port.
SrvHWIndex 1…254 Index of the hardware node for receiving service commands. Any of TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT nodes can be used as long as the hardware node is not linked to a communication protocol instance.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Please note TCPSERVER.IdleTimeout and TCPCLIENT.IdleTimeout attributes will be used to check activity of both destination and service sockets. The destination and service TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a configured number of seconds. Also the service TCPSERVER or TCPCLIENT sockets will be disconnected if no data is received within a number of seconds configured in the destination socket UDP.IdleTimeout attribute. This means there has to be an ongoing communication to prevent TCP sockets from being automatically disconnected.

Tip

Default TCP/UDP port for destination node (DstHWIndex) is 64950 and service node (SrvHWIndex) is 64966.

InternalCfg group

InternalCfg group is used to enable internal data processing. This includes performing logic operations such as ‘OR’ and ‘AND’ - a simplified PLC functionality. At the moment InternalCfg group can have only one element PLC and its configuration is described in the following section. More elements will be added in the future. Please refer to the sample below containing a PLC instance.

<InternalCfg>
  <PLC Index="99" XMLpath="myplc.xml"/>
</InternalCfg>

Important

Only one PLC element can be defined in InternalCfg group.

PLC

Internal data processing and basic PLC functionality is provided by PLC instance. This allows to perform logic operations such as ‘OR’ and ‘AND’ on the received data values.

Please see sample PLC node and all its attributes in the table below.

<PLC Index="99" XMLpath="myplc.xml" Name="PLC instance"/>
Table 2.26 PLC attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 1…254 Index is a unique identifier of the PLC instance. It is used to reference data points defined in the PLC instance from other configuration files e.g. IO object tables (please see DI.Device; AI.Device; DO.Device; AO.Device attributes of the Slave protocol instance). Make sure the selected value doesn’t overlap with communication protocol instance indexes.
XMLpath Max 100 chars XML configuration file name and path. This file contains PLC data point table and other settings. Path may be omitted if the XML file is stored in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and file name when specifying.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

PLC data point tables are defined in a separate XML file specified in XMLpath attribute. Contents of this XML file are described in the section Internal PLC.

3. IEC60870-5-101 Slave

This section contains details on how to configure IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) instance must have XML configuration file where IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. This may be useful if identical set of IO objects need to be reported to several Master stations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC101sl_test.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC101sl.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC101sl_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-101 Slave configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC101sl_test.xml’) must have a root node IEC101slConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
5 optional IO object groups AutoCfg; DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC101slConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC101sl" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4" date="2022-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
           …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <AutoCfg>
    <AUTO Source="1" Name="RTU1"/>
           …
  </AutoCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10"/>
           …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="10" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0"/>
           …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
           …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
           …
  </AOTable>
</IEC101slConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table. They are identical for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances. IO object table can be created manually by populating these groups or AutoCfg group can be used to automatically include all IO objects of the source communication instance.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-101 controlled station (Slave) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <XMLSettings … />
  <LinkSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <ASDUSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Periodic … />
  <BufferSizes … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 3.1 IEC60870-5-101 Slave XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings LinkAddrSize="1" ClassIgnore="0" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 3.2 IEC60870-5-101 Slave LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
LinkAddrSize 1 or 2 1 byte Link layer address size in bytes. Please note link address size of the protocol instances sharing the same hardware node must be the same.
ClassIgnore 0 0 Class of the received message is being used to determine either Class 1 or Class 2 data should be sent.
1 Class of the received message is ignored, Class 1 and Class 2 data is sent regardless of the requested Class. Please note this functionality is deviation from communication standard and should be avoided.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 3.3 for description.
Table 3.3 IEC60870-5-101 Slave Link flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Link flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send variable and fixed length link layer messages as required (First byte of the variable link layer message is - 0x68 and fixed length message - 0x10).
xxxx.xxx1 Send only variable length link layer messages (First byte of the link layer message - 0x68).
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Don’t use single character ACK and NACK responses (0xE5 and 0xA2).
xxxx.xx1x Use single character ACK and NACK responses (0xE5 and 0xA2).
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx [FCB] bit (link control field) must be zero in ‘Status of Link’ request received from Master station. We will not reply to the ‘Status of Link’ request if [FCB] bit is set.
xxxx.x1xx [FCB] bit (link control field) is ignored in ‘Status of Link’ request received from Master station.
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx [ACD] bit (link control field) in response messages is set only if Class 1 data is available.
xxxx.1xxx [ACD] bit (link control field) in response messages is always set.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx [ACD] bit (link control field) value of the ‘Status of Link’ response is 0 [no access demand]
xxx1.xxxx [ACD] bit (link control field) value of the ‘Status of Link’ response is 1 [access demand]
Bits 5…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" StartupGIDelay="10" />
Table 3.4 IEC60870-5-101 Slave CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 1…232 - 1 60 sec Delay in seconds before resetting the link if there is no request from Master station. Reset remote link message is required after communication loss exceeding configured offline delay in order to restart communication.
StartupGIDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Incoming General interrogation commands are rejected for a configured number of seconds on system startup. Negative confirmation will be sent to General Interrogation requests received before the delay expires. This delay allows us to poll data from outstations for the first time on startup, before data is sent to upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings COTSize="1" CAASize="1" IOASize="2" InvalidEvent="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" DIEventType="2" AIEventType="14" DOType="46" AOType="50" DOProc="2" AOProc="0" DIInterDelay="8000" DIIndetDelay="3500" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" TimeSync="1" TranspTypes="1" orCat="3" Flags="0x00" ForwardGI="1" />
Table 3.5 IEC60870-5-101 Slave ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
COTSize 1 or 2 1 byte Cause Of Transmission size in bytes including Originator address (default 1 byte - if originator address is not used)
CAASize 1 or 2 1 byte Common address of ASDU size in bytes
IOASize 1; 2 or 3 2 bytes Information Object Address size in bytes
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will not be set (‘0’). Time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages are adjusted based on a timezone selected for the current communication protocol instance. As it is impossible to distinguish between Standard time and Daylight Saving Time (DST) at the end of the DST (this is when clock is turned back one hour) all time-tags generated during the final hour of the DST are treated as Standard time. For example time-tag with 01:04:00 BST will be treated as 01:04:00 GMT. There is no issue at the begning of the DST (this is when clock is turned forward one hour).
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will be set (‘1’) if the time-tag contains Daylight Saving Time (DST) (Summer Time). It is also expected that the peer station sets Summer Time [SU] bit in all time-tags containing DST. If the peer station doesn’t set the [SU] bit it is assumed that all time-tags contain Standard time.
DIEventType See Table 5.3 2 [M_SP_TA_1] Use this ASDU type to send DI events which don’t have DI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 2 – ‘Single-point Information’, DI event will be sent using ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min)
AIEventType See Table 5.8 14 [M_ME_TC_1] Use this ASDU type to send AI events which don’t have AI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 14 – ‘Short floating point’, AI event will be sent using ASDU type 14 [M_ME_TC_1], CP24time2A, msec and min)
DOType See Table 5.12 0 = any Only accept command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Single or Double command) if DO object doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
AOType See Table 5.16 0 = any Only accept setpoint command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Normalized or Scaled setpoint) if AO object doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
DOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if DO object doesn’t have DO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
AOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if AO object doesn’t have AO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
DIInterDelay 0…232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.InterDelay attribute. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds)
DIIndetDelay 0…232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.IndetDelay attribute. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds)
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
TimeSync 0 0 Reject incoming clock synchronization messages.
1 Accept incoming clock synchronization messages and synchronize internal real time clock. Please note internal real time clock will be synchronized immediately if a time difference between received time stamp and the internal clock is greater than 1 hour. If a time difference is less than 1 hour, internal clock will be adjusted only once an hour.
TranspTypes 0 0 ASDU type of every DI/AI object is determined by XML configuration settings.
1 ASDU type of every DI/AI object will be made transparent whenever possible. The same ASDU type will be used to report DI/AI object to upstream station as received from downstream outstation, providing both source and destination communication protocol instances are compatible. Otherwise default ASDU type will be used. Please note the object will be excluded from General Interrogation response before it is received from downstream outstation on |leandcfw| startup. This is because it is impossible to determine ASDU type of the object before is has been received from outstation.
orCat 1…8 3 Originator category value for outgoing commands [IEC61850-7-3:2011]. Used only for commands sent to IEC61850 Client instances. Default value 3 = [remote-control]
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 3.6 for description.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
Table 3.6 IEC60870-5-101 Slave ASDU flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF ASDU flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use internal time when sending delayed INTER or INDET state event. This setting applies only to 2 Single Point object conversion to a Double Point. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event’s time tag will contain the current time i.e. the time when this event is generated.
xxxx.1xxx Use original time tag of the event that resulted in INTER or INDET state. This setting applies only to 2 Single Point object conversion to a Double Point. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event will contain original time tag of the event (received before the delay) that resulted in INTER/INDET state.
Bits 0…2;4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control quality flags of the DI/AI events generated when outstation goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings NotInitFlags="0x80" DisabledFlags="0x80" OfflineFlags="0x40" PostOfflineFlags="0x80" EventMask="0x00" />
Table 3.7 IEC60870-5-101 Slave ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NotInitFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. See Table 3.9 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires on |leandcfw| startup. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
DisabledFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station gets Disabled with a Service command. See Table 3.9 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station gets Disabled. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
OfflineFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station state changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires) See Table 3.9 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when OfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
PostOfflineFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers after PostOfflineDelay timer expires. See Table 3.9 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when PostOfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 3.8 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 3.8 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use
Table 3.9 DI/AI qualifier quality bits
Bits Value Description
Quality bits [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI/AI qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will not be set
xxx1.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will be set
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will not be set
xx1x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will be set
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will not be set
x1xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will be set
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will not be set
1xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will be set
Bits 0…3 xxxx.0000 Bits are used for Single/Double status information and Overflow [OV] indication. These will not be updated when communication status of the station changes.

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" CmdForward="10"/>
Table 3.10 IEC60870-5-101 Slave Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from the destination (e.g. downstream station) after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and negative response is sent to the upstream (Master) station. Application timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged if communication to the destination (e.g. downstream station) is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance attempts to send command response to the upstream (Master) station. If it is not possible to send a response within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). Command timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged if communication to upstream (Master) station is lost.
Select 1…232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, controlable object (DO/AO) is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.
CmdForward 0…232 - 1 10 sec Command forward timeout is a maximal delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits destination (Master protocol instance) to become available for accepting a new command. If destination protocol instance is in the process of executing previous command, it may not be able to accept new command before the previous command is complete. The new command fails within a configured number of seconds if it can’t be forwarded to the destination. This timeout allows control command queueing for a short period of time and ensures pending command is automatically purged if destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command. Value 0 disables command queueing and command fails instantly if the destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />

Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

BufferSizes

Communication and event buffer sizes can be specified in this node.

Please see sample BufferSizes node and all its attributes in the table below.

<BufferSizes DIEVmult="1.1" AIEVmult="2.1" ASDUTx="253" />
Table 3.13 IEC60870-5-101 Slave BufferSizes attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
DIEVmult 2…32 4 DI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of DI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of DI objects)
AIEVmult 2…32 4 AI event buffer size multiplier. Buffer size will be calculated by multiplying this attribute and the total number of AI objects linked to protocol instance. Attribute supports decimal point and thus values such as 2.5 or 4.66 may be entered (default value 4 – buffer size is initialized four times the number of AI objects)
ASDUTx 14…253 253 bytes Application layer transmission buffer size in bytes. Maximal length of message transmitted over IEC60870-5-101 communication link is 255 bytes. Including the link layer framing, maximal size of the application layer is 253 bytes (if LinkAddrSize is 1 byte) or 252 (if LinkAddrSize is 2 bytes). This attribute is used to limit maximal length of a transmitted message.

4. IEC60870-5-104 Slave

This section contains details on how to configure IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) instance must have XML configuration file where IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. This may be useful if identical set of IO objects need to be reported to several Master stations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC104sl_test.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC104sl.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC104sl_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-104 Slave configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC104sl_test.xml’) must have a root node IEC104slConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
5 optional IO object groups AutoCfg; DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC104slConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC104sl" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4" date="2022-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <AutoCfg>
    <AUTO Source="1" Name="RTU1"/>
        …
  </AutoCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="10" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</IEC104slConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table. They are identical for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances. IO object table can be created manually by populating these groups or AutoCfg group can be used to automatically include all IO objects of the source communication instance.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <XMLSettings … />
  <TransportSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <ASDUSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Periodic … />
  <BufferSizes … />
  <Miscellaneous … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 4.1 IEC60870-5-104 Slave XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

TransportSettings

Protocol transport interface settings such as timeout and message window sizes can be specified using attributes of TransportSettings element node.

Please see sample TransportSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TransportSettings T1="15" T2="10" T3="20" Kparam="12" Wparam="8" />
Table 4.2 IEC60870-5-104 Slave TransportSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
T1 1…65535 15 sec Timeout of send or test APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance waits a reply to a sent APDU [I-frame] or test message [TESTFR_act]. If no reply is received from peer station within a configured timeout, communication protocol instance initiates active close of the TCP socket.
T2 1…65535 10 sec Timeout for acknowledges in case of no data messages as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. (requirement: T2timer < T1timer) It is a delay in seconds before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame] in case there are any unacknowledged messages from the peer station.
T3 1…65535 20 sec Timeout for sending test messages in case of a long idle state from IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a maximal idle time in seconds before a test message [TESTFR_act] is sent to a peer station by the communication protocol instance. If this timeout is selected greater than T3 timeout configured in the peer station, it is most likely the test message will be sent by the peer station first.
Kparam 1…30 12 APDU Maximum difference receive sequence number to send state variable as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Maximal number of outgoing APDU messages [I-frame] communication protocol instance will send to a peer station before it waits for an acknowledge [S-frame]
Wparam 1…29 8 APDU Latest acknowledge after receiving w number I format APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Number of incoming APDU messages [I-frame] received from a peer station before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame]

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and the table listing all available attributes below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10" StartupGIDelay="10" />
Table 4.3 IEC60870-5-104 Slave CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before status of this protocol instance is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated after TCP socket has been closed. Default 0 seconds - station status will change to OFFLINE immediately after TCP socket has been closed by a remote host.
StartupGIDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Incoming General interrogation commands are rejected for a configured number of seconds on system startup. Negative confirmation will be sent to General Interrogation requests received before the delay expires. This delay allows us to poll data from outstations for the first time on startup, before data is sent to upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings InvalidEvent="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" DIEventType="31" AIEventType="36" DOType="46" AOType="50" DOProc="2" AOProc="0" DIInterDelay="8000" DIIndetDelay="3500" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" TimeSync="1" TranspTypes="1" orCat="3" Flags="0x00" ForwardGI="1" CommandLatency="300" />
Table 4.4 IEC60870-5-104 Slave ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will not be set (‘0’). Time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages are adjusted based on a timezone selected for the current communication protocol instance. As it is impossible to distinguish between Standard time and Daylight Saving Time (DST) at the end of the DST (this is when clock is turned back one hour) all time-tags generated during the final hour of the DST are treated as Standard time. For example time-tag with 01:04:00 BST will be treated as 01:04:00 GMT. There is no issue at the begning of the DST (this is when clock is turned forward one hour).
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will be set (‘1’) if the time-tag contains Daylight Saving Time (DST) (Summer Time). It is also expected that the peer station sets Summer Time [SU] bit in all time-tags containing DST. If the peer station doesn’t set the [SU] bit it is assumed that all time-tags contain Standard time.
DIEventType See Table 5.3 30 [M_SP_TB_1] Use this ASDU type to send DI events which don’t have DI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 30 – ‘Single-point Information’, DI event will be sent using ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time)
AIEventType See Table 5.8 36 [M_ME_TF_1] Use this ASDU type to send AI events which don’t have AI.TypeID attribute specified in their element node. This setting also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point) reported to a General Interrogation request. (default value 36 – ‘Short floating point’, AI event will be sent using ASDU type 36 [M_ME_TF_1], CP56time2A, full time)
DOType See Table 5.12 0 = any Only accept command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Single or Double command) if DO object doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
AOType See Table 5.16 0 = any Only accept setpoint command if received with this ASDU Type (e.g. Normalized or Scaled setpoint) if AO object doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in the element node. (default value 0 – accept command with any ASDU type)
DOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if DO object doesn’t have DO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
AOProc 0; 1 or 2 0 = any Enabled command procedures (e.g. Direct Execute or Select-Before-Execute) if AO object doesn’t have AO.qualifier attribute specified in the element node. Values: 0 – accept any command procedure; 1 – accept only Direct Execute; 2 – accept only Select-Before-Execute;
DIInterDelay 0…232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.InterDelay attribute. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds)
DIIndetDelay 0…232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double status objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. This attribute is used for DI objects which don’t have DI.IndetDelay attribute. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds)
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
TimeSync 0 0 Reject incoming clock synchronization messages.
1 Accept incoming clock synchronization messages and synchronize internal real time clock. Please note internal real time clock will be synchronized immediately if a time difference between received time stamp and the internal clock is greater than 1 hour. If a time difference is less than 1 hour, internal clock will be adjusted only once an hour.
TranspTypes 0 0 ASDU type of every DI/AI object is determined by XML configuration settings.
1 ASDU type of every DI/AI object will be made transparent whenever possible. The same ASDU type will be used to report DI/AI object to upstream station as received from downstream outstation, providing both source and destination communication protocol instances are compatible. Otherwise default ASDU type will be used. Please note the object will be excluded from General Interrogation response before it is received from downstream outstation on |leandcfw| startup. This is because it is impossible to determine ASDU type of the object before is has been received from outstation.
orCat 1…8 3 Originator category value for outgoing commands [IEC61850-7-3:2011]. Used only for commands sent to IEC61850 Client instances. Default value 3 = [remote-control]
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 4.5 for description.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
CommandLatency 0…232 - 1 0 sec Maximal difference in seconds between received time-tagged control command and the internal time. If this attribute is used, time-tag of the received control command is checked and command will be discarded if it has been substantially delayed. Value 0 disables time-tagged command validation and any incoming control command will be accepted.
Table 4.5 IEC60870-5-104 Slave ASDU flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF ASDU flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use internal time when sending delayed INTER or INDET state event. This setting applies only to 2 Single Point object conversion to a Double Point. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event’s time tag will contain the current time i.e. the time when this event is generated.
xxxx.1xxx Use original time tag of the event that resulted in INTER or INDET state. This setting applies only to 2 Single Point object conversion to a Double Point. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event will contain original time tag of the event (received before the delay) that resulted in INTER/INDET state.
Bits 0…2;4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control quality flags of the DI/AI events generated when outstation goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings NotInitFlags="0x80" DisabledFlags="0x80" OfflineFlags="0x40" PostOfflineFlags="0x80" EventMask="0x00" />
Table 4.6 IEC60870-5-104 Slave ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NotInitFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. See Table 4.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires on |leandcfw| startup. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
DisabledFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station gets Disabled with a Service command. See Table 4.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when station gets Disabled. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
OfflineFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers when station state changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires) See Table 4.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when OfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
PostOfflineFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x80 Invalid [IV] Set quality bits of all DI/AI qualifiers after PostOfflineDelay timer expires. See Table 4.8 for quality bit description. Note DI/AI qualifier quality bits (of static objects) will always be set when PostOfflineDelay timer expires. However DI/AI events will be generated only if not masked by EventMask attribute.
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 4.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 4.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use
Table 4.8 DI/AI qualifier quality bits
Bits Value Description
Quality bits [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI/AI qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will not be set
xxx1.xxxx Blocked [BL] bit will be set
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will not be set
xx1x.xxxx Substituted [SB] bit will be set
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will not be set
x1xx.xxxx Not Topical [NT] bit will be set
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will not be set
1xxx.xxxx Invalid [IV] bit will be set
Bits 0…3 xxxx.0000 Bits are used for Single/Double status information and Overflow [OV] indication. These will not be updated when communication status of the station changes.

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" CmdForward="10"/>
Table 4.9 IEC60870-5-104 Slave Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from the destination (e.g. downstream station) after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and negative response is sent to the upstream (Master) station. Application timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged if communication to the destination (e.g. downstream station) is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance attempts to send command response to the upstream (Master) station. If it is not possible to send a response within a configured number of seconds, command is considered to be failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). Command timeout ensures pending control commands are automatically purged if communication to upstream (Master) station is lost.
Select 1…232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, controlable object (DO/AO) is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.
CmdForward 0…232 - 1 10 sec Command forward timeout is a maximal delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits destination (Master protocol instance) to become available for accepting a new command. If destination protocol instance is in the process of executing previous command, it may not be able to accept new command before the previous command is complete. The new command fails within a configured number of seconds if it can’t be forwarded to the destination. This timeout allows control command queueing for a short period of time and ensures pending command is automatically purged if destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command. Value 0 disables command queueing and command fails instantly if the destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />

Miscellaneous

Miscellaneous and project-specific settings can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Miscellaneous node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Miscellaneous LegacyAIEVinitdelay="2" />
Table 4.13 IEC60870-5-104 Slave Miscellaneous attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
LegacyAIEVinitdelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Attribute enables specially marked (legacy spontaneous-only) AI object initialization after configured number of seconds on system startup. This feature applies only to AI objects that have Legacy Bit[2] = 1 in AI.qualifier. By default Legacy AI objects are sent upstream spontaneously with a last known value from internal database whenever downstream outstation goes online e.g. after a communication loss or when Enabled with a Service command. Legacy AI events do not have Invalid [IV] nor Not Topical [NT] bits set, with the exception on system startup. AI events will have value 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set when initialized for the first time on startup. This is a standard behaviour for Legacy AI events and it is not affected by the use of the LegacyAIEVinitdelay attribute. This attribute extends functionality by providing a mechanism to remove Invalid [IV] bit after configured number of seconds on system startup. Legacy AI objects with value 0 and cleared Invalid [IV] bit will be sent with Background scan message(s) after a number of seconds configured in this attribute. As a result upstream station (e.g. SCADA) will have a valid legacy AI object (without Invalid [IV] bit) with value 0 in the database and will be ready to process the first genuine AI event when it arrives.

5. IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave IO table

This section describes how to create an IO object table for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances. Group object nodes DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable are included in XML configuration files of the IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication protocol instances as described in previous sections IEC60870-5-101 Slave and IEC60870-5-104 Slave.

DITable group

Group node DITable and element nodes DI are used to define DI information objects that provide status information to upstream Master station. Each DI node must have a source DI information object to obtain the status information from. The source is created by linking DI node to a DI information object of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using DI.Device and DI.Index attributes as follows:
1. Select the source Master protocol instance - use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance and enter this value in DI.Device attribute.
2. Select the source DI object - use value of the DI.Index attribute of any DI object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance and enter this value in DI.Index attribute.

Information object address (IOA) to send status information object upstream is specified in InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample DITable group and DI element nodes below. There are 5 status information objects defined with 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0" GroupMask="0x0001" … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x10" TypeID="30"  … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="-2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x00" TypeID="30"  … />
     <DI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Total="2" … />
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0" GroupMask="0x0001" TypeID="30" OffIndex="5" InterDelay="8000" IndetDelay="3500" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 5.1 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Device 1…254 n/a Source communication protocol instance, any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as the source for this DI object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.
Index -8…224 - 1 n/a Source DI object. Any DI element of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a source. Use value of the DI.Index attribute of any DI object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. In addition to regular DIs there are internal indications available. Internal indications are used to monitor real-time status of the source protocol instance. Each internal indication has a service index and they are summarized in the Table 5.4. Indexes don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
InfAddr 1…16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the DI object. This IOA will be used to send object to upstream station. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 5.2 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
GroupMask 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Include object in Interrogation group/groups. Each bit of the group mask attribute needs to be set in order to include object in a particular interrogation group. Please refer to the Table 5.9 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
TypeID See Table 5.3 2 [M_SP_TA_1] or 30 [M_SP_TB_1] Use this ASDU Type to send a DI event. Attribute also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Single or Double status information) being reported to General interrogation request. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
OffIndex -8…232 - 8 Same as Index DI object index of the second single point used as a source for conversion to double status indication. Resulting Double point will have ON value when source DI object specified in Index attribute is ON. Resulting Double point will have OFF value when source DI object specified in OffIndex attribute is ON. See Table 5.5 for additional information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, no conversion will take place if this attribute is omitted.
InterDelay 0…232 - 1 10000 msec Intermediate state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double point objects. Intermediate state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 10000 - event will be generated if Intermediate state lasts longer than 10 seconds) This attribute has a higher priority than IEC101sl and IEC104sl ASDUSettings.DIInterDelay. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
IndetDelay 0…232 - 1 5000 msec Indeterminate (error) state reporting delay in milliseconds used when single status information objects are converted to double point objects. Indeterminate (error) state of the resulting DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 5000 - event will be generated if Indeterminate (error) state lasts longer than 5 seconds) This attribute has a higher priority than IEC101sl and IEC104sl ASDUSettings.DIIndetDelay. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.qualifier

Table 5.2 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation enabled. An OFF event will be internally generated following every sent DI ON event. DI object will always have OFF value in Interrogation responses.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI events enabled. DI event will be sent upstream if state of the object changes or new event is received from the source communication protocol instance
xxxx.x1xx DI events disabled
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI object will be included in General Interrogation response
xxxx.1xxx DI object will be excluded from General Interrogation response
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event when 2 Single Point objects are merged into a Double Point object. e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used for resulting DPI.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event when 2 Single Point objects are merged into a Double Point object. e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used for resulting DPI.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx All DI events will be sent upstream
x1xx.xxxx DI events with OFF values or with set [IV] bit will be discarded. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be sent upstream
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will not be sent upstream
Bit 4 Any Bits reserved for future use

DI.TypeID

Table 5.3 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave DI TypeID
TypeID for IEC60870-5-101 TypeID for IEC60870-5-104 Description
1 1 Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1], no time-tag
2 N/A Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
3 3 Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1], no time-tag
4 N/A Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 4 [M_DP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
30 30 Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
31 31 Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 31 [M_DP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
Other Other Undefined, default values will be used: IEC60870-5-101 default ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min IEC60870-5-104 default ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time

Tip

Note, all DI objects are internally stored and processed as ‘Double-point status information’. If ‘Single-point status information’ type needs to be reported to the upstream Master station, object is being converted just before it is sent.

DI Service Indexes

Service digital inputs are internal indications that provide real-time status information of communication protocol instances. Service indications have negative index values and can be used just as any regular DI indexes.

Table 5.4 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave Service DI indexes
Index Status Description
-2 (0xFFFFFFFE) ON Communication between leandc application and peer station is running, peer station is Online. This service index can be used for any protocol instance (Master and Slave instances).
OFF Communication between leandc application and peer station is lost, peer station is Offline. This service index can be used for any protocol instance (Master and Slave instances).
-3 (0xFFFFFFFD) ON Communication between leandc application and peer station is Enabled. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
OFF Communication between leandc application and peer station is Disabled. This service index can be used for any protocol instance.
-4* (0xFFFFFFFC) ON Communication to peer station is Started. Refer to the footnote below for the list of protocol instances that provide this service indication.
OFF Communication to peer station is Stopped. Refer to the footnote below for the list of protocol instances that provide this service indication.
-5 (0xFFFFFFFB) ON Only used for protocol instances linked to UART hardware node; State of the UART Ring Indicator (RI) pin(9) is active (+12V). This service DI can be used only if UART.CtrlRdTimer attribute is defined.
OFF Only used for protocol instances linked to UART hardware node; State of the UART Ring Indicator (RI) pin(9) is not active (-12V). This service DI can be used only if UART.CtrlRdTimer attribute is defined.
-1 and -6…-8 Any Internal indications reserved for future use

Tip

* Index=”-4” service indication only applies to the following protocol instances:
IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication is [Started] or [Stopped]. ON ([Started] state) indicates [STARTDT_con] has been received from outstation;
IEC60870-5-104 controlled station (Slave) communication is [Started] or [Stopped]. ON ([Started] state) indicates [STARTDT_act] message has been received from upstream station;
IEC61850 Client association state. ON indicates associated state i.e. [Initiate-ResponsePDU] message has been received from IED;

DI SPI/DPI conversion

Single to double point conversion takes place if OffIndex attribute is used. Values of source DI objects and resulting DPI object are listed in the truth table below.

Table 5.5 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave SPI/DPI truth table
Value of Index DI Value of OffIndex DI Resulting DPI
OFF (0) OFF (0) Intermediate (0)
OFF (0) ON (1) OFF (1)
ON (1) OFF (0) ON (2)
ON (1) ON (1) Indeterminate (error) (3)
Other Other Indeterminate (error) (3)

Intermediate and Indeterminate state reporting can be delayed using InterDelay and IndetDelay attributes respectively. If ON->INTER->OFF or OFF->INTER->ON transition successfully completes before InterDelay timer expiration, Intermediate state will not be reported. Delay setting has to be carefully selected to ensure it always exceeds time required for ON->INTER->OFF or OFF->INTER->ON transitions to complete, to take advantage of this functionality. If delay attributes are set 0 Intermediate and Indeterminate states will be reported as soon as values of source DI objects become those listed in the table above.

AITable group

Group node AITable and element nodes AI are used to define AI information objects that provide analog information to upstream Master station. Each AI node must have a source AI information object to obtain the analog information from. The source is created by linking AI node to a AI information object of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using AI.Device and AI.Index attributes as follows:
1. Select the source Master protocol instance - use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance and enter this value in AI.Device attribute.
2. Select the source AI object - use value of the AI.Index attribute of any AI object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance and enter this value in AI.Index attribute.

Information object address (IOA) to send analog information object upstream is specified in InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample AITable group and AI element nodes below. There are 5 analog information objects defined with 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Offset="28.0" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x00" ZeroDeadband="1.0" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x01" Coeff="0.05" GroupMask="0x0002" … />
     <AI Device="10" Index="3" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0" Offset="2.0" Total="2" … />
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0" Coeff="100.0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="5.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" GroupMask="0x0002" TypeID="13" Total="2" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 5.6 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Device 1…254 n/a Source communication protocol instance, any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as the source for this AI object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.
Index -8…224 - 1 n/a Source AI object. Any AI element of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a source. Use value of the AI.Index attribute of any AI object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. Indexes don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
InfAddr 1…16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the AI object. This IOA will be used to send object to upstream station. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 5.7 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the analog object value before sending to upstream Master station. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
GroupMask 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Include object in Interrogation group/groups. Each bit of the group mask attribute needs to be set in order to include object in a particular interrogation group. Please refer to the Table 5.9 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
TypeID See Table 5.8 14 [M_ME_TC_1] or 36 [M_ME_TF_1] Use this ASDU Type to send a AI event. Attribute also affects ASDU type of the static data (e.g. Normalized, Scaled, Short floating point value) being reported to General interrogation request Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Total 1…16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling and application examples using StartOffset ; ZeroDeadband ; Offset ; OffsetDeadband ; NonZeroOffset attributes.
