DOTable group

Group node DOTable and element nodes DO are used to define DO information objects that allow to receive a control command from upstream Master station. Each DO node must have a destination to forward the control command to. The destination is created by linking DO node to a DO information object of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using DO.Device and DO.Index attributes as follows:
1. Select the destination Master protocol instance - use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance and enter this value in DO.Device attribute.
2. Select the destination DO object - use value of the DO.Index attribute of any DO object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance enter this value in DO.Index attribute.

Information object address (IOA) to receive the control command is specified in the InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 5 control commands defined with 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" Policy="0" … />
     <DO Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" Policy="250" … />
     <DO Device="10" Index="-2" InfAddr="3" Policy="0" … />
     <DO Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" Policy="0" Total="2" … />
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x10" Policy="0" TypeID="0" OffIndex="33" Total="2" Name="CB command" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DO Service Indexes

Service digital outputs are internal controls that enable to change operation state of communication protocol instances. Service controls have negative index values and can be used just as any regular DO indexes.

Table 5.13 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave Service DO indexes
Index Qualifier Description
-2 (0xFFFFFFFE) ON or OFF
Send forced Poll only applicable to the following communication protocol instances:
IEC60870-5-101/3/4 Master - Send General Interrogation command (ASDU type 100 [C_IC_NA_1]) to downstream outstation;
IEC61850 Client - Send General Interrogation by setting [GI] bit of all enabled Report Control Blocks;
Spabus Master - Read all DI values if DI requests are excluded from regular polling with Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.

* This service command only applies to the following protocol instances:
IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) send [STARTDT_act] or [STOPDT_act] to the downstream station;
IEC61850 Client send MMS [Initiate-RequestPDU] or [Conclude-RequestPDU] to the IED;

AOTable group

Group node AOTable and element nodes AO are used to define AO information objects that allow to receive a setpoint command from upstream Master station. Each AO node must have a destination to forward the setpoint command to. The destination is created by linking AO node to a AO information object of any Master protocol instance. (Master protocol instances are defined in CommunicationCfg group in leandc.xml file)

The link is created using AO.Device and AO.Index attributes as follows:
1. Select the destination Master protocol instance - use value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance and enter this value in AO.Device attribute.
2. Select the destination AO object - use value of the AO.Index attribute of any AO object listed in the IO object table of a Master protocol instance and enter this value in AO.Index attribute.

Information object address (IOA) to receive the setpoint command is specified in the InfAddr attribute.

Please see sample AOTable group and AO element nodes below. There are 5 setpoint commands defined with 4 AO element nodes.

<AOTable>
     <AO Device="10" Index="0" InfAddr="1" Policy="0" … />
     <AO Device="10" Index="1" InfAddr="2" Policy="250" … />
     <AO Device="10" Index="-2" InfAddr="3" Policy="0" … />
     <AO Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" Policy="0" Total="2" … />
</AOTable>

Please see sample AO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AO Device="10" Index="2" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x80" Coeff="15.3" Policy="0" TypeID="0" Total="2" Name="Filter value" />

Tip

Attributes of the AO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

Table 5.14 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave AO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description

Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as the destination for this AO object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.

Command Policy

Table 5.17 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave command execution policy
Policy Description
0 Select and Execute commands received from upstream Master station will be forwarded to the destination outstation. Command responses to upstream Master station will be sent only after received from the destination outstation.
1 Select command confirmation response to upstream Master station will be generated by the communication protocol instance immediately after command reception. Execute command will be forwarded to the destination outstation and response to upstream Master station will be sent only after received from the destination outstation
2 Select and Execute command confirmation responses to upstream Master station will be generated by the communication protocol instance immediately after command reception. Termination response to upstream Master station will be sent only after received from the destination outstation
250 Dummy policy can be used to check availability of the destination outstation and DO/AO object configuration. All DO/AO command validation checks will be performed, but no actual command will be sent to the destination station. Positive confirmation and termination responses will be generated by the communication protocol instance if command validation was successfully and destination outstation is online
3…249 Reserved for future use

AUTOCfg group

Group node AutoCfg and element nodes AUTO enable automatic object linking without a need to create DI/AI/DO/AO object table. All DI/AI/DO/AO objects of the Master protocol instance are automatically linked to Slave protocol instance if this feature is used. Easiest way to enable automatic linking is by specifying value of the Index attribute of any Master protocol instance in the Source attribute. By default information addresses of DI/AI/DO/AO objects will be the same as defined in Master protocol instance’s object table. It is also possible to override automatic information address initialization and have them initialized sequentially using DIInfAddr; AIInfAddr; DOInfAddr; AOInfAddr attributes. The first object will have information address as specified and following objects will be initialized sequentially. AutoCfg group can have multiple AUTO nodes as shown in the sample below.

<AutoCfg>
     <AUTO Source="1" Name="RTU1" />
     <AUTO Source="2" Name="RTU2" />
     <AUTO Name="RTU3" />
</AutoCfg>

Please see sample AUTO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AUTO Source="1" DIInfAddr="1001" AIInfAddr="2001" DOInfAddr="4001" AOInfAddr="5001" DIqual="0x00" AIqual="0x00" DOqual="0x00" AOqual="0x00" DIGroupMask="0x0001" AIGroupMask="0x0002" Policy="0" CommsOnlineAddr="1" Name="Auto configuration" />

Tip

Attributes of the AUTO element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

Table 5.18 IEC60870-5-101/104 Slave AUTO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Source 1…254 n/a Source communication protocol instance, any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as the source. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, value of the IEC101sl.Source or IEC104sl.Source attributes will be used if omitted.

Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will have the same information addresses as defined in source communication protocol object table.

Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will have the same information addresses as defined in source communication protocol object table.

Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will have the same information addresses as defined in source communication protocol object table.
AOInfAddr 1…16777215 n/a Base AO information object address. Addresses of AO objects will be initialized sequentially starting with this value. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will have the same information addresses as defined in source communication protocol object table.

Each bit of the group mask attribute needs to be set in order to include object in a particular interrogation group. Please refer to the Table 5.9 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

CommsOnlineAddr 1…16777215 n/a Information address to report service DI – peer station communication (Online/Offline) status. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, communication status will not be reported if omitted.

6. IEC60870-5-101 Master

This section contains details on how to configure IEC60870-5-101 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-101 controlling station (Master) instance must have XML configuration file where IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. This may be useful if identical set of IO objects is acquired from several outstations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC101ma_test.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC101ma.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC101ma_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-101 Master configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC101ma_test.xml’) must have a root node IEC101maConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
4 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC101maConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC101ma" …  version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4" date="2022-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10" Total="16"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x00" Total="16" Coeff="1"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" InfAddr="1" TypeID="46" Total="16"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Index="0" InfAddr="1" TypeID="50" Total="16"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</IEC101maConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table. They are identical for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instances. Please refer to the tables Table 8.1; Table 8.4; Table 8.7 and Table 8.11 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-101 controlling station (Master) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <XMLSettings … />
  <LinkSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <ASDUSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Broadcast … />
  <Periodic … />
  <Miscellaneous … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 6.1 IEC60870-5-101 Master XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings LinkAddrSize="1" LinkOnlineCounter="5" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 6.2 IEC60870-5-101 Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
LinkAddrSize 1 or 2 1 byte Link layer address size in bytes. Please note link address size of the protocol instances sharing the same hardware node must be the same.
LinkOnlineCounter 0…65535 0 requests Application layer operation delay after link becomes valid. First application layer message (e.g. GI or Time Sync) will be delayed for a configured number of outgoing link messages after Reset Remote link response is received from outstation. Value 0 disables delay - application layer starts running immediately after Reset Remote link response is received from outstation.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 6.3 for description.
Table 6.3 IEC60870-5-101 Master Link flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Link flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send variable and fixed length link layer messages as required (First byte of the variable link layer message is - 0x68 and fixed length message - 0x10).
xxxx.xxx1 Send only variable length link layer messages (First byte of the link layer message - 0x68).
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Process received application layer messages while link online delay counter operates. This setting applies only if LinkOnlineCounter is used.
xxx1.xxxx Ignore received application layer messages while link online delay counter operates. Application message processing starts only after number of link messages defined in LinkOnlineCounter have been received from outstation.
Bits 1…3;5…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) reporting and related delays can be specified using attributes of CommsSettings element node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and the table listing all available attributes below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" ControlLockTimer="20" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" OnlineGIDelay="10" />
Table 6.4 IEC60870-5-101 Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NoRespCount 1…255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)
DegradedRetries 0…255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
DegradedTimeout 0…232 - 1 600 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
ControlLockTimer 0…120 20 sec Control command lock timer is used to poll only one outstation for a configured number of seconds after sending a control command. All other outstations that share the same hardware channel (e.g. serial port) are temporary excluded from polling while ControlLockTimer operates. This feature enables to speed up reception of a control command feedback. ControlLockTimer can only be used if more than one outstation share the hardware channel. Value 0 disables control lock timer feature.
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)
OnlineGIDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec General Interrogation command will be delayed for a configured number of seconds after outstation goes online. This delay is designed to allow outstation to poll data after reset/power-on and before data is beeing requested by leandc application with a General Interrogation command.

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings COTSize="1" CAASize="1" IOASize="2" InvalidEvent="1" IgnoreTimetags="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DOQOC="1" DOType="46" AOType="50" Flags="0x00" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1" TimetagFBrange="180"/>
Table 6.5 IEC60870-5-101 Master ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
COTSize 1 or 2 1 byte Cause Of Transmission size in bytes including Originator address (default 1 byte - if originator address is not used)
CAASize 1 or 2 1 byte Common address of ASDU size in bytes
IOASize 1; 2 or 3 2 bytes Information Object Address size in bytes
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation. DI.qualifier or AI.qualifier attribute can be used to disable timetag processing for each DI/AI.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no hysteresis, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will not be set (‘0’). Time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages are adjusted based on a timezone selected for the current communication protocol instance. As it is impossible to distinguish between Standard time and Daylight Saving Time (DST) at the end of the DST (this is when clock is turned back one hour) all time-tags generated during the final hour of the DST are treated as Standard time. For example time-tag with 01:04:00 BST will be treated as 01:04:00 GMT. There is no issue at the begning of the DST (this is when clock is turned forward one hour).
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will be set (‘1’) if the time-tag contains Daylight Saving Time (DST) (Summer Time). It is also expected that the peer station sets Summer Time [SU] bit in all time-tags containing DST. If the peer station doesn’t set the [SU] bit it is assumed that all time-tags contain Standard time.
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
DOQOC See Table 8.10 0 Qualifier Of Command [QOC] is used to set additional information (e.g. [no additional definition]; [short-pulse duration]) when command is being sent to the DO object which doesn’t have DO.QOC attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.10 for available values. (default value 0 [no additional definition])
DOType See Table 8.9 transparent DO ASDU type is used when command is being sent to the DO object which doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.9 for values. ASDU type is transparent if neither this attribute nor DO.TypeID attribute is used.
AOType See Table 8.13 transparent AO ASDU type is used when command is being sent to the AO object which doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.13 for values. ASDU type is transparent if neither this attribute nor AO.TypeID attribute is used.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 6.6 for description.
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
TimetagFBrange 0…600 240 sec Received time-tag hour forward-backward adjustment range. If the short time-tag [CP24Time2a] of the event received from outstation is closer to full hour (0 mins 0 secs) than the specified range in seconds, the hour value of the resulting timestamp will be automatically adjusted. This functionality ensures correct hour value is attached to the short time-tag [CP24Time2a], as it carries only minutes and milliseconds, if event arrived late. Hour, day, month and year values are taken from internal system time. If the time value of the event time-tag is just before a full hour (e.g. min:msec = 59:58000) and there is a delay in communication channel, there is a chance the event is received only after internal hour has already changed (e.g. hh:min:sec.msec = 13:00:01.000). This will lead to incorrect hour (hour = 13) being applied to the resulting timestamp, although it is most likely the event was generated before the hour change (e.g. generated at hh:min:sec.msec = 12:59:58.000). TimetagFBrange attribute ensures the hour of the resulting timestamp is automatically decremented if the time of the received time-tag falls within a forward-backward adjustment range and internal hour has recently changed. Similar functionality applies if the time of the received time-tag appears to be in the future, but the internal hour hasn’t changed yet. In this case hour of the resulting timestamp is automatically incremented. Default value 240 will adjust received event time-tags min:msec = 56:00000…03:59999 if they arrive when internal time is hh:min:sec.msec = 12:56:00.000…13:03:59.999
Table 6.6 IEC60870-5-101 Master ASDU flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF ASDU flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use internal time when sending delayed INTER or INDET state event. This setting applies only to Double Point DI objects if Intermediate or Indeterminate state delay is enabled. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event’s time tag will contain the current time i.e. the time when this event is generated.
xxxx.1xxx Use original time tag of the event that resulted in INTER or INDET state. This setting applies only to Double Point DI objects if Intermediate or Indeterminate state delay is enabled. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event will contain original time tag of the event (received before the delay) that resulted in INTER/INDET state.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Check Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be discarded.
xxx1.xxxx Ignore Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be processed as if no test bit was set.
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Ignore Originator Address [OA] of the received command responses. Command response will be accepted even if it has different Originator Address [OA] than sent command.
xx1x.xxxx Check Originator Address [OA] of the received command responses. Command response will be ignored if it has different Originator Address [OA] than sent command.
Bits 0…2;6…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 6.7 IEC60870-5-101 Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 6.8 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 6.8 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" />
Table 6.9 IEC60870-5-101 Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.
Select 1…232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, controlable object (DO/AO) is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />
Table 6.10 IEC60870-5-101 Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

7. IEC60870-5-104 Master

This section contains details on how to configure IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) instance must have XML configuration file where IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. This may be useful if identical set of IO objects is acquired from several outstations.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC104ma_test.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC104ma.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC104ma_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-104 Master configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC104ma_test.xml’) must have a root node IEC104maConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
4 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC104maConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC104ma" …  version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4" date="2022-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x10" Total="16"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x00" Total="16" Coeff="1"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" InfAddr="1" TypeID="46" Total="16"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Index="0" InfAddr="1" TypeID="50" Total="16"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</IEC104maConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table. They are identical for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instances. Please refer to the tables Table 8.1; Table 8.4; Table 8.7 and Table 8.11 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <XMLSettings … />
  <TransportSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <ASDUSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Broadcast … />
  <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

XMLSettings

XML file parse settings such as information object address validation can be specified in this node.

Please see sample XMLSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<XMLSettings IOAOverlap="1" />
Table 7.1 IEC60870-5-104 Master XMLSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IOAOverlap 0 0 Each information object (DI/AI/DO/AO) specified in an IO table must have unique information object address (IOA). Error message will be generated and IO object table will be purged if address duplication is detected.
1 Information address duplication is checked only within confines of a particular object type (DI/AI/DO/AO). Objects of different types are allowed to reuse same information addresses. Error message will be generated and objects of a particular type will be purged if address duplication is detected.

TransportSettings

Protocol transport interface settings such as timeouts and message window sizes can be specified using attributes of TransportSettings element node.

Please see sample TransportSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TransportSettings T0="30" T1="15" T2="10" T3="20" Kparam="12" Wparam="8" />
Table 7.2 IEC60870-5-104 Master TransportSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
T0 1…65535 30 sec Timeout of connection establishment as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a delay in seconds for how long TCP socket should wait acknowledge from a peer station after sending connection establishment request (e.g. TCP SYN)
T1 1…65535 15 sec Timeout of send or test APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance waits a reply to a sent APDU [I-frame] or test message [TESTFR_act]. If no reply is received from peer station within a configured timeout, communication protocol instance initiates active close of the TCP socket.
T2 1…65535 10 sec Timeout for acknowledges in case of no data messages as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. (requirement: T2timer < T1timer) It is a delay in seconds before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame] in case there are any unacknowledged messages from the peer station.
T3 1…65535 20 sec Timeout for sending test messages in case of a long idle state from IEC60870-5-104 standard. It is a maximal idle time in seconds before a test message [TESTFR_act] is sent to a peer station by the communication protocol instance. If this timeout is selected greater than T3 timeout configured in the peer station, it is most likely the test message will be sent by the peer station first.
Kparam 1…30 12 APDU Maximum difference receive sequence number to send state variable as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Maximal number of outgoing APDU messages [I-frame] communication protocol instance will send to a peer station before it waits for an acknowledge [S-frame]
Wparam 1…29 8 APDU Latest acknowledge after receiving w number I format APDUs as per IEC60870-5-104 standard. Number of incoming APDU messages [I-frame] received from a peer station before communication protocol instance sends an acknowledge [S-frame]

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified using attributes of CommsSettings element node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" OnlineGIDelay="10" Flags="0x00" />
Table 7.3 IEC60870-5-104 Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 6 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated after TCP socket has been closed. Default 6 seconds - station status will change to OFFLINE 6 seconds after TCP socket has been closed by either host.
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)
OnlineGIDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec General Interrogation command will be delayed for a configured number of seconds after outstation goes online. This delay is designed to allow outstation to poll data after reset/power-on and before data is beeing requested by leandc application with a General Interrogation command.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various communication related settings. See Table 7.4 for description.
Table 7.4 IEC60870-5-104 Master Communication flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Communication flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Send General Interrogation command when outstation goes online after a communication loss (station status changes to ONLINE)
xxxx.1xxx Don’t send General Interrogation command when outstation goes online after a communication loss (station status changes to ONLINE). General Interrogation is always sent on system startup regardless of this setting.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Purge unacknowledged [I-frames] when new connection to outstation is established after a communication loss.
xxx1.xxxx Resend unacknowledged [I-frames] when new connection to outstation is established after a communication loss. Care must be taken when this option is enabled as it may result in previously unacknowledged Control commands being sent. This can happen after any length of time.
Bits 0…2;5…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings InvalidEvent="1" IgnoreTimetags="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DOQOC="1" DOType="46" AOType="50" Flags="0x00" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1" />
Table 7.5 IEC60870-5-104 Master ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation. DI.qualifier or AI.qualifier attribute can be used to disable timetag processing for each DI/AI.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no hysteresis, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will not be set (‘0’). Time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages are adjusted based on a timezone selected for the current communication protocol instance. As it is impossible to distinguish between Standard time and Daylight Saving Time (DST) at the end of the DST (this is when clock is turned back one hour) all time-tags generated during the final hour of the DST are treated as Standard time. For example time-tag with 01:04:00 BST will be treated as 01:04:00 GMT. There is no issue at the begning of the DST (this is when clock is turned forward one hour).
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will be set (‘1’) if the time-tag contains Daylight Saving Time (DST) (Summer Time). It is also expected that the peer station sets Summer Time [SU] bit in all time-tags containing DST. If the peer station doesn’t set the [SU] bit it is assumed that all time-tags contain Standard time.
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
DOQOC See Table 8.10 0 Qualifier Of Command [QOC] is used to set additional information (e.g. [no additional definition]; [short-pulse duration]) when command is being sent to the DO object which doesn’t have DO.QOC attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.10 for available values. (default value 0 [no additional definition])
DOType See Table 8.9 transparent DO ASDU type is used when command is being sent to the DO object which doesn’t have DO.TypeID attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.9 for values. ASDU type is transparent if neither this attribute nor DO.TypeID attribute is used.
AOType See Table 8.13 transparent AO ASDU type is used when command is being sent to the AO object which doesn’t have AO.TypeID attribute specified in its element node. Refer to Table 8.13 for values. ASDU type is transparent if neither this attribute nor AO.TypeID attribute is used.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 7.6 for description.
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
Table 7.6 IEC60870-5-104 Master ASDU flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF ASDU flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use internal time when sending delayed INTER or INDET state event. This setting applies only to Double Point DI objects if Intermediate or Indeterminate state delay is enabled. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event’s time tag will contain the current time i.e. the time when this event is generated.
xxxx.1xxx Use original time tag of the event that resulted in INTER or INDET state. This setting applies only to Double Point DI objects if Intermediate or Indeterminate state delay is enabled. In case Intermediate/Indeterminate state reporting is delayed with DI.InterDelay or DI.IndetDelay attributes, the INTER/INDET state event will contain original time tag of the event (received before the delay) that resulted in INTER/INDET state.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Check Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be discarded.
xxx1.xxxx Ignore Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be processed as if no test bit was set.
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Ignore Originator Address [OA] of the received command responses. Command response will be accepted even if it has different Originator Address [OA] than sent command.
xx1x.xxxx Check Originator Address [OA] of the received command responses. Command response will be ignored if it has different Originator Address [OA] than sent command.
Bits 0…2;6…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

(default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 7.8 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported

xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.

8. IEC60870-5-101/104 Master IO table

This section describes how to create an IO object table for IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instances. Group object nodes DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable are included in XML configuration files of the IEC60870-5-101 and IEC60870-5-104 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instances as described in previous sections IEC60870-5-101 Master and IEC60870-5-104 Master.

DITable group

DITable group and its elements DI are used to define DI information objects that contain status information received from outstation. Each DI element can be linked to DI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining status information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives DI status information from outstation and processes it based on settings in the Table 8.1.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked DI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the DITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DI information objects.

In order to receive status information from outstation information object address (IOA) needs to be specified in the InfAddr attribute. Status information is processed when received from outstation with any of the following ASDU types: 1 [M_SP_NA_1]; 2 [M_SP_TA_1]; 3 [M_DP_NA_1]; 4 [M_DP_TA_1]; 30 [M_SP_TB_1]; 31 [M_DP_TB_1]

Please see sample DITable group and DI element nodes below. There are 5 status information objects defined with 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x00" />
     <DI Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x10" />
     <DI Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x10" TypeID="31"/>
     <DI Index="3" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0" InterDelay="10000" IndetDelay="0" OnDelay="0" OffDelay="0" TypeID="31" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 8.1 IEC60870-5-101/104 Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
InfAddr 1…16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the DI object. This IOA will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 8.2 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
InterDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
IndetDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec ON position reporting delay in milliseconds. ON position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. OFF->ON->OFF->ON) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after ON position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec OFF position reporting delay in milliseconds. OFF position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. ON->OFF->ON->OFF) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after OFF position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
TypeID See Table 8.3 transparent Use this ASDU type to send a DI object upstream, if transparent ASDUs are enabled in IEC101 or IEC104 Slave protocol instance with ASDUSettings.TranspTypes attribute. This ASDU type will be used to send object regardless of the received ASDU type. There is no default value, attribute must not be specified if not used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration. ASDU type received from outstation will be used to report object upstream if transparent ASDUs are enabled in Slave protocol instance with ASDUSettings.TranspTypes attribute.
Total 1…16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.qualifier

Table 8.2 IEC60870-5-101/104 Master DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1 for [M_SP_NA_1] type and ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [M_DP_NA_1] type)
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation enabled. An OFF event will be internally generated following every sent DI ON event. Static DI object will be set to OFF value, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated only if a DI object state has changed
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time DI object is received from outstation. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this DI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from outstation
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from outstation
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 4;6 Any Bits reserved for future use

DI.TypeID

Table 8.3 IEC60870-5-101/104 Master DI TypeID
TypeID for IEC60870-5-101 TypeID for IEC60870-5-104 Description
1 1 Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1], no time-tag
2 N/A Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
3 3 Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1], no time-tag
4 N/A Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 4 [M_DP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min
30 30 Static ‘Single-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 1 [M_SP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
31 31 Static ‘Double-point Information’ (response to GI) will be sent with ASDU type 3 [M_DP_NA_1]. Events will be sent with ASDU type 31 [M_DP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time
Other Other Undefined, default values will be used: IEC60870-5-101 default ASDU type 2 [M_SP_TA_1], CP24time2A, msec and min IEC60870-5-104 default ASDU type 30 [M_SP_TB_1], CP56time2A, full time

Tip

Note, all DI objects are internally stored and processed as ‘Double-point status information’. If ‘Single-point status information’ type needs to be reported to the upstream Master station, object is being converted just before it is sent.

AITable group

AITable group and its elements AI are used to define AI information objects that contain analog information received from outstation. Each AI element can be linked to AI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining analog information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives AI analog information from outstation and processes it based on settings in the Table 8.4.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked AI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the AITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link AI information objects.

In order to receive analog information from outstation information object address (IOA) needs to be specified in the InfAddr attribute. Analog information is processed when received from oustation with any of the following ASDU types: 5 [M_ST_NA_1]; 6 [M_ST_TA_1]; 32 [M_ST_TB_1]; 9 [M_ME_NA_1]; 10 [M_ME_TA_1]; 34 [M_ME_TD_1]; 11 [M_ME_NB_1]; 12 [M_ME_TB_1]; 35 [M_ME_TE_1]; 13 [M_ME_NC_1]; 14 [M_ME_TC_1]; 36 [M_ME_TF_1]

Please see sample AITable group and AI element nodes below. There are 5 analog information objects defined with 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="-17.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4" TypeID="36"/>
     <AI Index="3" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Coeff="0.08" Deadband="8" Percent="3" Total="2"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" TypeID="36" Total="2" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 8.4 IEC60870-5-101/104 Master AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
InfAddr 1…16777215 n/a Information Object Address (IOA) of the AI object. This IOA will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Addresses don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 8.5 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. This attribute has a higher priority than IEC101ma and IEC104ma ASDUSettings.AIDeadband. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. This attribute has a higher priority than IEC101ma and IEC104ma ASDUSettings.AIPercent. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
TypeID See Table 8.6 transparent Use this ASDU type to send a AI object upstream, if transparent ASDUs are enabled in IEC101 or IEC104 Slave protocol instance with ASDUSettings.TranspTypes attribute. This ASDU type will be used to send object regardless of the received ASDU type. There is no default value, attribute must not be specified if not used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration. ASDU type received from outstation will be used to report object upstream if transparent ASDUs are enabled in Slave protocol instance with ASDUSettings.TranspTypes attribute.
Total 1…16777214 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and InfAddr values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

AI.qualifier

Table 8.5 IEC60870-5-101/104 Master AI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x
Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation enabled. New 0 value event will be generated internally following every:
/ event with a nonzero value received from outstation and
/ event with a nonzero value resulted from a deadband/percent or scaling processing.
Static AI object will be set to value 0, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated if an AI object is received from outstation with a ‘spontaneous’ Cause Of Transmission ([COT] = 3) or received value exceeds deadband/percent limit.
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time AI object is received from outstation regardless of the Cause Of Transmission. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this AI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from outstation
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from outstation
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Process analog value received from outstation in General Interrogation
xx1x.xxxx Ignore analog value received from outstation in General Interrogation
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original AI value and store original value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
x1xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original value, but store 0 value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 0;4 Any Bits reserved for future use

Tip

Note, all AI objects are internally stored and processed as ‘Short floating point’ values. If any other type needs to be reported to the upstream Master station, object is being converted just before it is sent.

DOTable group

DOTable group and its elements DO are used to define control commands that can be sent to outstation. Each DO element can be linked to DO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a control command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the control command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked DO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 8.7 and sends the command to outstation.
Please refer to the DOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DO information objects.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 5 control commands defined with 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x00" TypeID="45"/>
     <DO Index="1" InfAddr="2" qualifier="0x10" TypeID="46"/>
     <DO Index="2" InfAddr="3" qualifier="0x10" QOC="3"/>
     <DO Index="3" InfAddr="4" qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" InfAddr="1" qualifier="0x00" QOC="0" TypeID="46" Total="2" Name="CB command" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.
