9. IEC60870-5-103 Master

This section contains details on how to configure IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Each IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) instance must have XML configuration file where IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. This may be useful if identical set of IO objects is acquired from several IEDs.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IEC103ma_test.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in IEC103ma.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IEC103ma_test.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC60870-5-103 Master configuration file (e.g. ‘IEC103ma_test.xml’) must have a root node IEC103maConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
3 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable and DOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC103maConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC103ma" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4" date="2022-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="120" />
    <ASDUSettings SUthroughoutDST="1" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="240" INF="160"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="134" INF="148" MEA="0" Coeff="0.09" Percent="0.1"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" qualifier="0" FUN="240" INF="160" TypeID="0"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
</IEC103maConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable groups make up the IO object table of the IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables Table 9.12; Table 9.14 and Table 9.16 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC60870-5-103 controlling station (Master) instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <LinkSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <ASDUSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Broadcast … />
  <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings Flags="0x00"/>
Table 9.1 IEC60870-5-103 Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 9.2 for description.
Table 9.2 IEC60870-5-103 Master Link flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Link flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send variable and fixed length link layer messages as required (First byte of the variable link layer message is - 0x68 and fixed length message - 0x10).
xxxx.xxx1 Send only variable length link layer messages (First byte of the link layer message - 0x68).
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Use ‘Reset of remote link’ message to check if station is online. [Reset of remote link] message has function code 0x40.
xxxx.x1xx Use ‘Reset FCB’ message to check if station is online. [Reset FCB] message has function code 0x47. This message is defined only in IEC60870-5-103.
Bits 1;3…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" ControlLockTimer="20" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" OnlineGIDelay="10" />
Table 9.3 IEC60870-5-103 Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NoRespCount 1…255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)
DegradedRetries 0…255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
DegradedTimeout 0…232 - 1 600 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
ControlLockTimer 0…120 20 sec Control command lock timer is used to poll only one outstation for a configured number of seconds after sending a control command. All other outstations that share the same hardware channel (e.g. serial port) are temporary excluded from polling while ControlLockTimer operates. This feature enables to speed up reception of a control command feedback. ControlLockTimer can only be used if more than one outstation share the hardware channel. Value 0 disables control lock timer feature.
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)
OnlineGIDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec General Interrogation command will be delayed for a configured number of seconds after outstation goes online. This delay is designed to allow outstation to poll data after reset/power-on and before data is beeing requested by leandc application with a General Interrogation command.

ASDUSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of ASDUSettings element node.

Please see sample ASDUSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ASDUSettings InvalidEvent="1" IgnoreTimetags="1" SUthroughoutDST="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1" Flags="0x00" />
Table 9.4 IEC60870-5-103 Master ASDUSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InvalidEvent 0 1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will not be generated
1 DI/AI events with set Invalid [IV] bit will be generated
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no hysteresis, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.
SUthroughoutDST 0 0 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will not be set (‘0’). Time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages are adjusted based on a timezone selected for the current communication protocol instance. As it is impossible to distinguish between Standard time and Daylight Saving Time (DST) at the end of the DST (this is when clock is turned back one hour) all time-tags generated during the final hour of the DST are treated as Standard time. For example time-tag with 01:04:00 BST will be treated as 01:04:00 GMT. There is no issue at the begning of the DST (this is when clock is turned forward one hour).
1 Summer Time [SU] bit in the time-tag of outgoing messages will be set (‘1’) if the time-tag contains Daylight Saving Time (DST) (Summer Time). It is also expected that the peer station sets Summer Time [SU] bit in all time-tags containing DST. If the peer station doesn’t set the [SU] bit it is assumed that all time-tags contain Standard time.
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Various settings to enable customized data processing. See Table 9.5 for description.
Table 9.5 IEC60870-5-103 Master ASDU flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF ASDU flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Check Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be discarded.
xxx1.xxxx Ignore Test bit of the received Cause Of Transmission [COT]. DI/AI messages received with set test bit in the [COT] will be processed as if no test bit was set.
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Don’t generate DI position change event when positive command confirmation is received from outstation. DI event is generated only when received from oustation with Causes Of Transmission [COT]=1,9,11,12.
xx1x.xxxx Generate DI position change event when positive command confirmation is received from outstation. DI event is generated when command response with Cause Of Transmission [COT]=20 is received.
Bits 0…3;6…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 9.6 IEC60870-5-103 Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 9.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 9.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" />
Table 9.8 IEC60870-5-103 Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="Europe/Riga" />
Table 9.9 IEC60870-5-103 Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.

Broadcast

Broadcast common address of ASDU (CAA) usage for various commands can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Broadcast node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Broadcast GI="1" TimeSync="0" />
Table 9.10 IEC60870-5-103 Master Broadcast attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
GI 0 0 Send General Interrogation [C_IC_NA_1] commands with individual Common Addresses of ASDU (CAA)
1 Send General Interrogation [C_IC_NA_1] commands with broadcast Common Address of ASDU (CAA). Broadcast address is 255
TimeSync 0 0 Send Time Synchronization [C_CS_NA_1] commands with individual link and Common Addresses of ASDU (CAA)
1 Send Time Synchronization [C_CS_NA_1] commands with broadcast link and Common Address of ASDU (CAA). Broadcast address is 255

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic GI="600" TimeSync="0" />
Table 9.11 IEC60870-5-103 Master Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
GI 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic General Interrogation command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic General Interrogation command.
TimeSync 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic time synchronization command. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.

DITable group

DITable group and its elements DI are used to define DI information objects that contain status information received from IED. Each DI element can be linked to DI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining status information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives DI status information from IED and processes it based on settings in the Table 9.12.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked DI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the DITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DI information objects.

In order to receive status information from IED [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes.

Please see sample DITable group and DI element nodes below. There are 5 status information objects defined with 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00"/>
     <DI Index="1" FUN="1" INF="2" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DI Index="2" FUN="240" INF="55" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DI Index="3" FUN="240" INF="56" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0" InterDelay="10000" IndetDelay="0" OnDelay="0" OffDelay="0" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 9.12 IEC60870-5-103 Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
FUN 0…255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the DI object. This FUN will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
INF 0…255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the DI object. This INF will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 9.13 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
InterDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
IndetDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec ON position reporting delay in milliseconds. ON position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. OFF->ON->OFF->ON) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after ON position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec OFF position reporting delay in milliseconds. OFF position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. ON->OFF->ON->OFF) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after OFF position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and INF values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.Qualifier

Table 9.13 IEC60870-5-103 Master DI internal Qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3)
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x Additional ‘Zero’ DI event generation enabled. An OFF event will be internally generated following every sent DI ON event. Static DI object will be set to OFF value, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated only if a DI object state has changed
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time DI object is received from outstation. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this DI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from outstation
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from outstation
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 3;4;6 Any Bits reserved for future use

AITable group

AITable group and its elements AI are used to define AI information objects that contain analog information received from IED. Each AI element can be linked to AI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining analog information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives AI analog information from IED and processes it based on settings in the Table 9.14.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked AI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the AITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link AI information objects.

In order to receive an analog information from IED [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes. It also essential to select index of a particular measurement because IEC60870-5-103 station sends multiple measurands in one message. Index of a particular analog value is selected with MEA attribute.

Please see sample AITable group and AI element nodes below. There are 5 analog information objects defined with 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" FUN="1" INF="1" MEA="5" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="2" FUN="85" INF="83" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="-17.0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="3" FUN="105" INF="103" MEA="0" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="0.08" Total="2"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" FUN="85" INF="83" MEA="2" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" DIAndIndex="0" LogicValue="1" Total="2" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 9.14 IEC60870-5-103 Master AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
FUN 0…255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the AI object. This FUN will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
INF 0…255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the AI object. This INF will be used to receive object from downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
MEA 0…31 n/a Number of the analog value in the received measurement message. Use value 0 to select first measurement in the received message. Numbers don’t have to be arranged in an ascending order.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 9.15 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. This attribute has a higher priority than ASDUSettings.AIDeadband. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. This attribute has a higher priority than ASDUSettings.AIPercent. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
DIAndIndex 0…65534 n/a Index of the DI object to perform logical conjunction (AND function). Use value of the DI.Index attribute. Analog value will be stored in the database and event will be generated only if value of the DI object is the same as specified in LogicValue attribute. Attribute is optional and must not be specified in configuration if not used. There is no default value.
LogicValue 0…255 0 Value of the object used for logical conjunction/disjunction (AND/OR function). Please note all DI values have to be treated as DPIs (ON = 2; OFF = 1) if used for logic functions. Quality flags (e.g. [IV]) are not part of the logical processing, DI values are used regardless of state of the quality flags. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and MEA values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

AI.Qualifier

Table 9.15 IEC60870-5-103 Master AI internal Qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation disabled
xxxx.xx1x
Additional ‘Zero’ AI event generation enabled. New 0 value event will be generated internally following every:
/ event with a nonzero value received from outstation and
/ event with a nonzero value resulted from a deadband/percent or scaling processing.
Static AI object will be set to value 0, static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Event is generated if an AI object is received from outstation with a ‘spontaneous’ Cause Of Transmission ([COT] = 1) or received value exceeds deadband/percent limit.
xxxx.x1xx Event is generated every time AI object is received from outstation regardless of the Cause Of Transmission. Also invalid [IV] flag is automatically cleared when outstation goes online which ensures this AI object is always valid. This option is only used for backward compatibility.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original AI value and store original value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
x1xx.xxxx Process events received from outstation with their original value, but store 0 value in the static database. Static value is used when Slave protocol instance responds to an Interrogation or sends AI periodically.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 0;3;4;5 Any Bits reserved for future use

DOTable group

DOTable group and its elements DO are used to define control commands that can be sent to IED. Each DO element can be linked to DO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a control command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the control command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked DO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 9.16 and sends the command to IED.
Please refer to the DOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DO information objects.

In order to send a control command [FUNCTION TYPE] and [INFORMATION NUMBER] has to be specified in FUN and INF attributes.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 5 control commands defined with 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00"/>
     <DO Index="1" FUN="1" INF="2" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DO Index="2" FUN="240" INF="55" Qualifier="0x10"/>
     <DO Index="3" FUN="240" INF="56" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" FUN="1" INF="1" Qualifier="0x00" Total="2" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DO attributes

Table 9.16 IEC60870-5-103 Master DO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DO object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
FUN 0…255 n/a Function Type (FUN) of the DO object. This FUN will be used to send command to downstream outstation. Function types don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
INF 0…255 n/a Information Number (INF) of the DO object. This INF will be used to send command to downstream outstation. Information numbers don’t have to be arranged in ascending order.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 9.17 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and INF values without a need to create a DO node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DO.Qualifier

Table 9.17 IEC60870-5-103 Master DO internal Qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DO internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DO object will not be inverted
xxxx.xxx1 DO object will be inverted (OFF → ON; ON → OFF)
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DO is enabled, command will be sent to outstation
1xxx.xxxx DO is disabled, command will not be sent to outstation
Bits 1…6 Any Bits reserved for future use

10. Modbus Master

This section contains details on how to configure Modbus RTU/ASCII/TCP Master communication protocol instance. Each Modbus Master instance must have XML configuration file where Modbus messages, IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. It may be useful if multiple outstations have identical set of IO objects.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘Device_IO.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in Modbusma.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”Device_IO.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

Modbus Master configuration file (e.g. ‘Device_IO.xml’) must have a root object node ModbusmaConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
3 optional message configuration groups InitMessages; PollMessages and CtrlMessages;
4 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<ModbusmaConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/Modbusma" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="2.00" date="2022-03-19" time="12:00:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <LinkSettings Type="RTU" />
    <CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="3" DegradedTimeout="60" OfflineDelay="10" />
    <Hardcoded Type="BCAIIS8" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <InitMessages>
    <MSG InitMsg="1" Func="17" Data="0x00"/>
        …
  </InitMessages>
  <PollMessages>
    <MSG PollMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0002" Count="1"/>
        …
  </PollMessages>
  <CtrlMessages>
    <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x000A" Data="0x0000"/>
        …
  </CtrlMessages>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" Total="2"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Coeff="0.09" Deadband="0.1"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="1"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</ModbusmaConfig>

InitMessages; PollMessages; CtrlMessages groups contain Modbus messages used for communication to outstation. Messages don’t have to be defined if device type is specified in Hardcoded.Type attribute.

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table of the Modbus Master communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables Table 10.22; Table 10.26; Table 10.30 and Table 10.32 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the Modbus Master instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <LinkSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <Hardcoded … />
  <AppSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

LinkSettings

Link layer settings can be specified using attributes of LinkSettings element node.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings Frame="RTU" />
Table 10.1 Modbus Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Frame RTU or TCP RTU Frame format of the Modbus messages. Please note frame format of all protocol instances sharing the hardware node must be the same. UART; UDP and TCPCLIENT hardware nodes can be used for Modbus® RTU frame format. Only TCPCLIENT hardware node can be used for Modbus® TCP frame format.

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" />
Table 10.2 Modbus Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NoRespCount 1…255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)
DegradedRetries 0…255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
DegradedTimeout 0…232 - 1 300 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)

Please see sample Hardcoded node and all its attributes in the table below.

AppSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of AppSettings element node.

Please see sample AppSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AppSettings AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" RatioP0="2" ForwardGI="1" CmdRetries="0"/>
Table 10.5 Modbus Master AppSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
RatioP0 1…255 2 Polling ratio between Priority 0 and 1 messages. Default value 2 means Priority 1 message will be sent after every two Priority 0 messages.
ForwardGI 0 1 Ignore General Interrogation command received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Use General Interrogation command received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA) to poll DI/AI values by sending all defined Poll Messages one after another without checking message priorities.
CmdRetries 0..255 0 Number of repeated attempts to send control command if Exception is received from outstation or response timeout occurs (outstation doesn’t reply). Value 0 disables retries, command is considered failed and removed instantly if exception is received from outstation. However in case of a timeout, the command is repeated for the number of times specified in the NoRespCount attribute.

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 10.6 Modbus Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 10.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 10.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Timeout values can be specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" t35="0.01" />
Table 10.8 Modbus Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.
t35 0.00001…42949 0.01 sec Receive line idle detection timer (t3.5 in the communication standard). Incoming message analyze begins when idle in the receive line exceeds configured number of seconds.

TimeSettings

Time settings node is used to construct a message for synchronizing Modbus device’s clock. Modbus communication standard doesn’t define a specific function for the purpose of time synchronization, Write Multiple registers [16] is normally used. However encoding of the date and time in Modbus registers varies greatly from one device to another. Attributes of the TimeSettings node below enable to build a custom Modbus message where date and time values can be placed in any registers and each formatted in a different way.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings Func="0x10" Reg="0xAA55" Count="8" YearType="97" MonType="33" DomType="33" DowType="0" HourType="33" MinType="33" SecType="33" YearBitOffset="48" MonBitOffset="32" DomBitOffset="40" DowBitOffset="0" HourBitOffset="16" MinBitOffset="24" SecBitOffset="0"/>
Table 10.9 Modbus Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Func 16 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.
Reg 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to this register.
Count 0…63 1 Number of Modbus registers to write to outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
YearType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the year number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means year will be excluded from the message.
MonType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the month number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means month will be excluded from the message.
DomType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the day of month number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means day of month will be excluded from the message.
DowType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the day of week number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means day of week will be excluded from the message.
HourType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the hour number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means hour will be excluded from the message.
MinType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the minute number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means minute will be excluded from the message.
SecType See Table 10.11 0 Format of the second number in the outgoing message. Value 0 means second will be excluded from the message.
YearBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the year number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
MonBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the month number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
DomBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the day of month number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
DowBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the day of week number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
HourBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the hour number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
MinBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the minute number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.
SecBitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Shift the second number left by the specified number of bits. See Table 10.10 for examples.

Table below shows position of a sample value ‘85’ (0x55) in a Modbus message depending on the BitOffset.

Table 10.10 Modbus Master Bit Offset sample values
BitOffset Modbus Message
0 {01 10 … 00 55 00 00 …}
1 {01 10 … 00 AA 00 00 …}
2 {01 10 … 01 54 00 00 …}
3 {01 10 … 02 A8 00 00 …}
4 {01 10 … 05 50 00 00 …}
8 {01 10 … 55 00 00 00 …}
16 {01 10 … 00 00 00 55 …}
24 {01 10 … 00 00 55 00 …}
Table 10.11 Modbus Master Time variable encoding types
Type Description
0 Value is not used
33 Encode value as 16bit Unsigned Integer big endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 … 07 E2 …}
35 Encode value as 16bit Unsigned Integer little endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 … E2 07 …}
97 Encode value as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) big endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 … 20 18 …}
98 Encode value as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) little endian. For example value ‘2018’ will appear in Modbus message as follows: {01 10 … 18 20 …}
Other Value is not used

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic TimeSync="0" />
Table 10.12 Modbus Master Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeSync 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic time synchronization command. Time synchronization message must be defined in TimeSettings node. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.

InitMessages group

Group node InitMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages that are being sent to outstation during an initialization stage. Outstation replies can be checked against the pre-defined data to ensure correct outstation is connected during the initialization stage. Modbus Write messages can be used to change settings of the outstation during the initialization stage, if necessary.

Tip

InitMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required for initialization of hardcoded devices are set-up automatically.

Please see sample InitMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<InitMessages>
     <MSG InitMsg="1" Func="17" Data="0x00"/>
     <MSG InitMsg="2" Func="4" Reg="0x0003" Count="1" Data="0x00" />
</InitMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG InitMsg="1" Func="4" Reg="0x0100" Count="1" Data="0xAA BB CC DD 05 03" Flags="0x00" Name="Read Input Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

Init MSG attributes

Table 10.13 Modbus Master Initialization message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InitMsg 1…65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.
Func See Table 10.14 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.
File 1…65535 or 0x0001…0xFFFF 0x0001 Modbus Memory file number number. Attribute is used only for File Record messages Func=”20” or Func=”21”
Reg 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to or read from this register. See Table 10.14 to check if attribute is optional.
Count 0…63 1 Number of Modbus registers to read from outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted. Attribute is used only for read messages Func=”3” or Func=”4”
Data Up to 126 hexadecimal bytes 0x00…0xFF 0 Data to be written to outstation or expected in a reply from outstation. Data can be specified as hexadecimal values separated by whitespaces e.g. “AA BB CC DD 05 03” or a single hexadecimal number e.g. “0xAABBCCDD0503”. If writing / reading multiple Modbus registers first 2 data bytes will be written to / read from the base register specified in Reg attribute, next to 2 bytes base register + 1, etc.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Message flags to customize processing. See Table 10.15 for available flags. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Init MSG.Func

Table below shows supported values of the Func attribute and whether Reg attribute must be specified when particular Modbus function is used.

Table 10.14 Modbus Master Initialization message functions
Func Reg required Function Name
3 Yes [Read Holding Registers] message reads contents of one or more outstation registers. Number of registers to read is set by the Count attribute. Contents of the Data attribute will be compared to the data received from outstation. Initialization will not complete if received data doesn’t match.
4 Yes [Read Input Registers] message reads contents of one or more outstation registers. Number of registers to read is set by the Count attribute. Contents of the Data attribute will be compared to the data received from outstation. Initialization will not complete if received data doesn’t match.
5 Yes [Force Single Coil] message writes data to a single outstation register (2 bytes). Contents of the Data attribute will be written to outstation with this function. Initialization will not complete if exception is received (i.e. outstation rejects the write).
6 Yes [Preset Single Register] message writes data to a single outstation register (2 bytes). Contents of the Data attribute will be written to outstation with this function. Initialization will not complete if exception is received (i.e. outstation rejects the write).
16 Yes [Preset Multiple Registers] message writes data to multiple outstation registers (up to 126 bytes). Contents of the Data attribute will be written to outstation with this function. Initialization will not complete if exception is received (i.e. outstation rejects the write). Number of registers to write is determined by the length of the Data attribute.
17 No [Report Slave ID] message reads Modbus device ID. Contents of the Data attribute will be compared to the data received from outstation. Initialization will not complete if received data doesn’t match.
20 Yes [Read File Record] message reads one or more records organized in a file. Number of records to read is set by the Count attribute. File number is set by the File attribute. Contents of the Data attribute will be compared to the data received from outstation. Initialization will not complete if received data doesn’t match.
21 Yes [Write File Record] message writes one or more records to a file. Contents of the Data attribute will be written to outstation with this function. File number is set by the File attribute. Initialization will not complete if exception is received (i.e. outstation rejects the write). Number of records to write is determined by the length of the Data attribute.
Other — Function is not supported

Init MSG.Flags

Table 10.15 Modbus Initialization message flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Message flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Data received from outstation has to match contents of the Data attribute exactly
xxxx.xxx1 Data received from outstation has to contain contents of the Data attribute. This option is normally used with Report Server ID [17] message and enables to check only portion of the received reply. For example if Data=”41 42 43” (represents string “ABC”) a reply from outstation {01 17 08 41 42 43 20 56 31 2E 30 …} (represents string “ABC V1.0”) is considered valid.

PollMessages group

Group node PollMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages that are being sent to continuously poll outstation data. All defined messages are sent to outstation in a sequential order. Data received from outstation can be mapped using DI and AI nodes.

Tip

PollMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required to poll data from a hardcoded device are set-up automatically.

Please see sample PollMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<PollMessages>
     <MSG PollMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0055" Count="2" />
     <MSG PollMsg="2" Func="4" Reg="0x0003" Count="1" />
</PollMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG PollMsg="1" Func="4" Reg="0x0100" Count="1" Priority="0" Name="Read Input Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

Poll MSG attributes

Table 10.16 Modbus Master Poll message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
PollMsg 1…65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.
Func See Table 10.17 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.
Reg 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be read from this register.
Count 0…63 1 Number of Modbus registers to read from outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Priority 0 or 1 0 This attribute allows to assign different priorities to messages which means some messages will be sent to outstation more often than others. Priority 0 messages are sent more often than priority 1 messages. Polling ratio between priority 0 and 1 messages is controlled by RatioP0 attribute.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Poll MSG.Func

Table below shows supported values of the Func attribute.

Table 10.17 Modbus Master Poll message functions
Func Function Name
3 [Read Holding Registers]
4 [Read Input Registers]
Other Function is not supported

CtrlMessages group

Group node CtrlMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages for writing data to outstation. Use DO node to specify which control message has to be sent to outstation when command is received.

Tip

CtrlMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. Messages required to send data to a hardcoded device are set-up automatically.

Please see sample CtrlMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Modbus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0055" Type="1" />
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="16" Reg="0x0003" Data="0x0001" Type="0" />
</CtrlMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0100" Data="0x1122" Count="1" Type="0" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Name="Write Registers message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

Ctrl MSG attributes

Table 10.18 Modbus Master Control message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
CtrlMsg 1…65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.
Func See Table 10.19 n/a Modbus function number. Modbus function is mandatory for all messages.
Reg 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0 Modbus register number. Data will be written to or read from this register.
Data Up to 126 hexadecimal bytes 0x00…0xFF 0 Data to be written to outstation. Data can be specified as hexadecimal values separated by whitespaces e.g. “AA BB CC DD 05 03” or a single hexadecimal number e.g. “0xAABBCCDD0503”. If writing multiple Modbus registers first 2 data bytes will be written to the base register specified in Reg attribute, next to 2 bytes base register + 1, etc. See compatibility Table 10.21 to check how this attribute is used for different message types.
Count 0…63 1 Number of Modbus registers to read from outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted. Attribute is used only for read messages Func=”3” and Func=”4”
Type See Table 10.20 0 Select format of outgoing data. Attribute is optional only for read messages Func=”3” and Func=”4”
FollowCtrlMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the Control message that will be sent before this message. Current message will be sent after Control message with the identifier specified in this attribute is complete. Value 0 means this message is sent on its own and doesn’t follow any messages. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Ctrl MSG.Func

Table below shows supported values of the Func attribute and whether Count and Type attributes must be specified when particular Modbus function is used.

Table 10.19 Modbus Master Control message functions
Func Count required Type required Function Name
3 Yes No [Read Holding Registers] message reads contents of one or more outstation registers. Number of registers to read is set by the Count attribute.
4 Yes No [Read Input Registers] message reads contents of one or more outstation registers. Number of registers to read is set by the Count attribute.
5 No Yes [Force Single Coil] message writes data to a single outstation register (2 bytes).
6 No Yes [Preset Single Register] message writes data to a single outstation register (2 bytes).
16 No Yes [Preset Multiple Registers] message writes data to multiple outstation registers (up to 126 bytes). Number of registers to write is determined by the Data attribute.
Other — — Function is not supported

Ctrl MSG.Type

Table 10.20 Modbus Master Control message types
Type Description
0 Send contents of the MSG.Data attribute to outstation.
1
Set or Clear one bit in the initial data that’s position is specified by the DO.BitOffset attribute. Inversion enable Bit[0] in DO.Qualifier selects if the bit is going to be set or cleared.
Inversion disabled (Bit[0] = 0 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0x0000 and one bit will be set.
Inversion enabled (Bit[0] = 1 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0xFFFF and one bit will be cleared.
MSG.Data attribute is ignored.
This type can be used only for DO control messages, it is not supported for AO.
33 Encode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer big endian. For example value ‘65297’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … FF 11 …}
34 Encode data as 16bit Signed Integer big endian. For example value ‘-239’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … FF 11 …}
35 Encode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer little endian. For example value ‘65297’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … 11 FF …}
36 Encode data as 16bit Signed Integer little endian. For example value ‘-239’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … 11 FF …}
37 Encode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [3210]. For example value ‘65541’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 00 01 00 05 …}
38 Encode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [3210]. For example value ‘-65275’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … FF FF 01 05 …}
39 Encode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [1032]. For example value ‘327681’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 00 01 00 05 …}
40 Encode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [1032]. For example value ‘-65275’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 01 05 FF FF …}
41 Encode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [2301]. For example value ‘16778496’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 00 01 00 05 …}
42 Encode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [2301]. For example value ‘-64255’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … FF FF 01 05 …}
43 Encode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [0123]. For example value ‘83886336’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 00 01 00 05 …}
44 Encode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [0123]. For example value ‘-64255’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 01 05 FF FF …}
65 Encode data as Short floating point number byte order [3210]. For example value ‘2.001007’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 40 00 10 80 …}
66 Encode data as Short floating point number byte order [1032]. For example value ‘2.001007’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 10 80 40 00 …}
67 Encode data as Short floating point number byte order [2301]. For example value ‘2.001007’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 00 40 80 10 …}
68 Encode data as Short floating point number byte order [0123]. For example value ‘2.001007’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 10 … 80 10 00 40 …}
97 Encode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) big endian. For example value ‘1234’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … 12 34 …}
98 Encode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) little endian. For example value ‘3412’ will be encoded to Modbus message as {01 06 … 12 34 …}
Other Not used

Important

If read message (Func=”3” or Func=”4”) is used, received data will be decoded based on the Type attribute of the following/preceding write message. I.e. the same way as data would be encoded for the write message. Type attribute must not be used for read messages.

Compatibility

Table below shows compatibility between Func and Type attributes and whether Data attribute must be specified when particular message type is used.

Table 10.21 Modbus Master Control message attribute compatibility
Func Type Data Description
3;4 n/a n/a
Read message reads contents of the outstation register. Read message has 2 purposes depending on its relation to a write message:
1/ Read message is followed by a write message. In this case data read from outstation can be modified and sent to outstation with the following write message.
2/ Write message is followed by a read message. In this case data sent to outstation with a preceding write message can be verified with this read message.
Both options can be used in the same sequence, i.e. read-write-read(verify) sequence of messages is allowed.
5;6 0 Data to send Write message with contents of the Data attribute will be sent to outstation.
1 n/a
Type=”1” can be used only for DO control messages, it is not supported for AO.
One bit in the initial data, that’s position is specified by the DO.BitOffset attribute, will be set or cleared. Initial data value (before modifying the bit) can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or will be set up automatically depending on inversion enable Bit[0] in DO.Qualifier.
Inversion disabled (Bit[0] = 0 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0x0000 and one bit will be set.
Inversion enabled (Bit[0] = 1 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0xFFFF and one bit will be cleared.
33;34;35;36 Optional
Behavior depends on whether the message is used for DO or AO:
DO: ON command adds DO.Step attribute contents to the initial data value. OFF command subtracts DO.Step attribute contents from the initial data value. Initial data value can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or specified in the Data attribute e.g. Data=”0x0000”.
AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
Outgoing data will be encoded as a 16bit Integer, see Table 10.20 for details.
97;98 Optional
Behavior depends on whether the message is used for DO or AO:
DO: ON command adds DO.Step attribute contents to the initial data value. OFF command subtracts DO.Step attribute contents from the initial data value. Initial data value can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or specified in the Data attribute e.g. Data=”0x0000”.
AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
Outgoing data will be encoded as a 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD), see Table 10.20 for details.
16 0 Data to send Write message with contents of the Data attribute will be sent to outstation.
1 n/a
Type=”1” can be used only for DO control messages, it is not supported for AO.
One bit in the initial data, that’s position is specified by the DO.BitOffset attribute, will be set or cleared. Initial data value (before modifying the bit) can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or will be set up automatically depending on inversion enable Bit[0] in DO.Qualifier.
Inversion disabled (Bit[0] = 0 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0x0000 and one bit will be set.
Inversion enabled (Bit[0] = 1 in DO.Qualifier) initial data value will be 0xFFFF and one bit will be cleared.
33;34;35;36 Optional
Behavior depends on whether the message is used for DO or AO:
DO: ON command adds DO.Step attribute contents to the initial data value. OFF command subtracts DO.Step attribute contents from the initial data value. Initial data value can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or specified in the Data attribute e.g. Data=”0x0000”.
AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
Outgoing data will be encoded as a 16bit Integer, see Table 10.20 for details.
37;38;39;40;41;42;43;44 0x00000000
Behavior depends on whether the message is used for DO or AO:
DO: ON command adds DO.Step attribute contents to the initial data value. OFF command subtracts DO.Step attribute contents from the initial data value. Initial data value can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or specified in the Data attribute e.g. Data=”0x0000”.
AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
Outgoing data will be encoded as a 32bit Integer, see Table 10.20 for details.
Data attribute must always be present for these message types. Even if its contents are not used, the length of data (2 registers or 4 bytes) instructs Modbus master instance that 2 registers need to be written.
65;66;67;68 0x00000000
Behavior depends on whether the message is used for DO or AO:
DO: ON command adds DO.Step attribute contents to the initial data value. OFF command subtracts DO.Step attribute contents from the initial data value. Initial data value can either be received from outstation in a preceding read message or specified in the Data attribute e.g. Data=”0x0000”.
AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
Outgoing data will be encoded as a Short floating point number, see Table 10.20 for details.

97;98 Optional

AO: value received from upstream station will be written to outstation.
