Other — — Function is not supported

Tip

Please refer to sections DO samples and AO samples for configuration and Modbus message samples.

DITable group

DITable group and its elements DI are used to define DI information objects that contain status information received from outstation. Each DI element can be linked to DI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining status information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives DI status information from outstation and processes it based on settings in the Table 10.22.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked DI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the DITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DI information objects.

Tip

DITable group and DI nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. DI information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample DITable group and DI element nodes below. There are 5 status information objects defined with 4 DI element nodes.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" />
     <DI Index="1" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="1" Type="1" />
     <DI Index="2" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="2" Type="1" Qualifier="0x01"/>
     <DI Index="3" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="4" Type="1" Total="2"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Type="1" Qualifier="0" ChatterFilter="100" OnValues="0x01 0x02" OffValues="5,6" OnDelay="0" OffDelay="0" Total="1" Name="Input 1" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 10.22 Modbus Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
PollMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.PollMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
BitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Offset of the bit that carries status information. See Table 10.25 for examples of offset values. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
Type See Table 10.24 1 Select format of the received data. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 10.23 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ChatterFilter 1…65535 50 msec Chatter filter in milliseconds for Digital Inputs. State change of the digital input will be reported only if it remains stable for the period that exceeds configured filter. This attribute applies only to LEIODC series units.
OnValues 0…65535 or 0x00…0xFFFF (up to 32) n/a Values received from station will result in a DI state ON. The DI will have ON state, if a register data received from station matches one of the values specified in this attribute. Up to 32 values can be specified in decimal or hexadecimal notation separated by whitespaces or commas e.g. “2,3 0x05 0xf1”. Either OnValues or OffValues attribute must be specified if DI.Type=”5” is used. If OffValues attribute is not used, any value received from station that is not included in OnValues list will result in a DI state OFF. If OffValues attribute is used, any value received from station that is not included in either attributes will result in a DI state INTER.
OffValues 0…65535 or 0x00…0xFFFF (up to 32) n/a Values received from station will result in a DI state OFF. The DI will have OFF state, if a register data received from station matches one of the values specified in this attribute. Up to 32 values can be specified in decimal or hexadecimal notation separated by whitespaces or commas e.g. “2,3 0x05 0xf1” Either OnValues or OffValues attribute must be specified if DI.Type=”5” is used. If OnValues attribute is not used, any value received from station that is not included in OffValues list will result in a DI state ON. If OnValues attribute is used, any value received from station that is not included in either attributes will result in a DI state INTER.
OnDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec ON position reporting delay in milliseconds. ON position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. OFF->ON->OFF->ON) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after ON position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec OFF position reporting delay in milliseconds. OFF position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. ON->OFF->ON->OFF) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after OFF position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and BitOffset values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1)
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 1..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

AITable group

AITable group and its elements AI are used to define AI information objects that contain analog information received from outstation. Each AI element can be linked to AI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining analog information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives AI analog information from outstation and processes it based on settings in the Table 10.26.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked AI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the AITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link AI information objects.

Tip

AITable group and AI nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. AI information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample AITable group and AI element nodes below. There are 5 analog information objects defined with 4 AI element nodes.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="1" Type="33" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="2" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="2" Type="65" Coeff="-17.0" Percent="1.4"/>
     <AI Index="3" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="4" Type="33" Coeff="0.08" Total="2"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" RegOffset="0" Type="33" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" Total="1" Name="Voltage" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 10.26 Modbus Master AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
PollMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.PollMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
RegOffset 0…63 or 0x00…0x3F 0 Offset of the register to read the analog information from. See Table 10.29 for examples of offset values. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
Type See Table 10.28 33 Select format of the received data. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 10.27 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIDeadband. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIPercent. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and RegOffset values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

AI.Type

Table 10.28 Modbus Master AI decode types
Type Description
0 Not used
33 Decode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … FF 11 …} will be decoded as ‘65297’
34 Decode data as 16bit Signed Integer big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … FF 11 …} will be decoded as ‘-239’
35 Decode data as 16bit Unsigned Integer little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 11 FF …} will be decoded as ‘65297’
36 Decode data as 16bit Signed Integer little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 11 FF …} will be decoded as ‘-239’
37 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [3210]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 00 01 00 05 …} will be decoded as ‘65541’
38 Decode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [3210]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … FF FF 01 05 …} will be decoded as ‘-65275’
39 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [1032]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 00 01 00 05 …} will be decoded as ‘327681’
40 Decode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [1032]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 01 05 FF FF …} will be decoded as ‘-65275’
41 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [2301]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 00 01 00 05 …} will be decoded as ‘16778496’
42 Decode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [2301]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … FF FF 01 05 …} will be decoded as ‘-64255’
43 Decode data as 32bit Unsigned Integer byte order [0123]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 00 01 00 05 …} will be decoded as ‘83886336’
44 Decode data as 32bit Signed Integer byte order [0123]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 01 05 FF FF …} will be decoded as ‘-64255’
65 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [3210]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 40 00 10 80 …} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
66 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [1032]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 10 80 40 00 …} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
67 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [2301]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 00 40 80 10 …} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
68 Decode data as Short floating point number byte order [0123]. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 80 10 00 40 …} will be decoded as ‘2.001007’
97 Decode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) big endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 12 34 …} will be decoded as ‘1234’
98 Decode data as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal (BCD) little endian. For example received Modbus data {01 04 … 12 34 …} will be decoded as ‘3412’
Other Not used

Table below shows position of a sample value ‘341’ (0x0155) in a Modbus message and the RegOffset required to read this value.

Table 10.29 Modbus Master Register Offset sample values
RegOffset Modbus Message
0 {01 04 … 01 55 00 00 …}
1 {01 04 … 00 00 01 55 …}

DOTable group

DOTable group and its elements DO are used to define control commands that can be sent to outstation. Each DO element can be linked to DO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a control command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the control command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked DO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 10.30 and sends the command to outstation.
Please refer to the DOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DO information objects.

Tip

DOTable group and DO nodes are optional if Hardcoded.Type is used. DO information objects are initialized automatically for hardcoded devices.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 5 control commands defined with 4 DO element nodes.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0"/>
     <DO Index="1" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="1"/>
     <DO Index="2" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="2" Qualifier="0x01"/>
     <DO Index="3" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="4" Total="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Qualifier="0x00" PulseDuration="500" Step="1" Total="1" Name="Output 1" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DO attributes

Table 10.30 Modbus Master DO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DO object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
CtrlMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the control message that is used to send command to outstation. Use value of the MSG.CtrlMsg attribute. Value 0 means no Control message is selected. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
BitOffset 0…1023 or 0x00…0x3FF 0 Offset of the bit that is to send control. See Table 10.25 for examples of offset values. Attribute is optional only if Hardcoded.Type is used.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 10.31 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
PulseDuration 1…65535 1500 msec Digital output pulse duration in milliseconds. Digital output will be activated when command is received and automatically released after configured number of milliseconds. This attribute applies only to LEIODC series units.
Step 0 or 1.18×10-38 … 3.4×1038 1 Step value to add to/subtract from initial data value. Contents of this attribute will be mathematically added to (if ON command is received from upstream station) or subtracted from (if OFF command is received from upstream station) initial data value and the result will be sent to outstation. Initial data can either be read from outstation with a read message or contents of the MSG.Data attribute can be used. See compatibility Table 10.21 to check how this attribute is used for different control message types.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and BitOffset values without a need to create a DO node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DO.Qualifier

Table 10.31 Modbus Master DO internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DO internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DO object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0)
xxxx.xxx1 DO object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1)
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DO is enabled, command will be sent to outstation
1xxx.xxxx DO is disabled, command will not be sent to outstation
Bits 1..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

DO samples

Example 1:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”1”. DO inversion is not enabled, which means Bit 0 of the initial data value 0x0000 will be set. The resulting data 0x0001 will be written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="0" Name="DO sets Bit 0"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 06 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 00 01 ...

Example 2:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”1”. DO inversion is enabled, which means Bit 1 of the initial data value 0xFFFF will be cleared. The resulting data 0xFFFD will be written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="1" Qualifier="0x01" Name="DO clears Bit 1"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 06 03 05 FF FD ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 FF FD ...

Example 3:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”1” that follows a [Read Holding Registers] message. Initial data will be read from outstation before modifying the bit. Data read from outstation is 0xAA00 in this example. DO inversion is not enabled, which means Bit 7 of the initial data value 0xAA00 will be set. The resulting data 0xAA80 will be written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" Name="Read register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="1" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" BitOffset="7" Name="DO sets Bit 7"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 AA 00 ...
COMM <- 01 06 03 05 AA 80 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 AA 80 ...

Example 4:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”33” that follows a [Read Holding Registers] message. Initial data will be read from outstation before adding/subtracting step value. Data read from outstation 0xAA00 in this example will be decoded as 16bit Unsigned Integer ‘43520’. If DO ON command is received, step value ‘4’ will be added to ‘43520’. The result ‘43524’ will be encoded as 16bit Unsigned Integer 0xAA04 and written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" Name="Read register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="33" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Step="4" Name="DO ON adds 4, DO OFF subtracts 4"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 AA 00 ...
COMM <- 01 06 03 05 AA 04 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 AA 04 ...

Example 5:

Configuration below has a [Preset Multiple Registers] message with MSG.Type=”37” that follows a [Read Holding Registers] message. Initial data will be read from outstation before adding/subtracting step value. Data read from outstation 0x0000AA00 in this example will be decoded as 32bit Unsigned Integer ‘43520’. If DO OFF command is received, step value ‘4’ will be subtracted from ‘43520’. The result ‘43516’ will be encoded as 32bit Unsigned Integer 0x0000A9FC and written to outstation registers 0x0305 and 0x0306. Please note MSG.Data attribute must always be present for messasge types that expect to write more than one Modbus register (more than 2 bytes).

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="2" Name="Read registers 0x0305 and 0x0306"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="16" Reg="0x0305" Data="0x00000000" Type="37" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write registers 0x0305 and 0x0306"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Step="4" Name="DO ON adds 4, DO OFF subtracts 4"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 02 ...
COMM -> 01 03 04 00 00 AA 00 ...
COMM <- 01 10 03 05 00 02 04 00 00 A9 FC ...
COMM -> 01 10 03 05 00 02 ...

Example 6:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”0” which is followed by a [Read Holding Registers] message. Contents of the MSG.Data attribute will be written to outstation register 0x0305. Read message will be sent afterwards in order to verify the written data. Value 0xAA55 is read from outstation in this example which matches the written data. Positive command termination will be generated in this case. If data received from outstation in a read message doesn’t match written data, negative command termination will be generated.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="0" Data="0xAA55" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Read and Verify register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Name="DO writes constant data"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 06 03 05 AA 55 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 AA 55 ...
COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 AA 55 ...

Example 7:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”97” which is preceded and followed by [Read Holding Registers] messages. Initial data will be read from outstation before adding/subtracting step value. Data read from outstation 0x0198 in this example will be decoded as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal ‘198’. If DO ON command is received, step value ‘15’ will be added to ‘198’. The result ‘213’ will be encoded as 16bit Binary Coded Decimal 0x0213 and written to outstation register 0x0305. Read message will be sent afterwards in order to verify the written data. Value 0x0213 is read from outstation in this example which matches the written data. Positive command termination will be generated in this case. If data received from outstation in a read message doesn’t match written data, negative command termination will be generated.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" Name="Read register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="97" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="3" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Name="Read and Verify register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Step="15" Name="DO ON adds 15, DO OFF subtracts 15"/>
</DOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 01 98 ...
COMM <- 01 06 03 05 02 13 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 02 13 ...
COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 02 13 ...

AOTable group

AOTable group and its elements AO are used to define setpoint commands that can be sent to outstation. Each AO element can be linked to AO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a setpoint command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the setpoint command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked AO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 10.32 and sends the command to outstation.
Please refer to the AOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link AO information objects.

Please see sample AOTable group and AO element nodes below. There are 4 setpoint commands defined with 4 AO element nodes.

<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="1"/>
     <AO Index="1" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="*1"/>
     <AO Index="2" CtrlMsg="1" Qualifier="0x01" />
     <AO Index="3" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="4.2"/>
</AOTable>

Please see sample AO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Qualifier="0x00" Coeff="1.2" Name="Regulate 1" />

Tip

Attributes of the AO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AO attributes

Table 10.32 Modbus Master AO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AO object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
CtrlMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the control message that is used to send command to outstation. Use value of the MSG.CtrlMsg attribute. Value 0 means no Control message is selected.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 10.33 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the setpoint value before sending to outstation. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

AO.Qualifier

Table 10.33 Modbus Master AO internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF AO internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Send AO value to outstation without changes
xxxx.xxx1 Add/Subtract AO value to the value received from outstation. In order to use this functionality current register value must be read from outstation with Func=”3” or Func=”4” message. AO command value received from upstream station will then be added to the register contents received from outstation and the result (sum) will be sent to outstation.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Send AO value to outstation without changes
xxxx.xx1x Multiply AO value to the value received from outstation. In order to use this functionality current register value must be read from outstation with Func=”3” or Func=”4” message. Register contents received from outstation will then be multiplied by the AO command value received from upstream station and the result (product) will be sent to outstation.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AO is enabled, command will be sent to outstation
1xxx.xxxx AO is disabled, command will not be sent to outstation
Bits 2..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

AO samples

Example 1:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”33”. If a setpoint value e.g. ‘516’ is received from upstream station, it will be encoded as 16bit Unsigned Integer 0x0204 and written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="33" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Name="AO as 16bit Integer"/>
</AOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 06 03 05 02 04 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 02 04 ...

Example 2:

Configuration below has a [Preset Multiple Registers] message with MSG.Type=”37”. If a setpoint value e.g. ‘516’ is received from upstream station, it will be multiplied by coefficeint ‘2.5’ first. The result ‘1290’ will be encoded as 32bit Unsigned Integer 0x0000050A and written to outstation registers 0x0305 and 0x0306. Please note MSG.Data attribute must always be present for messasge types that expect to write more than one Modbus register (more than 2 bytes).

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="16" Reg="0x0305" Data="0x00000000" Type="37" Name="Write registers 0x0305 and 0x0306"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="2.5" Name="AO as 32bit Integer"/>
</AOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 10 03 05 00 02 04 00 00 05 0A ...
COMM -> 01 10 03 05 00 02 ...

Example 3:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”35” that follows a [Read Holding Registers] message. A setpoint value received from upstream station will be added to initial data value received from outstation, because Add/Subtract bit is enabled Qualifier=”0x01”. Data read from outstation 0x0602 in this example will be decoded as 16bit Unsigned Integer ‘518’. If a setpoint value e.g. ‘5’ is received from upstream station, it will be added to ‘518’. The result ‘523’ will be encoded as 16bit Unsigned Integer 0x0B02 and written to outstation register 0x0305.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" Name="Read register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="35" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Qualifier="0x01" Name="AO add to 16bit Integer"/>
</AOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 06 02 ...
COMM <- 01 06 03 05 0B 02 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 0B 02 ...

Example 4:

Configuration below has a [Preset Multiple Registers] message with MSG.Type=”65” which is followed by a [Read Holding Registers] message. If a setpoint value e.g. ‘3.4’ is received from upstream station, it will be encoded as Short floating point number 0x4059999A and written to outstation registers 0x0305 and 0x0306. Read message will be sent afterwards in order to verify the written data. Value 0x4059999A is read from outstation in this example which matches the written data. Positive command termination will be generated in this case. If data received from outstation in a read message doesn’t match written data, negative command termination will be generated. Please note MSG.Data attribute must always be present for messasge types that expect to write more than one Modbus register (more than 2 bytes).

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="16" Reg="0x0305" Data="0x00000000" Type="65" Name="Write registers 0x0305 and 0x0306"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="2" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Read and Verify registers 0x0305 and 0x0306"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Name="AO as Short floating point number"/>
</AOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 10 03 05 00 02 04 40 59 99 9A ...
COMM -> 01 10 03 05 00 02 ...
COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 02 ...
COMM -> 01 03 04 40 59 99 9A ...

Example 5:

Configuration below has a [Preset Single Register] message with MSG.Type=”34” which is preceded and followed by [Read Holding Registers] messages. A setpoint value received from upstream station will be added to initial data value received from outstation, because Add/Subtract bit is enabled Qualifier=”0x01”. Data read from outstation 0xFFFE in this example will be decoded as 16bit Signed Integer ‘-2’. If a setpoint value e.g. ‘6’ is received from upstream station, it will be added to ‘-2’. The result ‘4’ will be encoded as 16bit Signed Integer 0x0004 and written to outstation register 0x0305. Read message will be sent afterwards in order to verify the written data. Value 0x0004 is read from outstation in this example which matches the written data. Positive command termination will be generated in this case. If data received from outstation in a read message doesn’t match written data, negative command termination will be generated.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" Name="Read register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Func="6" Reg="0x0305" Type="34" FollowCtrlMsg="1" Name="Write register 0x0305"/>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="3" Func="3" Reg="0x0305" Count="1" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Name="Read and Verify register 0x0305"/>
</CtrlMessages>
<AOTable>
     <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Qualifier="0x01" Name="AO add to 16bit Integer"/>
</AOTable>

Modbus RTU communication to outstation may contain the following:

COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 FF FE ...
COMM <- 01 06 03 05 00 04 ...
COMM -> 01 06 03 05 00 04 ...
COMM <- 01 03 03 05 00 01 ...
COMM -> 01 03 02 00 04 ...

11. Spabus Master

This section contains details on how to configure Spabus Master communication protocol instance. Each Spabus Master instance must have XML configuration file where Spabus messages, IO object table and additional protocol-related settings are stored. One XML file can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. It may be useful if multiple IEDs have identical set of IO objects.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘IED1.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in Spabusma.XMLpath attribute of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IED1.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

Spabus Master configuration file (e.g. ‘IED1.xml’) must have a root node SpabusmaConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
2 optional message configuration groups PollMessages and CtrlMessages;
4 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<SpabusmaConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/spabusma" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="2.00" date="2022-04-01" time="12:00:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="3" DegradedTimeout="60" OfflineDelay="10" />
    <AppSettings RatioP0="2" RatioL="3" DnumRangeMax="16" ChannelRangeMax="8" />
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <PollMessages>
    <MSG PollMsg="1" Channel="10" Category="V" DataNumber="1/4" Priority="0"/>
        …
  </PollMessages>
  <CtrlMessages>
    <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Channel="10" Category="V" DataNumber="1" Value="5"/>
        …
  </CtrlMessages>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" Request="120V1" OnValue="2" OffValue="1" Total="2"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" PollMsg="1" Coeff="0.09" Deadband="0.1"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" OnRequest="120V4" OffRequest="120V5" OnValue="1" OffValue="2"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Index="0" CtrlMsg="1" Coeff="1"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</SpabusmaConfig>

PollMessages; CtrlMessages groups contain Spabus messages used for communication to outstation. PollMessages don’t have to be defined if DI.Request and AI.Request attributes are used. CtrlMessages don’t have to be defined if DO.OnCtrlMsg and DO.OffCtrlMsg attributes are used.

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table of the Spabus Master communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables Table 11.14; Table 11.16; Table 11.18 and Table 11.20 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the Spabus Master instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <LinkSettings … />
  <CommsSettings … />
  <AppSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <TimeSettings … />
  <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All elements are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

LinkSettings

Spabus message settings can be specified using attributes of the LinkSettings element.

Please see sample LinkSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<LinkSettings Flags="0x00" />
Table 11.1 Spabus Master LinkSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Miscellaneous Spabus message settings. See Table 11.2 for description.
Table 11.2 Message format flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Message format flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Include channel number in Event request mesage R0L (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 Omit channel number from Event request mesage RL
Bits 1…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings NoRespCount="5" DegradedRetries="5" DegradedTimeout="600" ControlLockTimer="30" OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" />
Table 11.3 Spabus Master CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
NoRespCount 1…255 5 retries Outstation no-response counter. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation fails to reply to a configured number of subsequent requests. Station status will be changed to OFFLINE instantly, unless additional delay is configured in OfflineDelay attribute. (default 5 retries - outgoing message will be retried 5 times before station status is changed to OFFLINE)
DegradedRetries 0…255 5 retries Outgoing message retries before activating DegradedTimeout. Outstation will be temporarily excluded from polling if it fails to reply to a configured number of requests. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
DegradedTimeout 0…232 - 1 300 sec Degraded timeout in seconds. Outstation is excluded from polling for a configured number of seconds if it has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in DegradedRetries attribute. Value 0 disables degraded timeout functionality.
ControlLockTimer 0…120 20 sec Control command lock timer is used to poll only one outstation for a configured number of seconds after sending a control command. All other outstations that share the same hardware channel (e.g. serial port) are temporary excluded from polling while ControlLockTimer operates. This feature enables to speed up reception of a control command feedback. ControlLockTimer can only be used if more than one outstation share the hardware channel. Value 0 disables control lock timer feature.
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated only after outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount attribute. Application example: if this delay is 10, status will be changed to OFFLINE when outstation has failed to reply to a number of requests configured in NoRespCount plus 10 second delay
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)

AppSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of the AppSettings element.

Please see sample AppSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AppSettings IgnoreTimetags="0" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" RatioP0="2" RatioL="3" DnumRangeMax="16" ChannelRangeMax="8" ForwardGI="1" TimetagFBrange="2" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 11.4 Spabus Master AppSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation. DI.Qualifier attribute can be used to disable timetag processing for each DI.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
RatioP0 1…255 2 Polling ratio between Priority 0 and 1 messages. Default value 2 means Priority 1 message will be sent after every two Priority 0 messages.
RatioL 1…255 3 Polling ratio between poll messages and Event request R0L. Default value 3 means Event request R0L will be sent after every three poll messages. This attribute doesn’t take into account message Priority value, all poll messages are being accounted together i.e. if RatioP0 attribute has a default value 2, the poll sequence will be: two Priority 0 messages, one Priority 1 message and Event request R0L. If IED response conatains any Events, the R0L request will be repeated immediately until all Events are read from IED. Only then normal Priority 0 and 1 polling will resume.
DnumRangeMax 1…255 16 Maximal number of SPA data numbers that can be consolidated in one request message. Consider situation when one DI has Request=”10V2” and another DI has Request=”10V3”. These 2 separate messages can be consolidated into a single Request=”10V2/3”. Default value 16 ensures no more than 16 SPA data numbers are requested in one message. Data number consolidation applies only to messages created automatically from DI.Request and AI.Request attributes. Messages defined within PollMessages group will not be consolidated.
ChannelRangeMax 1…255 8 Maximal number of SPA channel numbers that can be consolidated in one request message. Consider situation when one DI has Request=”10V2” and another DI has Request=”11V2”. These 2 separate messages can be consolidated into a single Request=”10/11V2”. Default value 8 ensures no more than 8 SPA channel numbers are requested in one message. Channel number consolidation applies only to messages created automatically from DI.Request and AI.Request attributes. Messages defined within PollMessages group will not be consolidated.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t use General Interrogation command received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA) to request DI values. This option only applies if DI data values are requested only during IED initialization i.e. Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.
1 Use General Interrogation command received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA) to request DI values. This option only applies if DI data values are requested only during IED initialization i.e. Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.
TimetagFBrange 0…30 1 sec Received event time-tag minute forward-backward adjustment range. If the time-tag of the event received from IED is closer to full minute (0 secs) than the specified range in seconds, the minute value of the resulting timestamp will be automatically adjusted. This functionality ensures correct minute value is attached to the SPA time-tag, as it carries only seconds and milliseconds, if event arrived late. Minute, hour, day, month and year values are taken from internal system time. If the time value of the event time-tag is just before a full minute (e.g. sec.msec = 59:580) and there is a delay in communication channel, there is a chance the event is received only after internal minute has already changed (e.g. min:sec.msec = 30:01.000). This will lead to incorrect minute (min = 30) being applied to the resulting timestamp, although it is most likely the event was generated before the minute change (e.g. generated at min:sec.msec = 29:59.580). TimetagFBrange attribute ensures the minute of the resulting timestamp is automatically decremented if the time of the received time-tag falls within a forward-backward adjustment range and internal minute has recently changed. Similar functionality applies if the time of the received time-tag appears to be in the future, but the internal minute hasn’t changed yet. In this case minute of the resulting timestamp is automatically incremented. Default value 1 will adjust received event time-tags sec.msec = 59.000…00.999 if they arrive when internal time is min:sec.msec = 29:59.000…30:00.999
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Settings to customize data polling algorithm. See Table 11.5 for description.
Table 11.5 Polling algorithm flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Application flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Request DI data values continuously (default value).
xxxx.xxx1 Request DI data values only on startup during IED initialization i.e. whenever IED goes online after a communication loss. Event buffer and AI values will be polled continuously. DI position changes are based on received Events. This setting only applies to DI requests created automatically i.e. DI.Request attribute is used and DI.PollMsg attribute is not used. DI also must have OnEvent and OffEvent attributes in order for the request to be excluded from continuous polling. If these attributes are missing or Bit[4] = 1 in DI.Qualifier, the particular DI request will be sent continuously.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Don’t send clear Event buffer WC message on startup. (default value)
xxxx.xx1x Always send clear Event buffer WC message when establishing communication to IED. Clear Event buffer will be the first message sent to IED on startup and whenever IED goes online after a communication loss.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Use initialization state.
xxxx.x1xx Don’t use initialization state. This option is only used for testing.
Bits 3…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 11.6 Spabus Master ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 11.7 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 11.7 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" />
Table 11.8 Spabus Master Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.

TimeSettings

Time settings of the communication protocol instance are specified in this node.

Please see sample TimeSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TimeSettings TimeZone="UTC" Flags="0x00"/>
Table 11.9 Spabus Master TimeSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of incoming and outgoing messages assuming the peer station operates in the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Message time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Miscellaneous time synchronization settings. See Table 11.10 for description.
Table 11.10 Time Synchronization flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Time synchronization flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Include leading zeros to Year, Month, Day, Hour and Minute values of Date WD synchronization message (default value). Sample outgoing date string WD:12-03-02 12.05
xxxx.xxx1 Omit leading zeros from Year, Month, Day, Hour and Minute values of Date WD synchronization message. Sample outgoing date string WD:12-3-2 12.5
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Include leading zeros to Second and Millisecond values of Time WT and Date WD messages (default value). Sample outgoing time string WT:03.034
xxxx.xx1x Omit leading zeros from Second and Millisecond values of Time WT and Date WD messages. Sample outgoing time string WT:3.34
Bits 2…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic TimeSync="0" PreciseSync="0" DIPoll="120"/>
Table 11.11 Spabus Master Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
TimeSync 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic time synchronization command. This attribute enables Date WD synchronization message. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.
PreciseSync 0…232 - 1 0 sec Precise Time synchronization command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic precise time synchronization command. This attribute enables Time WT synchronization message. Time Synchronization commands are only sent at predefined intervals. This means station Online/Offline status change doesn’t trigger time synchronization command.
DIPoll 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic polling of DI values in seconds. This setting only applies if DI values are excluded from continuous polling (are requested only during IED initialization) with Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.

PollMessages group

Group node PollMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages that are being sent to continuously poll outstation data. All defined messages are sent to outstation in a sequential order. Data received from outstation can be mapped using DI and AI nodes.

Tip

PollMessages group and MSG nodes are optional if DI.Request and AI.Request attributes are used. In this case messages required to poll data will be created automatically.

Please see sample PollMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 3 Spabus messages configured using 3 MSG element nodes.

<PollMessages>
     <MSG PollMsg="1" Channel="120" Category="V" DataNumber="1/4" Priority="0"/>
     <MSG PollMsg="2" Channel="120/121" Category="V" DataNumber="1" Priority="0"/>
     <MSG PollMsg="3" Channel="10" Category="I" DataNumber="15" Priority="1"/>
</PollMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG PollMsg="1" Channel="120" Category="V" DataNumber="1/4" Priority="0" Name="CB position message" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

Poll MSG attributes

Table 11.12 Spabus Master Poll message attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
PollMsg 1…65534 n/a This is a unique identifier of the message. Message numbering must start with 1 and messages must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place to prevent insertion of a new message because it affects object mapping to messages.
Channel 0…999 or 0…999/1…999 n/a Spabus channel number. This attribute supports channel range e.g. 10/12, where 10 is the first and 12 is the last channel requested. Range can be specified only in one of the attributes Channel or DataNumber. Therefore if channel range is used DataNumber attribute can’t have a range.
Category I, M, O, S, V n/a Spabus Category value.
DataNumber 1…999999 or 1…999999/1…999999 n/a Spabus data number. This attribute supports data number range e.g. 10/12, where 10 is the first and 12 is the last data number requested. Range can be specified only in one of the attributes Channel or DataNumber. Therefore if data number range is used Channel attribute can’t have a range.
Priority 0 or 1 0 This attribute allows to assign different priorities to messages which means some messages will be sent to outstation more often than others. Priority 0 messages are sent more often than priority 1 messages. Polling ratio between priority 0 and 1 messages is controlled by RatioP0 attribute.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

CtrlMessages group

Group node CtrlMessages and child element nodes MSG contain messages for writing data to outstation. Use DO node to specify which control message has to be sent to outstation when command is received.

Tip

CtrlMessages group and MSG nodes are optional DO.OnRequest and DO.OffRequest attributes are used. In this case messages required to send data will be created automatically.

Please see sample CtrlMessages group and MSG child element nodes below. There are 2 Spabus messages configured using 2 MSG element nodes.

<CtrlMessages>
     <MSG CtrlMsg="1" Channel="120" Category="V" DataNumber="4" />
     <MSG CtrlMsg="2" Channel="120" Category="V" DataNumber="5" />
</CtrlMessages>

Please see sample MSG node and all its attributes in the table below.

<MSG CtrlMsg="1" Channel="120" Category="V" DataNumber="4" Value="11" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Name="CB Open" />

Tip

Attributes of the MSG element node can be arranged in any order, it will not affect XML file validation.

Channel 0…999 n/a Spabus channel number. This attribute does not support channel range e.g. 10/12.

DITable group

DITable group and its elements DI are used to define DI information objects that contain status information received from IED. Each DI element can be linked to DI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining status information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives DI status information from IED and processes it based on settings in the Table 11.14.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked DI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the DITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DI information objects.

Please see sample DITable group and DI elements below. There are 5 status information objects defined with 4 DI elements.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" DataPos="1" OnValue="2" OffValue="1" Total="2"/>
     <DI Index="2" Request="120V1" OnValue="2" OffValue="1" IndetValue="3" InterDelay="0"/>
     <DI Index="3" Request="10V1/2" DataPos="1/2 OnValue="0/1" OffValue="1/0"/>
     <DI Index="4" Request="10/11V1" DataPos="1/2 OnValue="0/1" OffValue="1/0"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" PollMsg="1" DataPos="1" Request="120V1" Qualifier="0x00" OnValues="2" OffValues="1" InterValue="0" IndetValue="3" OnEvent="10E1" OffEvent="10E2" InterEvent="10E0" IndetEvent="10E3" InterDelay="0" IndetDelay="0" OnDelay="0" OffDelay="0" Total="1" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 11.14 Spabus Master DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
PollMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the message that is used to poll data from outstation. Use value of the MSG.PollMsg attribute. Value 0 means no poll message is selected, Request attribute must be used to specify the message. This attribute has higher priority than Request, if both attributes are specified PollMsg will be used.
DataPos 1…16 or 1…16/1…16 1 Data position in the received message. This attribute supports 2 positions e.g. 1/2 for double status information that is reported with 2 different Spabus channel or data numbers.
Request see description n/a
Spabus request to poll data from outstation. Attribute has the following format [Channel][Category][Data Number].
Range of [Channel] values 0..999
[Category] is one of I, M, O, S, V
Range of [Data Number] values 1..999999
This attribute supports channel and data number ranges for double status information that is reported with 2 different Spabus channels or data numbers e.g. [First Channel]/[Last Channel][Category][Data Number] or [Channel][Category][First Data Number]/[Last Data Number]
Examples Request=”15I2” or Request=”15/16I2” or Request=”15I2/4”
Only one range can be used at a time i.e. either channel range or data number range.
Attribute is optional if PollMsg is used.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 11.15 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnValues 0…65535 or 0…65535/0…65535 1
Received data value that corresponds to ON position. Data can be specified in any of the following ways:
> Single data value OnValues=”1”;
> 2 data values for double status information that is reported with 2 different Spabus channel or data numbers e.g. OnValues=”0/1”;
> A list of up to 32 values separated by commas e.g. OnValues=”2,3,7”. Any list value received from IED will result in DI ON position;
> Wildcard OnValues=”*” means any value will be accepted.
Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
OffValues 0…65535 or 0…65535/0…65535 0
Received data value that corresponds to OFF position. Data can be specified in any of the following ways:
> Single data value OffValues=”1”;
> 2 data values for double status information that is reported with 2 different Spabus channel or data numbers e.g. OffValues=”0/1”;
> A list of up to 32 values separated by commas e.g. OffValues=”2,3,7”. Any list value received from IED will result in DI OFF position;
> Wildcard OffValues=”*” means any value will be accepted.
Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
InterValue 0…65535 0 Received data value that corresponds to Intermediate position. This attribute doesn’t support 2 data values. The same specified value will be used for both data values if double status information is reported with 2 different Spabus channel or data numbers. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
IndetValue 0…65535 3 Received data value that corresponds to Indeterminate (error) position. This attribute doesn’t support 2 data values. The same specified value will be used for both data values if double status information is reported with 2 different Spabus channel or data numbers. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
OnEvent 0…999E0…63 n/a Spabus Event that corresponds to ON position. Spabus Event carries a timestamp and if this Event is received before the change of position is received by polling data, the resulting position change will have a timestamp received with this Event. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
OffEvent 0…999E0…63 n/a Spabus Event that corresponds to OFF position. Spabus Event carries a timestamp and if this Event is received before the change of position is received by polling data, the resulting position change will have a timestamp received with this Event. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
InterEvent 0…999E0…63 n/a Spabus Event that corresponds to Intermediate position. Spabus Event carries a timestamp and if this Event is received before the change of position is received by polling data, the resulting position change will have a timestamp received with this Event. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
IndetEvent 0…999E0…63 n/a Spabus Event that corresponds to Indeterminate (error) position. Spabus Event carries a timestamp and if this Event is received before the change of position is received by polling data, the resulting position change will have a timestamp received with this Event. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
InterDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
IndetDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec ON position reporting delay in milliseconds. ON position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. OFF->ON->OFF->ON) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after ON position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec OFF position reporting delay in milliseconds. OFF position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. ON->OFF->ON->OFF) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after OFF position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and DataPos values without a need to create a DI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.Qualifier

Table 11.15 Spabus Master DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from outstation
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from outstation
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Exclude DI request from continuous polling. This option only applies if DI data values are requested only during IED initialization i.e. Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.
xxx1.xxxx Poll this DI continuously even if DI values are requested only during IED initialization i.e. Bit[0] = 1 in AppSettings.Flags.

xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received

Spabus request to poll data from outstation. Attribute has the following format [Channel][Category][Data Number].
Range of [Channel] values 0..999
[Category] is one of I, M, O, S, V
Range of [Data Number] values 1..999999
Example Request=”15I2”
Attribute is optional if PollMsg is used.
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 11.17 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIDeadband. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIPercent. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Total 1…254 1 Total number of information objects. Attribute is used to create a sequence of information objects with consecutive Index and DataPos values without a need to create a AI node for each information object. (default value 1 - only 1 object is created) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

AI.Qualifier

Table 11.17 Spabus Master AI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF AI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx AI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx AI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 0..6 Any Bits reserved for future use

DOTable group

DOTable group and its elements DO are used to define control commands that can be sent to IED. Each DO element can be linked to DO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a control command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the control command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked DO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 11.18 and sends the command to IED.
Please refer to the DOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DO information objects.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 3 control commands defined in this sample.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" OnCtrlMsg="1" OffCtrlMsg="1" OnValue="1" OffValue="2"/>
     <DO Index="1" OnRequest="120V4" OffRequest="120V5" OnValue="0" OffValue="1" />
     <DO Index="2" OnRequest="120V4" OffRequest="120V5" Qualifier="0x01" FollowCtrlMsg="2"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" OnCtrlMsg="2" OffCtrlMsg="4" OnRequest="120V4" OffRequest="120V5" Qualifier="0x00" OnValue="1" OffValue="2" FollowCtrlMsg="2" Name="CB command" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DO attributes

Table 11.18 Spabus Master DO attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DO object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
OnCtrlMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the Control message that is used to send ON command to outstation. Use value of the MSG.CtrlMsg attribute. Value 0 means no control message is selected., OnRequest attribute must be used to specify the message. This attribute has higher priority than OnRequest, if both attributes are specified OnCtrlMsg will be used.
OffCtrlMsg 1…65534 0 Identifier of the Control message that is used to send OFF command to outstation. Use value of the MSG.CtrlMsg attribute. Value 0 means no control message is selected., OffRequest attribute must be used to specify the message. This attribute has higher priority than OffRequest, if both attributes are specified OffCtrlMsg will be used.
OnRequest see description n/a

[Category] is one of I, M, O, S, V

Example OnRequest=”120V4”
