12. IEC61850 Client

This section contains details on how to configure IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. IEC61850 standard specifies the System Configuration Language (SCL) for files which are used to store configuration data of the IED. Most commonly used files are IED Capability Description (ICD), Configured IED Description (CID) and System Configuration Description (SCD). CID or SCD file is required for each IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. It contains communication capabilities and settings of the Server station (IED) we need to communicate to. In addition to CID/SCD file a XML configuration file is required. It contains IO object table and additional protocol-related settings. The same pair of CID/SCD and XML files can be used for multiple communication protocol instances. It may be useful if multiple IEDs have identical set of IO objects.

Name and location path of the configuration files is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. Files ‘IED_IO.xml’ and ‘IED.cid’ are used as a sample. Enter names of the files in IEC61850cl.XMLpath and IEC61850cl.SCLpath attributes of the communication protocol instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath=”IED_IO.xml” and SCLpath=”IED.cid” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the files are located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

IEC61850 Client configuration file (e.g. ‘IED_IO.xml’) must have a root node IEC61850clConfig which cosists of:
2 mandatory groups VersionControl and ProtocolCfg;
4 optional IO object groups DITable; AITable; DOTable and AOTable.
Please see the sample below.
<IEC61850clConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/IEC61850cl" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="4.00" date="2022-01-25" time="12:00:09"/>
  <ProtocolCfg>
    <CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10"/>
    <TransportSettings CallingTSEL="0x0A" SourceREF="0x04"/>
        …
  </ProtocolCfg>
  <DITable>
    <DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST"/>
        …
  </DITable>
  <AITable>
    <AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX"/>
        …
  </AITable>
  <DOTable>
    <DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO"/>
        …
  </DOTable>
  <AOTable>
    <AO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Mod" fc="CO"/>
        …
  </AOTable>
</IEC61850clConfig>

DITable; AITable; DOTable; AOTable groups make up the IO object table of the IEC61850 Client communication protocol instance. Please refer to the tables Table 12.27; Table 12.30; Table 12.34 and Table 12.36 for their attributes.

ProtocolCfg group

ProtocolCfg group and its child elements contain protocol-related settings of the IEC61850 Client instance.

Important

It is essential to keep element nodes in the listed order otherwise it will affect the XML file validation.

Please see sample ProtocolCfg group and all available child elements below. Refer to further sections for attributes of each element.

<ProtocolCfg>
  <CommsSettings … />
  <TransportSettings … />
  <SessionSettings … />
  <PresentationSettings … />
  <AssociationSettings … />
  <MMSSettings … />
  <ScsmSettings … />
  <AcsiSettings … />
  <AppSettings … />
  <ServiceSettings … />
  <Timeouts … />
  <Periodic … />
</ProtocolCfg>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

CommsSettings

Communication state (e.g. online and offline) change behavior and related delays can be specified in this node.

Please see sample CommsSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CommsSettings OfflineDelay="10" PostOfflineDelay="1000" />
Table 12.1 IEC61850 Client CommsSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
OfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 6 sec Offline delay in seconds before station status is changed to OFFLINE. Offline delay timer is activated after TCP socket has been closed. Default 6 seconds - station status will change to OFFLINE 6 seconds after TCP socket has been closed by either host.
PostOfflineDelay 0…232 - 1 0 sec Additional delay to change quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects if station hasn’t been online for a very long time. Quality marking of station’s DI/AI objects will be changed after configured number of seconds following status change to OFFLINE. (Application example: DI/AI objects can be marked with Not Topical [NT] bit when station status changes to OFFLINE i.e. after OfflineDelay timer expires and Invalid [IV] bit after this delay expires.)

TransportSettings

Settings of the Transport layer (ISO8073) can be specified using attributes of TransportSettings element node.

Please see sample TransportSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<TransportSettings CallingTSEL="0001" SourceREF="15" PDUsize="2048" TS1timeout="0" Flags="0x00" LogFlags="0x00"/>
Table 12.2 IEC61850 Client TransportSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
CallingTSEL Up to 8 hexadecimal characters 0…F 0001 [Calling Transport-Selector] field value for outgoing Connection Request [CR-TPDU].
SourceREF 1…65535 10 [SRC-REF] Reference selected by the transport entity initiating the Connection Request [CR-TPDU] to identify the requested transport connection.
PDUsize 27…211 1024 Proposed maximum TPDU size parameter used for outgoing Connection Request [CR-TPDU]. Only power of 2 values (e.g. 128, 256, 512) can be specified.
TS1timeout 0…65535 5 sec Supervisory Timer 1 [TS1] in seconds. Timer is stated when Connection Request [CR-TPDU] message is sent. Network connection will be closed if no Connection Confirm [CC-TPDU] is received from IED before the timer expires. Value 0 disables the timer.
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Miscellaneous settings of the Transport layer. See Table 12.3 for description.
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Informative message logging settings of the Transport layer. See Table 12.12 for description. Informative message recording to loggfile must be enabled globally with LOGGER.LogFlags attribute.
Table 12.3 Transport layer flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Transport layer flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Ignore destination reference [DST-REF] of the received [CC-TPDU]. (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 Check destination reference [DST-REF] of the received [CC-TPDU]. Communication will not be established if the received value doesn’t match SourceREF.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Ignore [Calling Transport-Selector] and [Responding Transport-Selector] identifiers of the received [CC-TPDU]. (default value)
xxxx.xx1x Check [Calling Transport-Selector] and [Responding Transport-Selector] identifiers of the received [CC-TPDU]. Communication will not be established if the received [Calling Transport-Selector] doesn’t match CallingTSEL or [Responding Transport-Selector] doesn’t match “OSI-TSEL” defined in the SCL file.
Bits 2…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

SessionSettings

Settings of the Session layer (ISO8327) can be specified using attributes of SessionSettings element node.

Please see sample SessionSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<SessionSettings CallingSSEL="0001" TIMtimeout="2" Flags="0x00" LogFlags="0x00"/>
Table 12.4 IEC61850 Client SessionSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
CallingSSEL Up to 16 hexadecimal characters 0…F 0001 [Calling Session Selector] field value for outgoing [CONNECT (CN) SPDU].
TIMtimeout 1…65535 5 sec
Disconnection and abort timer [TIM] in seconds. Timer is stated when sending [ABORT (AB) SPDU].
Network connection will be closed if timer expires before either:
> No [T-DISCONNECT] is received from Transport layer in case if Transport connection is released (Bit[2] = 0) or
> No [ABORT ACCEPT (AA) SPDU] is received from IED in case if Transport connection is kept (Bit[2] = 1).
Flags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Miscellaneous settings of the Session layer. See Table 12.5 for description.
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Informative message logging settings of the Session layer. See Table 12.12 for description. Informative message recording to loggfile must be enabled globally with LOGGER.LogFlags attribute.
Table 12.5 Session layer flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Session layer flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Ignore [Calling Session Selector] and [Called Session Selector] identifiers of the received [ACCEPT (AC) SPDU]. (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 Check [Calling Session Selector] and [Called Session Selector] identifiers of the received [ACCEPT (AC) SPDU]. Communication will not be established if the received [Calling Session Selector] doesn’t match “OSI-SSEL” defined in the SCL file or [Called Session Selector] doesn’t match CallingSSEL.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Transport connection is released when sending [FINISH (FN) SPDU]. (default value)
xxxx.xx1x Transport connection is kept when sending [FINISH (FN) SPDU].
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Transport connection is released when sending [ABORT (AB) SPDU]. (default value)
xxxx.x1xx Transport connection is kept when sending [ABORT (AB) SPDU].
Bits 3…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 Basic level of logging Disabled (default value)
xxxx.xxx1 Basic level of logging Enabled. Only generic information will be recorded to communication logfile.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x Verbose level of logging Disabled (default value)
xxxx.xx1x Verbose level of logging Enabled. Values of all received data fields will be recorded to communication logfile.
Bits 2…7 Any Bits reserved for future use
Informative logger flags summarized in this table apply to the following layers:
TransportSettings.LogFlags
SessionSettings.LogFlags
PresentationSettings.LogFlags
AssociationSettings.LogFlags
MMSSettings.LogFlags

AcsiSettings

Abstract Communication Service Interface (IEC61850-7-x ACSI) settings can be specified using attributes of AcsiSettings element node.

Please see sample AcsiSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AcsiSettings Bdyndsname="dynb" Udyndsname="dynu" Maxdynds="10" BOptFlds="0x0001" UOptFlds="0x0000" bufTime="0" Flags="0x0003" RCBFlags="0x0000" DSFlags="0x0000" LogFlags="0x0000"/>
Table 12.16 IEC61850 Client AcsiSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Bdyndsname 1…97 chars dynb Name for dynamic datasets that are going to be linked to Buffered Report Blocks. By default dynamic datasets are created in the “LLN0” of the same Logical Device (LD) where Data Object (DO) is located. In order to create datasets in a specific Logical Device, IED name and preferred Logical Device can be included e.g. “IEDLD0/dynb”
Udyndsname 1…97 chars dynu Name for dynamic datasets that are going to be linked to Unbuffered Report Blocks. By default dynamic datasets are created in the “LLN0” of the same Logical Device (LD) where Data Object (DO) is located. In order to create datasets in a specific Logical Device, IED name and preferred Logical Device can be included e.g. “IEDLD0/dynu”
Maxdynds 0…255 20 Maximal number of dynamic datasets that can be created. Datasets linked to Buffered and Unbuffered Report Blocks are accounted separately. Default value 20 means 20 (Buffered) + 20 (Unbuffered) dynamic datasets can be created.
BOptFlds 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0001 Optional Fields for Buffered Report Control Blocks. [OptFlds] of all used Report Control Blocks will be set to this value. Applies to all Report Control Blocks - defined in the SCL and received from IED during initialization. See Table 12.17 for description.
UOptFlds 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Optional Fields for Unbuffered Report Control Blocks. [OptFlds] of all used Report Control Blocks will be set to this value. Applies to all Report Control Blocks - defined in the SCL and received from IED during initialization. See Table 12.17 for description.
bufTime 0…232 - 2 0 msec Interval in milliseconds for buffering internal notifications before Information Report is generated [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables buffering and Information Reports are generated instantly.
Flags 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Miscellaneous Abstract Communication Service Interface settings. See Table 12.18 for description.
RCBFlags 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Report Control Block settings. See Table 12.19 for description.
DSFlags 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Dataset settings. See Table 12.20 for description.
LogFlags 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF 0x0000 Informative message logging settings. See Table 12.21 for description. Informative message recording to loggfile must be enabled globally with LOGGER.LogFlags attribute.

Table 12.18 Abstract Communication Service Interface flags
Bits Value Description
Flags [xxxx.xxxx.xxxx.xxxx] 0x0000…0xFFFF ACSI flags is 16 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…65535 and hex 0x0000…0xFFFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xxx0 Don’t read directory when station goes online. (default value) This setting applies only if IED doesn’t support Dynamic datasets. If IED supports Dynamic datasets, directory will always be read regardless of this setting.
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xxx1
Always read directory when station goes online. IED initialization will take longer, however this offers extra checks. Directory received from IED will be matched against the SCL tree and any inconsistencies will be reported. ACSI services:

It will happen only in one of these situations:
> IED supports Dynamic datasets;
> IED doesn’t support Dynamic datasets, but directory read is enabled with Bit[0] = 1.
xxxx.xxxx xxxx.xx1x Read Basic Types of all elements when station goes online with [GetDataDefinition]. It will only happen in 2 situations described above.

It will happen only in one of these situations:

> IED doesn’t support Dynamic datasets and Report Blocks are included in the SCL file.

xxxx.xxxx xxx1.xxxx Ignore missing [CommandTermination] after Enhanced security commands. This setting has to be used only if IED doesn’t generate [CommandTermination] when Enhanced security Direct or SBO command is complete. If there is no termination and this setting is not used, the command will only be completed after Application timeout expiration.
Bit 5 xxxx.xxxx xx0x.xxxx Ignore millisecond accuracy of timetags received from IED (default value)
xxxx.xxxx xx1x.xxxx Use millisecond accuracy of timetags received from IED. Some IEDs report lower accuracy if the IED is not synchronized. Enabling this setting will result in rounding of milliseconds based on the received accuracy and the timetag may appear different than record in IED’s internal event list.

AppSettings

Application layer settings can be specified using attributes of AppSettings element node.

Please see sample AppSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AppSettings IgnoreTimetags="1" AIDeadband="2" AIPercent="0.5" DIEventStartup="1" AIEventStartup="1" ForwardGI="1"/>
Table 12.22 IEC61850 Client AppSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
IgnoreTimetags 0 0 Use original timetags of events received from outstation. DI.Qualifier or AI.Qualifier attribute can be used to disable timetag processing for each DI/AI.
1 Substitute all timetags of events received from outstation with the local time.
2 Substitute future timetags of events received from outstation with the local time. Timetags of received events will be substituted only if a received timetag is in future compared to the local time. There is no hysteresis, if the received timetag is in future by at least 1 millisecond, it will be substituted.
AIDeadband 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Deadband attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Deadband attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables deadband feature.
AIPercent 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent deadband for all AI objects which doesn’t have AI.Percent attribute specified in their element node. Refer to individual AI.Percent attribute description for more information. Value 0 disables percent feature.
DIEventStartup 0 1 DI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started. This setting masks only events received from an outstation. Internal events created by station Offline/Disabled changes will be generated as normal.
1 DI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
AIEventStartup 0 1 AI events will not be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
1 AI events will be generated when received from outstation for the first time after leandc application has been started.
ForwardGI 0 1 Don’t forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)
1 Forward General Interrogation command to downstream outstations when received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA)

ServiceSettings

Service settings are used to control DI/AI event generation when station goes offline because of lost communication, is being Disabled using Service command, etc.

Please see sample ServiceSettings node and all its attributes in the table below.

<ServiceSettings EventMask="0x00" />
Table 12.23 IEC61850 Client ServiceSettings attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
EventMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Disable spontaneous reporting (events) of DI/AI objects when communication state of the station changes. See Table 12.24 for event mask description. (default 0x00 - DI/AI events are always generated - none masked) Note quality bits of static DI/AI qualifier will still be set even if event reporting is masked by EventMask attribute
Table 12.24 Service event masking bits
Bits Value Description
EventMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Event mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI/AI events will be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup. Events will be sent after OfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.xxx1 DI/AI events will not be generated if station is not initialized (doesn’t reply and gets marked OFFLINE) on leandc startup.
Bit 1 xxxx.xx0x DI/AI events will be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
xxxx.xx1x DI/AI events will not be generated when station gets Disabled with a Service command.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx DI/AI events will be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
xxxx.x1xx DI/AI events will not be generated when station status changes to OFFLINE (after OfflineDelay timer expires).
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx DI/AI events will be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
xxxx.1xxx DI/AI events will not be generated after PostOfflineDelay timer expires.
Bits 4…7 Any Bits reserved for future use

Timeouts

Command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts Application="30" Command="10" Select="30" Response="5"/>
Table 12.25 IEC61850 Client Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Application 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits response from downstream outstation after control command has been sent. If no response is received within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general application timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to downstream outstation is lost.
Command 1…232 - 1 10 sec Command timeout is a delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance tries to send command response to upstream Master station. If it is impossible to send the response within a configured timeout, command is considered failed and processing is terminated (command gets removed from the buffer). In general command timeout is used to terminate pending control commands, if communication to upstream Master station is lost.
Select 1…232 - 1 30 sec Select timeout is a maximal delay in seconds between received Select and Execute commands. If an Execute command is not received within a configured number of seconds, controlable object (DO/AO) is automatically de-selected, Execute command will not be accepted and new Select command is required. Select timeout is used to test reliability of the communication channel when receiving control commands to prevent major delays due to intermittent communications.
Response 0…232 - 1 5 sec Response timeout in seconds. Connection to IED will be closed if no response to a sent message has been received within this timeout.

Periodic

Periodic intervals to send various messages are specified in this node.

Please see sample Periodic node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Periodic GI="600" intgPd="60000" />
Table 12.26 IEC61850 Client Periodic attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
GI 0…232 - 1 0 sec Periodic General Interrogation command interval in seconds. Value 0 disables periodic General Interrogation command.
intgPd 0…232 - 1 0 msec Common interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. This attribute is used for all DI/AI objects which doesn’t have DI.intgPd or AI.intgPd attribute specified in their element node. Value 0 disables integrity reports.

DITable group

DITable group and its elements DI are used to define DI information objects that contain status information received from IED. Each DI element can be linked to DI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining status information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives DI status information from IED and processes it based on settings in the Table 12.27.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked DI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the DITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DI information objects.

Please see sample DITable group and DI element nodes below. There are 2 status information objects defined in this sample.

<DITable>
     <DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST"/>
     <DI Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Loc" fc="ST"/>
</DITable>

Please see sample DI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="DA" lnClass="XCBR" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="ST" Qualifier="0" InterDelay="10000" IndetDelay="0" OnDelay="0" OffDelay="0" OnValues="0x01 0x02" OffValues="5,6" daName="stVal" DSref="ABCLD/LLN0.myds" DSflags="0x00" TrgOps="0x00" intgPd="0" Name="CB position" />

Tip

Attributes of the DI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

DI attributes

Table 12.27 IEC61850 Client DI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the DI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
ldInst 1…64 chars n/a Logical Device instance from SCL file e.g. ‘LD0’
prefix 0…11 chars n/a Prefix of the Logical Node name from SCL file e.g.’DA’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have prefix. Leave blank i.e. prefix=”” in this case.
lnClass 4 chars n/a Logical Node Class from SCL file e.g. ‘XCBR’
lnInst 0…1010 - 1 n/a Logical Node Instance from SCL file e.g. ‘1’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have instance. Leave blank i.e. lnInst=”” in this case.
doName 1…64 chars n/a Data object name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘Pos’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘A.phsA’
fc 2 chars n/a Functional Constraint from SCL file e.g. ‘ST’
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 12.28 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
InterDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Intermediate position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Status Information (DPI) objects. Intermediate position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Intermediate position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
IndetDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec Indeterminate (error) position reporting delay in milliseconds for Double Point Information (DPI) objects. Indeterminate (error) position of the DPI will not be reported if it doesn’t exceed configured delay. (default value 0 - event will be generated instantly if DPI is in Indeterminate (error) position) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec ON position reporting delay in milliseconds. ON position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. OFF->ON->OFF->ON) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after ON position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffDelay 0…232 - 1 0 msec OFF position reporting delay in milliseconds. OFF position of the DI will be reported after a configured delay. This feature allows to filter out multiple position change events (e.g. ON->OFF->ON->OFF) received from outstation and generate a single position change event only after OFF position has remained stable for a configured number of milliseconds. (default value 0 - delay disabled) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OnValues 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF (up to 32) n/a Values received from IED will result in a DI state ON. This setting only applies if basic type of the DI object can have a range of values e.g. [Enum], [INT8]. By default received values are decoded to DI states as follows: INTER = 0,4,8; OFF = 1,5,9; ON = 2,6,10; INVALID = 3,7,11. This attribute overrides the default decoding and allows to select values that will result in ON state manually. Up to 32 values can be specified in decimal or hexadecimal notation separated by whitespaces or commas e.g. “2,3 0x05 0xf1”. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default decoding will apply if omitted. If OffValues attribute is not used, any value received from IED that is not included in OnValues list will result in a DI state OFF. If OffValues attribute is used, any value received from IED that is not included in either attributes will result in a DI state INTER.
OffValues 0…65535 or 0x0000…0xFFFF (up to 32) n/a Values received from IED will result in a DI state OFF. This setting only applies if basic type of the DI object can have a range of values e.g. [Enum], [INT8]. By default received values are decoded to DI states as follows: INTER = 0,4,8; OFF = 1,5,9; ON = 2,6,10; INVALID = 3,7,11. This attribute overrides the default decoding and allows to select values that will result in OFF state manually. Up to 32 values can be specified in decimal or hexadecimal notation separated by whitespaces or commas e.g. “2,3 0x05 0xf1” Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default decoding will apply if omitted. If OnValues attribute is not used, any value received from IED that is not included in OffValues list will result in a DI state ON. If OffValues attribute is used, any value received from IED that is not included in either attributes will result in a DI state INTER.
daName 1…64 chars stVal Data attribute name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘stVal’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘cVal.mag.f’ Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
DSref 1…129 chars n/a Name of the dataset that must be enabled for this object e.g. “IEDLD0/LLN0.mydataset”. Non-persistent dynamic dataset e.g. “@mydataset” can be created if IED supports Dynamic dataset creation. It is recommended not to use this attribute, unless you fully understand the implications. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will be automatically grouped in datasets if omitted.
DSflags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Dataset configuration options. See Table 12.29 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TrgOps 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Information Report trigger options. See Table 12.33 for Trigger Options description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
intgPd 0…232 - 2 0 Interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables integrity reports. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

DI.Qualifier

Table 12.28 IEC61850 Client DI internal qualifier
Bits Value Description
Qualifier [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF DI internal qualifier is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 DI object will not be inverted (ON = 1; OFF = 0 for [SPS] and [SPC] classes and ON = 2; OFF = 1; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [DPS] and [DPC] classes)
xxxx.xxx1 DI object will be inverted (ON = 0; OFF = 1 for [SPS] and [SPC] classes and ON = 1; OFF = 2; INTER = 0; INVALID = 3 for [DPS] and [DPC] classes)
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Use original timetag when event is received from IED
xxxx.1xxx Substitute timetag with local time when event is received from IED
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use time tag of the last event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the INTER->OFF event will be used.
xx1x.xxxx Use time tag of the first event if Intermediate state of the Double Point object was not reported (because Intermediate state didn’t exceed InterDelay). e.g. in transition ON->INTER->OFF time tag of the ON->INTER event will be used.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx DI is enabled and will be processed when received
1xxx.xxxx DI is disabled and will be discarded when received
Bits 1;2;4;6 Any Bits reserved for future use

DI.DSflags

Table 12.29 IEC61850 Client DI Dataset flags
Bits Value Description
DSflags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Dataset flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bits 1;0 xxxx.xx00 Dataset that is linked to buffered Report Block is required for this DI object
xxxx.xx01 Dataset that is linked to unbuffered Report Block is required for this DI object
xxxx.xx10 Dataset that is linked to any Report Block can be used for this DI object
xxxx.xx11 Reserved for future use
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Use any dataset that contains this DI object.
xx1x.xxxx Use referenced only dataset, that is set by DSref attribute. No other dataset will be used even if DSref dataset doesn’t contain this DI object.
Bits 2;3;6;7 Any Bits reserved for future use

AITable group

AITable group and its elements AI are used to define AI information objects that contain analog information received from IED. Each AI element can be linked to AI information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for obtaining analog information is as follows:
> Current communication protocol instance receives AI analog information from IED and processes it based on settings in the Table 12.30.
> Processed data is forwarded to the linked AI information object of the Slave protocol instance which sends it upstream to the Master station.
Please refer to the AITable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link AI information objects.

Please see sample AITable group and AI element nodes below. There are 2 analog information objects defined in this sample.

<AITable>
     <AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0"/>
     <AI Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsB" fc="MX"/>
</AITable>

Please see sample AI node and all its attributes in the table below.

<AI Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="CPH" lnClass="MMXU" lnInst="1" doName="A.phsA" fc="MX" Qualifier="0x20" Coeff="1.0" Deadband="0.5" Percent="0" StartOffset="6554" ZeroDeadband="3.0" Offset="-2.0" OffsetDeadband="2.0" NonZeroOffset="200.0" daName="cVal.mag.f" DSref="ABCLD/LLN0.myds" DSflags="0x00" TrgOps="0x00" intgPd="0" Name="Feeder current" />

Tip

Attributes of the AI element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

AI attributes

Table 12.30 IEC61850 Client AI attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 0…224 - 1 n/a Index is a unique identifier of the AI object. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects object mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
ldInst 1…64 chars n/a Logical Device instance from SCL file e.g. ‘LD0’
prefix 0…11 chars n/a Prefix of the Logical Node name from SCL file e.g.’CPH’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have prefix. Leave blank i.e. prefix=”” in this case.
lnClass 4 chars n/a Logical Node Class from SCL file e.g. ‘MMXU’
lnInst 0…1010 - 1 n/a Logical Node Instance from SCL file e.g. ‘1’ This attribute is mandatory even if particular name of the Logical Node doesn’t have instance. Leave blank i.e. lnInst=”” in this case.
doName 1…64 chars n/a Data object name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘Pos’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘A.phsA’
fc 2 chars n/a Functional Constraint from SCL file e.g. ‘MX’
Qualifier 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Internal object qualifier to enable customized data processing. See Table 12.31 for internal object qualifier description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 1 Coefficient to multiply the value of incoming analog object. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Absolute (static) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIDeadband. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Percent (dynamic) deadband for a real-time analog value. AI value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest received analog value exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Incoming analog values are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. This attribute has a higher priority than AppSettings.AIPercent. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
StartOffset * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Start offset is normally used to adjust 4-20mA transducer output range, e.g. offset by a value that represents 4mA. AI will be forced to 0 and Invalid [IV] bit set if the received value is smaller than this offset. StartOffset will be subtracted from the received value if the received value is greater or equal to this offset. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ZeroDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Zero Deadband is used to filter noise by forcing low AI values to 0. AI will be forced to 0 if its real-time absolute value (+/-) falls below ZeroDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset AI value after ZeroDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
OffsetDeadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 0 Offset Zero Deadband is used to filter noise around 0 value after applying Offset. AI will be forced to 0 if its absolute value (+/-) after offsetting falls below OffsetDeadband attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NonZeroOffset * 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 0 Offset only non-zero values after ZeroDeadband; Offset and OffsetDeadband has been applied. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
daName 1…64 chars cVal.mag.f Data attribute name from SCL file. It may contain either single level name e.g. ‘stVal’ or multiple level name e.g. ‘cVal.mag.f’ Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
DSref 1…129 chars n/a Name of the dataset that must be enabled for this object e.g. “IEDLD0/LLN0.mydataset”. Non-persistent dynamic dataset e.g. “@mydataset” can be created if IED supports Dynamic dataset creation. It is recommended not to use this attribute, unless you fully understand the implications. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, objects will be automatically grouped in datasets if omitted.
DSflags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Dataset configuration options. See Table 12.32 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TrgOps 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Information Report trigger options. See Table 12.33 for Trigger Options description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
intgPd 0…232 - 2 0 Interval in milliseconds for generating periodic integrity reports [IEC61850-7-2:2010]. Value 0 disables integrity reports. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

DOTable group

DOTable group and its elements DO are used to define control commands that can be sent to IED. Each DO element can be linked to DO information objects (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Procedure for sending a control command is as follows:
> Slave protocol instance receives the control command from upstream Master station and forwards it to the linked DO node defined here.
> Current communication protocol instance prepares the command based on settings in the Table 12.34 and sends the command to IED.
Please refer to the DOTable group section of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link DO information objects.

Please see sample DOTable group and DO element nodes below. There are 2 control commands defined in this sample.

<DOTable>
     <DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO"/>
     <DO Index="1" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="BlkOpn" fc="CO"/>
</DOTable>

Please see sample DO node and all its attributes in the table below.

<DO Index="0" ldInst="LD0" prefix="GNRL" lnClass="CSWI" lnInst="1" doName="Pos" fc="CO" Qualifier="0x00" Name="CB command" />

Tip

Attributes of the DO element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.
