13. Internal PLC

This section describes how to enable basic PLC functionality and define internal data points and commands. Only one PLC instance can be defined, but it can contain points that use data from all available communication protocol instances. Points are defined in the XML configuration file described in this section.

Name and location path of the XML configuration file is not predefined, it can be chosen freely. File name ‘myplc.xml’ is used as a sample. Enter name of the XML file in PLC.XMLpath attribute of the PLC instance created in leandc.xml as follows: XMLpath =”myplc.xml” . Location path doesn’t have to be specified if the XML file is located in the default directory (/home/leandc/app).

PLC configuration file (e.g. ‘myplc.xml’) must have a root node PLCConfig which cosists of:
1 mandatory group VersionControl;
1 optional settings group Settings;
1 optional condition group ConditionTable;
1 optional data point group PointTable;
Please see the sample below.
<PLCConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/plc" … version="1.00">
  <VersionControl conf="1.00" date="2023-03-01" time="12:00:13"/>
   <Settings>
    <Timeouts InApplication="8" OutApplication="7" CmdForward="6"/>
  </Settings>
  <ConditionTable>
    <Range CondId="1" OnMin="0.0001" OnMax="10e20" OffMin="0" OffMax="-inf"/>
        …
  </ConditionTable>
  <PointTable>
    <PNT Index="0" PlcType="or" SrcDevices="10" SrcIndexes="0" SrcTypes="DI"/>
        …
  </PointTable>
</PLCConfig>

Settings group

Various settings of the basic PLC instance are defined in the Settings group as shown below.

<Settings>
  <Timeouts … />
</Settings>

Tip

All element nodes are optional, default values will be used for attributes of omitted nodes.

Timeouts

PLC command processing timeouts are specified in this node.

Please see sample Timeouts node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Timeouts InApplication="8" OutApplication="7" CmdForward="6"/>
Table 13.1 PLC Timeouts attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
InApplication 1…232 - 1 30 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for the received (incoming) PLC command processing. This timeout applies to commands received from upstream (Slave) protocol instance e.g. SCADA. Command fails if the PLC instance can’t complete the command (i.e. command is forwarded to Master protocol instance(s) but no valid responses received) within a configured number of seconds. If the PLC instance forwards commands to several Master protocol instance(s) all commands must be completed (and valid responses received) within a configured number of seconds.
OutApplication 1…232 - 1 10 sec Application timeout is a delay in seconds for the outgoing (PLC generated / forwarded) command processing. This timeout applies to commands PLC instance sends to downstream (Master) protocol instance(s). Command fails if the PLC instance can’t complete the command (i.e. command is sent to outstation(s) but no valid responses received) within a configured number of seconds. In general this timeout is used to terminate pending commands, if communication to outstation(s) is lost.
CmdForward 0…232 - 1 10 sec Command forward timeout is a maximal delay in seconds for how long communication protocol instance awaits destination (Master protocol instance) to become available for accepting a new command. If destination protocol instance is in the process of executing previous command, it may not be able to accept new command before the previous command is complete. The new command fails within a configured number of seconds if it can’t be forwarded to the destination. This timeout allows control command queueing for a short period of time and ensures pending command is automatically purged if destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command. Value 0 disables command queueing and command fails instantly if the destination protocol instance is unable to accept the new command.

PointTable group

PointTable group and its elements PNT are used to create an internal point table. Each PNT element needs one or more sources of data to perform a logic or arithmetic operation. DI/AI information objects defined in IO table of any Master protocol instance can be used as data sources for internal PLC points.
The result of the logic or aritmetic operation becomes value of the internal data point. This result can be used by linking the internal point PNT to DI/AI information object (one or more) defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Please refer to the DITable group and AITable group sections of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to link an internal data point.

Please see sample PointTable group and PNT elements below. There are 2 data points defined with 2 PNT elements.

<PointTable>
  <PNT Index="0" PlcType="or" SrcDevices="10" SrcIndexes="0" SrcTypes="DI"/>
  <PNT Index="1" PlcType="add" SrcDevices="10,11" SrcIndexes="0,2" SrcTypes="AI,AI"/>
</PointTable>

Please see sample PNT node and all its attributes in the table below.

<PNT Index="0" PlcType="or" SrcDevices="10" SrcIndexes="0" SrcTypes="DI" CondIds="1" Deadband="12" Percent="5.4" ExcludeMask="0x80" CmdIndex="0" Action="1" Name="OR point"/>

Tip

Attributes of the PNT element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

PNT attributes

Table 13.2 Data point attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 0…224 - 1 Index is a unique identifier of the data point. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
PlcType or / and / add / mult Logic or arithmetic operation of the data point. This operation will be perfomed on a source data values and the result of the operation will become value of the internal data point. See Table 13.3 for more information.
SrcDevices ** 1…254 Index of the source communication protocol instance, any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as a source. Internal PLC instance can also be used as a source, in this case use the PLC.Index attribute of the PLC instance itself. Normally multiple data sources are required in order to perform a logic operation, therefore multiple Master protocol instances can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 protocol instances separated by commas are allowed e.g. SrcDevices=”10,17,20”.
SrcIndexes ** 0…224 - 1 Index of the source DI/AI object. Any DI/AI element of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a source. Use value of the DI.Index attribute of any object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. Normally multiple data sources are required in order to perform a logic operation, therefore multiple object indexes can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 DI/AI object indexes separated by commas are allowed e.g. SrcIndexes=”0,1,6”.
SrcTypes ** DI / AI Type of the source object. DI/AI objects can be used as a source for a data point. Normally multiple data sources are required in order to perform a logic or artithmetic operation, therefore multiple object types can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 object types separated by commas are allowed e.g. SrcTypes=”DI,DI,AI”.
CondIds ** 0…65535 Identifier of the condition defined in the ConditionTable group. Currently used to set conditions only for source AI objects. A list of up to 32 identifiers separated by commas can be specified in this attribute e.g. CondIds=”0,1,9”. Value 0 - no condition used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Deadband * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 Absolute (static) deadband applicable only to analog point value. Internal point value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest analog value (calculated from source AI values) exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Deadband. Defined Deadband is added and subtracted from old analog value stored in the database in order to create the absolute deadband range. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - deadband); Upper = (oldvalue + deadband). Analog values of the PLC point are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the deadband feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Percent * 0 or +1.18×10-38 … +3.4×1038 Percent (dynamic) deadband applicable only to analog point value. Internal point value will be updated and event will be generated if the latest analog value (calculated from source AI values) exceeds value stored in the database plus/minus Percent. Defined Percent is used to calculate the dynamic deadband range based on the old analog value stored in the database. Limits of this range are calculated as follows: Lower = (oldvalue - (oldvalue * percent / 100)); Upper = (oldvalue + (oldvalue * percent / 100)). Analog values of the PLC point are checked against the deadband range and event is generated if a new value is outside the limit. Value 0 disables the percent feature. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
ExcludeMask 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF Exclude source DI/AI values from processing based on their quality. See Table 13.4 for more information. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
CmdIndex 0…224 - 1 Index of the PLC command element. Any CMD element can be selected. Use value of the CMD.Index attribute. This attribute must be used only if the PLC data point needs to generate a control command automatically based on its value.
Action 0…255 Action that PLC data point performs automatically. See Table 13.5 for description.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Important

** It is essential to specify equal number of parameters in attributes SrcDevices; SrcIndexes; SrcTypes and CondIds. For example if 2 DI information objects are used as an internal data point sources, each of these attributes must have 2 parameters e.g. SrcDevices=”10,10”; SrcIndexes=”0,1”; SrcTypes=”DI,AI” and CondIds=”0,1”.

Tip

* Please refer to annex Received AI processing for additional information on AI processing options and application examples using Deadband and Percent attributes. Annex Analog value scaling for information on analog value scaling.

PLC operation types

There are 6 types of logic and arithmetic operations that can be performed on a DI/AI data received from outstation. These are summarized in the table below.
Table 13.3 PLC logic or arithmetic operations
PlcType Description
or
Perform logic OR operation based on a DI object state position. DI object can have 4 states - INTER; OFF; ON; INVALID but only ON and OFF (distinctive position) states are used to perform a PLC operation. If state of any of the source DI objects is INTER or INVALID the PLC data point will also have an INTER or INVALID state. By default quality bits of all source DI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source DI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the DI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. At least 2 source DI objects required to perform a logic OR operation. The resulting state of the PLC data point based on the distinctive position states (ON or OFF) of 2 source DI objects is shown below:
DI1 DI2 => PLC point:
OFF OFF => OFF
ON OFF => ON
OFF ON => ON
ON ON => ON
and
Perform logic AND operation based on a DI object state position. DI object can have 4 states - INTER; OFF; ON; INVALID but only ON and OFF (distinctive position) states are used to perform a PLC operation. If state of any of the source DI objects is INTER or INVALID the PLC data point will also have an INTER or INVALID state. By default quality bits of all source DI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source DI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the DI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. At least 2 source DI objects are required to perform a logic AND operation. The resulting state of the PLC data point based on the distinctive position states (ON or OFF) of 2 source DI objects is shown below:
DI1 DI2 => PLC point:
OFF OFF => OFF
ON OFF => OFF
OFF ON => OFF
ON ON => ON
add Addition of AI object values. 2 or more AI values received from outstation can be added together and the sum will become value of the PLC data point. By default quality bits of all source AI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source AI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the AI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. Addition takes place after AI value scaling i.e. after coefficient (if any) specified in the source protocol instance is applied.
mult Multiplication of AI object values. 2 or more AI values received from outstation can be multiplied together and the product will become value of the PLC data point. By default quality bits of all source AI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source AI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the AI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. Multiplication takes place after AI value scaling i.e. after coefficient (if any) specified in the source protocol instance is applied.
avgany Get average of AI object values. Average of 2 or more AI values received from outstation can be calculated and will become value of the PLC data point. If the source analog value is 0, it is included in calculation. By default quality bits of all source AI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source AI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the AI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. If any of the source AI values are excluded from processing based on quality by the ExcludeMask attribute, the average is calculated only from those AI values that are available and online.
avgnonzero Get average of non-zero AI object values. Average of 2 or more AI values received from outstation can be calculated and will become value of the PLC data point. If the source analog value is 0, it is excluded and average is calculated only from non-zero values. By default quality bits of all source AI objects are added together meaning that if any of the source AI objects have set Invalid [IV] bit or outstation (where the AI is received from) goes offline, the resulting PLC data point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit. This can be changed by the ExcludeMask attribute. If any of the source AI values are excluded from processing based on quality by the ExcludeMask attribute, the average is calculated only from those AI values that are available and online.

PNT exclusion based on quality

DI/AI values that are used as sources for PLC points can be excluded (ignored) if any of their quality bits are set or the source outstation where DI/AI object originates is offline. By default all source DI/AI values are used in PLC point processing and the resulting PLC point will have the same quality bits as all of the source DI/AI objects combined (logic OR is performed to quality bits of all source DI/AI objects).
Table 13.4 Source DI/AI quality exclusion bits
Bits Value Description
ExcludeMask [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Exclusion mask is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Last available value of the source DI/AI will be used for PLC point processing if a source DI/AI object is not received from outstation or outstation is OFFLINE. The resulting PLC point will be marked offline if any of the source DI/AI objects are offline.
xxxx.x1xx Source DI/AI value will be excluded from PLC point processing if a source DI/AI object is not received from outstation or outstation is OFFLINE. Any source DIs/AIs originating from outstation that is offline will not affect PLC point processing (their values will be ignored) and the resulting PLC point’s value will be based only on those source DI/AI values that are available and online.
Bit 3 xxxx.0xxx Invalid [IV] bit of the resulting PLC point will not be set if all source DI/AI objects are excluded from processing because of their quality or are not online i.e. not received from outstation. If all source DI/AI values are excluded from processing the resulting AI PLC point will have a valid 0 value and the resulting DI PLC point will have a valid OFF value.
xxxx.1xxx Invalid [IV] bit of the resulting PLC point will be set if all source DI/AI objects are excluded from processing because of their quality or are not online i.e. not received from outstation.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Blocked [BL] bit will be included in PLC point processing and the resulting PLC point will also have a set Blocked [BL] bit.
xxx1.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Blocked [BL] bit will be excluded from PLC point processing.
Bit 5 xx0x.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Substituted [SB] bit will be included in PLC point processing and the resulting PLC point will also have a set Substituted [SB] bit.
xx1x.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Substituted [SB] bit will be excluded from PLC point processing.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Not Topical [NT] bit will be included in PLC point processing and the resulting PLC point will also have a set Not Topical [NT] bit.
x1xx.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Not Topical [NT] bit will be excluded from PLC point processing.
Bit 7 0xxx.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Invalid [IV] bit will be included in PLC point processing and the resulting PLC point will also have a set Invalid [IV] bit.
1xxx.xxxx Source DI/AI values with set Invalid [IV] bit will be excluded from PLC point processing.
Bits 0,1 Any Bits reserved for future use

PNT actions

Point actions are primarily used to trigger commands based on a value of the PLC data point. Available actions are summarized in the table below.
Table 13.5 PLC Action values
Action Description
0 No Action.
1 Generate control command to a PLC command with index specified in the CmdIndex attribute every time the PLC point position transitions from OFF to ON and none of the quality bits [IV NT BL NT] are set. Outgoing control command will have a qualifier ON. A command will be generated for every PLC point transition, which means multiple commands may be sent if the point changes position more than once in a short period of time. Commands are placed in the queue and forwarded to the PLC command one by one. This ensures receiving outstation(s) have enough time to complete a previous command, before the next one is sent. Please note, the command queue is purged instantly when outstation goes offline. This means no previous commands will be sent when outstation goes online again.
2 Generate control command to a PLC command with index specified in the CmdIndex attribute every time the PLC point position transitions from ON to OFF and none of the quality bits [IV NT BL NT] are set. Outgoing control command will have a qualifier ON. A command will be generated for every PLC point transition, which means multiple commands may be sent if the point changes position more than once in a short period of time. Commands are placed in the queue and forwarded to the PLC command one by one. This ensures receiving outstation(s) have enough time to complete a previous command, before the next one is sent. Please note, the command queue is purged instantly when outstation goes offline. This means no previous commands will be sent when outstation goes online again.
3 Continuously generate control commands to a PLC command with index specified in the CmdIndex attribute for as long as PLC point position remains ON. Outgoing control commands will have a qualifier ON. A new PLC command will be generated every 1sec. Command generation stops when PLC point position is no longer ON or any of the quality bits [IV NT BL NT] are set. Please note, the command queue is purged instantly when outstation goes offline. This means no previous commands will be sent when outstation goes online again.
4 Continuously generate control commands to a PLC command with index specified in the CmdIndex attribute for as long as PLC point position remains OFF. Outgoing control commands will have a qualifier ON. A new PLC command will be generated every 1sec. Command generation stops when PLC point position is no longer OFF or any of the quality bits [IV NT BL NT] are set. Please note, the command queue is purged instantly when outstation goes offline. This means no previous commands will be sent when outstation goes online again.
5…255 Reserved for future use.

CommandTable group

CommandTable group and its elements CMD are used to create an internal command table.
The main purpose of the CMD elements is to generate and send multiple commands to one or more Master protocol instances when command is received from Slave protocol instance. CMD can be used as a destination for any DO/AO information object defined in the IO table of a Slave protocol instance. Please refer to the DOTable group and AOTable group sections of a Slave protocol instance for more information on how to use PLC CMD element as a destination for control commands.
Each CMD element needs one or more command destinations to forward the received command to. DO/AO information objects defined in the IO table of any Master protocol instance can be used as a command destination.

Please see sample CommandTable group and CMD elements below. There are 2 commands defined with 2 CMD elements.

<CommandTable>
  <CMD Index="0" PlcType="direct" DstDevices="10" DstIndexes="0" DstTypes="DO"/>
  <CMD Index="1" PlcType="divproportion" DstDevices="10,11" DstIndexes="0,2" DstTypes="AO,AO"/>
</CommandTable>

Please see sample CMD node and all its attributes in the table below.

<CMD Index="0" PlcType="direct" DstDevices="10" DstIndexes="0" DstTypes="DO" CondIds="1" Name="Direct command"/>

Tip

Attributes of the CMD element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

CMD attributes

Table 13.6 PLC command attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
Index 0…224 - 1 Index is a unique identifier of the PLC command. Index numbering must start with 0 and indexes must be arranged in an ascending order. This restriction has been put in place because insertion of a new index affects mapping to Slave communication protocol instances.
PlcType direct / divproportion Command pre-processing before forwarding. Type of processing can be defined in this attribute before command is forwarded to its destination station(s). See Table 13.7 for more information.
DstDevices * 1…254 Index of the destination communication protocol instance, any Master protocol instance listed in CommunicationCfg group. Use value of the Index attribute in order to select Master protocol instance as a destination. Multiple Master protocol instances can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 protocol instances separated by commas are allowed e.g. DstDevices=”10,17,20”.
DstIndexes * 0…224 - 1 Index of the destination DO/AO object. Any DO/AO element of the selected Master protocol instance can be used as a destination. Use value of the DO.Index attribute of any object listed in the IO table of the selected Master protocol instance. Multiple object indexes can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 DO/AO object indexes separated by commas are allowed e.g. DstIndexes=”0,1,6”.
DstTypes * DO / AO Type of the destination object. DO/AO objects can be used as a destination for a PLC command. Multiple object types can be specified in this attribute. A list of up to 32 object types separated by commas are allowed e.g. DstTypes=”DO,DO,AO”.
CondIds * 0…65535 Identifier of the condition defined in the ConditionTable group. Currently used to set conditions only for destination AO objects. A list of up to 32 identifiers separated by commas can be specified in this attribute e.g. CondIds=”0,1,9”. Only Substitution and Scaling conditions can be used for a PLC command. Value 0 - no condition used. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Important

* It is essential to specify equal number of parameters in attributes DstDevices; DstIndexes; DstTypes and CondIds. For example if 2 AO information objects are used as a destination, each of these attributes must have 2 parameters e.g. DstDevices=”10,10”; DstIndexes=”0,1”; DstTypes=”AO,AO” and CondIds=”0,1”.

PLC command types

There are 2 types of pre-processing that can take place before command is forwarded to the destionation protocol instance(s). These are summarized in the table below.
Table 13.7 PLC command pre-processing
PlcType Description
direct Forward control command to destination protocol instance without modifying its qualifier or setpoint value.
divproportion Divide AO setpoint value by the number of defined PLC command destinations. For example, if a PLC command has 2 destination AO objects, the received value 6 will be divided by 2 and value 3 will be sent to each destination AO object. This setting applies only to AO commands.

ConditionTable group

ConditionTable group is used to define conditions for processing and modifying PLC analog values. There are 3 condition types available:
Range of analog values defined using the Range element;
Analog value scaling with the Scaling element;
Analog value substitution with the Substitution element.

Please see sample ConditionTable group below. There are 5 conditions defined with 2 Range, 1 Scaling and 2 Substitution elements.

<ConditionTable>
  <Range CondId="1" OnMin="0" OnMax="10e4" OffMin="-5" OffMax="-inf"/>
  <Range CondId="2" OnMin="100" OnMax="200"/>
  <Scaling CondId="3" Min="-5" Max="11e6" Offset="1.1" Coeff="14"/>
  <Substitution CondId="4" Min="-5" Max="11e6" Values="1.1 -4e-5" Result="14" NextCondId="5"/>
  <Substitution CondId="5" Min="0" Max="200" Values="3,4,5" Result="0"/>
</ConditionTable>

Condition types and their attributes are described in the following sections.

Range element

Range element is used to define 2 ranges for analog values. Whenever received analog value falls within a defined range, the position change event ON or OFF is generated. These ON and OFF positions are used as a source for internal points to perform a logic operation. Effectively the Range element is used to convert ranges of AI object values into DI with ON and OFF positions.

Please see sample Range node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Range CondId="1" OnMin="0" OnMax="10e4" OffMin="-5" OffMax="-99999.9" Name="AI to DI conversion"/>

Tip

Attributes of the Range element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

Range attributes

Table 13.8 Range attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
CondId 1…65535 Condition identifier must be a unique number within a ConditionTable group. Identifier numbering must start with 1 and identifiers must be arranged in an ascending order.
OnMin 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Minimal (inclusive) analog value that will result in a ON position. Internal point PNT that uses AI as a data source will get ON position whenever received analog value is equal or exceeds this attribute and is less or equal to OnMax attribute. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified.
OnMax 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Maximal (inclusive) analog value that will result in a ON position. Internal point PNT that uses AI as a data source will get ON position whenever received analog value is less or equal to this attribute and is equal or exceeds OnMin attribute. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified.
OffMin 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Minimal (inclusive) analog value that will result in a OFF position. Internal point PNT that uses AI as a data source will get OFF position whenever received analog value is equal or exceeds this attribute and is less or equal to OffMax attribute. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration. Any analog value outside the range defined by OnMin and OnMax attributes will result in OFF position if this attribute is not used.
OffMax 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Maximal (inclusive) analog value that will result in a OFF position. Internal point PNT that uses AI as a data source will get OFF position whenever received analog value is less or equal to this attribute and is equal or exceeds to OffMin attribute. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration. Any analog value outside the range defined by OnMin and OnMax attributes will result in OFF position if this attribute is not used.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Scaling element

Scaling element is used to change (multiply, offset) analog values. Whenever received analog value falls within a defined range it will be scaled based on specified atributes.

Please see sample Scaling node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Substitution CondId="2" Min="-5" Max="11e6" Offset="5" Coeff="1.1" NextCondId="3" Name="AI/AO value scaling"/>

Tip

Attributes of the Scaling element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

Scaling attributes

Table 13.9 Scaling attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
CondId 1…65535 Condition identifier must be a unique number within a ConditionTable group. Identifier numbering must start with 1 and identifiers must be arranged in an ascending order.
Min 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Minimal (inclusive) analog value that will result in scaling. The resulting value of a PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD will have Offset added and multiplied by the Coeff whenever the source AI/AO value falls within a range set by Min and Max attributes. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Note, received AI/AO values are compared to this attribute after scaling in the originating protocol instance is applied (e.g. coefficient in source Master instance in case of an AI and Slave instance in case of an AO) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Max 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Maximal (inclusive) analog value that will result in scaling. The resulting value of a PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD will have Offset added and multiplied by the Coeff whenever the source AI/AO value falls within a range set by Min and Max attributes. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Note, received AI/AO values are compared to this attribute after scaling in the originating protocol instance is applied (e.g. coefficient in source Master instance in case of an AI and Slave instance in case of an AO) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Offset 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Add value of this attribute to a PLC point or command. This attribute has a higher priority (applied before) Coeff attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Coeff ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Multiply PLC point or command by the value of this attribute. This attribute has a lower priority (applied after) Offset attribute. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
NextCondId 0…65535 Identifier of the next condition to be applied after current condition. Use identifier of any condition defined in the ConditionTable group. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Substitution element

Substitution element is used to substitute particular analog values with one specified value. Whenever received analog value falls within a defined range or matches one of the listed values, it will be substituted with a specified value. This functionality could be used to replace values that exceed a certain limit, for example, if a received value exceeds 100, Substitution element can used to replace it with 100, so that the resulting value never exceeds 100.

Please see sample Substitution node and all its attributes in the table below.

<Substitution CondId="2" Min="-5" Max="11e6" Values="1 -5.47 7e12 0.004" Result="14" NextCondId="3" Name="AI/AO value substitution"/>

Tip

Attributes of the Substitution element can be arranged in any order, it doesn’t affect XML file validation.

Substitution attributes

Table 13.10 Substitution attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
CondId 1…65535 Condition identifier must be a unique number within a ConditionTable group. Identifier numbering must start with 1 and identifiers must be arranged in an ascending order.
Min 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Minimal (inclusive) analog value that will result in substitution. The resulting value of a PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD will be substituted by the Result whenever the source AI/AO value falls within a range set by Min and Max attributes. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Note, received AI/AO values are compared to this attribute after scaling in the originating protocol instance is applied (e.g. coefficient in source Master instance in case of an AI and Slave instance in case of an AO) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Max 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Maximal (inclusive) analog value that will result in substitution. The resulting value of a PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD will be substituted by the Result whenever the source AI/AO value falls within a range set by Min and Max attributes. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ can be specified. Note, received AI/AO values are compared to this attribute after scaling in the originating protocol instance is applied (e.g. coefficient in source Master instance in case of an AI and Slave instance in case of an AO) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Values 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 (up to 16) Match any analog value specified in this list. The resulting value of a PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD will be substituted by the Result value whenever the source AI/AO value matches any of the values specified in this attibute. Up to 16 postive/negative floating point numbers in a standard decimal (1204.78) or scientific (3.5e3) notation can be specified separated by whitespaces or commas e.g. “1,-5.47,7e12,0.004”. Note, received AI/AO values are compared to this attribute after scaling in the originating protocol instance is applied (e.g. coefficient in source Master instance in case of an AI and Slave instance in case of an AO) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Result 0 or ±1.18×10-38 … ±3.4×1038 Substitution value for the PLC point PNT or PLC command CMD. Value specified in this attribute will be used whenever received analog value falls within a range between Min and Max attributes or matches one of the Values attribute. Positive and negative infinity values ‘inf’ and ‘-inf’ must not be specified.
NextCondId 0…65535 Identifier of the next condition to be applied after current condition. Use identifier of any condition defined in the ConditionTable group. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.
Name Max 64 chars Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

14. Logfiles

There is an option to record raw communication traffic and decoded communication data to logfiles for troubleshooting and maintenance purposes. Fixed name configuration file lelogger.xml contains settings to enable recording of communication data. lelogger.xml must be kept in the same directory as leandc.xml file. Its path and name can’t be changed.

lelogger.xml configuration file consists of a root object node SystemConfig which has 3 optional child group object nodes VersionControl; CommsCfg; EventCfg, please see the sample below.

<SystemConfig xmlns="http://www.londelec.com/xmlschemas/leandc/lelogger" … version="1.00">
      <VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>
      <CommsCfg>
         <LOGGER Index="6" LogFlags="0x7F" Logfile="Log/ma2"/>
         …
         <HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
         …
         <PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
      </CommsCfg>
      <EventCfg>
         <EVENTLOG Index="104" LogFlags="0x3F" HourLimit="0" Logfile="Events/SL104_1"/>
         …
      </EventCfg>
</SystemConfig>

Tip

lelogger.xml file is optional and leandc application is able to run normally without it.
Node names are case sensitive.

LOGGER and HWLOG nodes

LOGGER and HWLOG nodes contain settings for raw communication traffic logging and these nodes are children of CommsCfg group node. Following functionality is available:

  • Record all raw traffic over a serial/Ethernet interface - HWLOG node;
  • Filter and record traffic related to a specific communication protocol instance - LOGGER node;

Configuration may contain both nodes at the same time in any combination. However only 1 logfile per protocol instance and 1 logfile per hardware interface is allowed.

Please see sample CommsCfg group node and LOGGER and HWLOG child element nodes below. The sample below shows 2 logfiles for recording filtered traffic related to particular communication protocol instance and 1 logfile for recording all traffic over a serial interface.

<CommsCfg>
   <LOGGER Index="5" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/serial101" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="4"/>
   <LOGGER Index="6" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Log/tcpserv104"/>
   <HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
</CommsCfg>

Please see all available attributes of the LOGGER and HWLOG nodes below:

<LOGGER Index="5" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Log/serial101" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="Europe/Riga" Name="IED logfile" />
<HWLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Log/COM1" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC" Name="COM port logfile" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

LOGGER and HWLOG attributes

Table 14.1 LOGGER and HWLOG attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a specific communication protocol instance. Use value of the Index attribute of any communication protocol instance to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for LOGGER node and must not be used for HWLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index ; TCPSERVER.Index ; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for HWLOG node and must not be used for LOGGER node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Select type of the messages to be logged. See Table 14.2 for description. Logfile will not be created if the value is 0.
Logfile Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.log’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.log’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (sample value ‘Log/abc’, where ‘Log’ is the name of the directory and ‘abc’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Logfile initialization settings. See Table 14.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0…12 4 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 4 hours – total of 6 files will be created daily at 00:00, 04:00, 08:00, 12:00, 16:00, 20:00) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of the recorded information based on the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* List of files created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings can be found in section Logfile samples.

LOGGER.LogFlags

Table 14.2 Communication logfile flags
Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Communication logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported Logfile will not be created, if the value is 0. Some bits are not used for all communication protocols. For those bits applicable protocols are listed.
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0
IEC60870-5-101/3 Link layer message recording disabled

xxxx.xx1x Incoming message logging enabled. Applies to IEC60870-5-101/3/4; Modbus and Spabus protocols.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Outgoing message logging disabled. Applies to IEC60870-5-101/3/4; Modbus and Spabus protocols.
xxxx.x1xx Outgoing message logging enabled. Applies to IEC60870-5-101/3/4; Modbus and Spabus protocols.
Bit 4 xxx0.xxxx Error message recording disabled.
xxx1.xxxx Error message recording enabled. These are communication errors arrising from corrupted messages and timeouts. Also includes incorrect or unexpected received data.

Warning message recording disabled.
xx1x.xxxx
Warning message recording enabled.

Informative message recording disabled.

PCAPLOG

PCAPLOG node enables to capture traffic through a specific or any Ethernet interfaces in a pcap format. PCAPLOG node is a child of CommsCfg group node.

Please see sample CommsCfg group and PCAPLOG child element node below.

<CommsCfg>
   <PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0x00" HourLimit="0"/>
</CommsCfg>

Important

Group node CommsCfg may contain only one PCAPLOG node. PCAPLOG must be the last in the group after all LOGGER and HWLOG nodes, if there are any.

Please see all available attributes of the PCAPLOG node below:

<PCAPLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x07" Logfile="Log/trace" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" Filter="vlan 0" BufferSize="1048576" Name="pcap trace" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

PCAPLOG attributes

Table 14.3 PCAPLOG attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
HWIndex 1…254 n/a Capture traffic through Ethernet interface used by this Hardware node. Use value of the TCPSERVER.Index ; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute to enable capture. Only one PCAPLOG node can be defined. Use LogFlags attribute to enable capture on all Ethernet interfaces, if required.
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Capture filter specifications. See Table 14.4 for description. Capture is disabled if value is 0.
Logfile Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.pcap’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.pcap’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (sample value ‘Log/abc’, where ‘Log’ is the name of the directory and ‘abc’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Logfile initialization settings. See Table 14.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0…12 4 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 4 hours – total of 6 files will be created daily at 00:00, 04:00, 08:00, 12:00, 16:00, 20:00) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
Filter 1…200 chars n/a Custom capture filter e.g. “vlan 0”. See pcap-filter(7) manual for more information.
BufferSize 64…268435456 bytes 1048576 Size of the pcap captured data buffer in bytes. Captured data is temporarily stored in the buffer and written to pcap file at fixed time intervals. This attribute is mainly used for testing purposes and should not be changed unless recommended by the supplier. Default value of 1MB is optimal for most applications.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* List of files created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings can be found in section Logfile samples.

PCAPLOG.LogFlags

Table 14.4 Capture filter flags
Bits Value Description
LogFlags [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF PCAP logger flags is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported Capture is disabled if the value is 0.
Bits 0,1 xxxx.xx00 Reserved - don’t use.
xxxx.xx01 Capture traffic through all available Ethernet interfaces. Traffic will not be filtered by IP address.
xxxx.xx10 Capture traffic trough a single Ethernet interface, the one used for communication.
xxxx.xx11 Filter captured traffic by IP address. Only messages with matching Source or Destination IP address will be captured. Address from TCPSERVER.ServerIPaddr ; TCPCLIENT.ServerIPaddr or UDP.RemoteIPaddr attribute is used as a filter.
Bit 2 xxxx.x0xx Capture filter by port number is disabled
xxxx.x1xx Capture filter by port number is enabled. Only messages with matching Source or Destination Port number will be captured. Port number from TCPSERVER.Port ; TCPCLIENT.Port or UDP.RemotePort attribute is used as a filter.
Bit 6 x0xx.xxxx SSH (TCP/UDP port 22) traffic capture disabled
x1xx.xxxx SSH (TCP/UDP port 22) traffic capture enabled
Bits 3…5;7 Any Bits reserved for future use

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes contain settings for decoded application level information (DI/AI/DO/AO object types, addresses, values, etc) logging and these nodes are children of EventCfg group node. Following functionality is available:

  • Record all decoded information over a serial/Ethernet interface - HWEVENTLOG node;
  • Filter and record decoded information related to a specific communication protocol instance - EVENTLOG node;

Configuration may contain both nodes at the same time in any combination. However only 1 logfile per protocol instance and 1 logfile per hardware interface is allowed.

Please see sample EventCfg group node and EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG child element nodes below. The sample below shows 2 logfiles for recording decoded information of a particular communication protocol instance and 1 logfile for recording decoded information over a serial interface.

<EventCfg>
   <EVENTLOG Index="5" LogFlags="0x3F" Logfile="Events/serial101" HourLimit="0" Mode="0"/>
   <EVENTLOG Index="6" LogFlags="0x0C" Logfile="Events/tcpserv104"/>
   <HWEVENTLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x40" Logfile="Events/COM1_events" HourLimit="0"/>
</EventCfg>

Please see all available attributes of the EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG nodes below:

<EVENTLOG Index="5" LogFlags="0xFF" Logfile="Events/101slave" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="Europe/Riga" Name="IED Events" />
<HWEVENTLOG HWIndex="1" LogFlags="0x06" Logfile="Events/COM1" Mode="0" HourLimit="4" TimeZone="UTC" Name="All IED Events" />

Tip

Attributes can be arranged in any order, it will not affect the XML file validation.

EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG attributes

Table 14.5 EVENTLOG and HWEVENTLOG attributes
Attribute Values or range Default Description
Index 1…254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a specific communication protocol instance. Use value of the Index attribute of any communication protocol instance to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for EVENTLOG node and must not be used for HWEVENTLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
HWIndex 1…254 n/a Attribute is used to enable logging for a hardware node. Use value of the UART.Index ; TCPSERVER.Index ; TCPCLIENT.Index or UDP.Index attribute to enable logging. Attribute is mandatory for HWEVENTLOG node and must not be used for EVENTLOG node. Indexes don’t have to be in a sequential order.
LogFlags 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x00 Select type of the decoded information to be logged. See Table 14.6 for description. Logfile will not be created if value is 0.
Logfile Max 200 chars n/a Name of a logfile excluding extension (e.g. ‘.event’). It is possible to specify relative or absolute path as part of the file name. Logfile will be created in the default directory (/home/leandc/app) if path is not specified. Date when the file was created and extension ‘.event’ will be appended to the file name automatically. Logfile will not be created if this attribute is left blank. (sample value ‘Events/abc’, where ‘Events’ is the name of the directory and ‘abc’ is the name of the file) Attribute is case sensitive, observe case of the path and name when specifying.

Mode

*

 0…255 or 0x00…0xFF 0x01 Logfile initialization settings. See Table 14.7 for description. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.

HourLimit

*

 0…12 6 hours Option to create a new file after selected number of hours in order to limit the size of a file. (default 6 hours – total of 4 files will be created daily at 00:00, 06:00, 12:00, 18:00) Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration, default value will be used if omitted.
TimeZone Max 200 chars n/a Adjust time-tags of the recorded information based on the specified time zone. Attribute must not be used if not required, there is no default value. Time-tags will not be adjusted if attribute omitted. Please see Time Zone specification for additional information.
Name Max 64 chars n/a Freely configurable name, just for reference. Attribute is optional and doesn’t have to be included in configuration.

Tip

* List of files created with various Mode and HourLimit attribute settings can be found in section Logfile samples.

Bits Value Description
Mode [xxxx.xxxx] 0x00…0xFF Logfile initialization Mode is 8 bit encoded variable. Decimal 0…255 and hex 0x00…0xFF values supported
Bit 0 xxxx.xxx0 New logfile will be created every time leandc application is being started/restarted. This means a total number of files created each day will reflect how many times application was started/restarted.
xxxx.xxx1 New file will not be created if there is already a logfile which was created the same day leandc application is being started/restarted. New information will be appended at the end of the existing file. This means there will only be one file created each day regardless of how many times leandc application was started/restarted.

Logfile samples

This section provides information on how communication and event logfiles are created based on default settings as well as contents of each file.

New communication logfile is created every 4 hours based on the default value of the LOGGER.HourLimit attribute. In addition to that new file will be created every time leandc application is started/restarted based on the default value “0x00” of the LOGGER.Mode attribute. Example below shows 2 lists of files created if application runs continuously and if being restarted.

Tip

File creation date and hour (yyyy-mm-dd_hh) is automatically added to the file name specified in LOGGER.Logfile attribute. The sample below shows a list of files created if application is running continuously without being restarted.

  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_00.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_04.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_08.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_12.log’

Time-tag (hhmmss) is automatically added to the name of the files created after leandc application restart. Time-tag will be added only if there is an existing file which was created within a 4 hour window (4 hours is a default value of the LOGGER.HourLimit attribute). The sample below shows a list of files created if application is restarted at 14:04:13 and 14:07:32, then stopped completely at 17:00:00 and started again at 21:10:10.

  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_12.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_140413.log’ <- file created after restart at 14:04:13. Time-tag is added because file created within a 4 hour window already exists (file created at 12:00:00).
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_140732.log’ <- file created after restart at 14:04:13. Time-tag is added because file created within a 4 hour window already exists (file created at 12:00:00).
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_16.log’
  • ‘logfile_2013-04-12_20.log’ <- file created when application starts at 21:10:10. No time-tag is added because there is no file created within a 4 hour window (from 20:00:00 to 23:59:59).

Default settings for event files are slightly different. New event logfile is created every 6 hours based on the default value of the EVENTLOG.HourLimit attribute. However new file will not be created on leandc application restart based on the default value “0x01” of the EVENTLOG.Mode attribute. New entries will appended to the existing file if there is a file created within a 6 hour window (6 hours is a default value of the EVENTLOG.HourLimit attribute). Example below shows a list of files created if application is being restarted.

Tip

File creation date and hour (yyyy-mm-dd_hh) is automatically added to the file name specified in EVENTLOG.Logfile attribute. The sample belows shows a list of files created if application is restarted at 14:04:13.

  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_00.event’
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_06.event’
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_12.event’ <- restart at 14:04:13, no new file created because file within a 6 hour window already exists. New entries are appended to this file.
  • ‘eventfile_2013-04-12_18.event’

Contents of a typical communication logfile are shown below:

17:14:34.170 INFO    ONLINE
17:14:34.205 COMM -> 10 40 01 41 16
17:14:34.205 COMM <- 10 00 01 01 16
17:14:34.413 COMM -> 68 0F 0F 68 73 01 67 01 06 01 00 00 42 86 0E 11 CB 05 0D A7 16
17:14:34.414 COMM <- 10 20 01 21 16
17:14:34.625 COMM -> 68 09 09 68 53 01 64 01 06 01 00 00 14 D4 16

Raw traffic captured through a communication interface is recorded to a file along with some is additional information. Each entry (row) in the file represents successfully decoded protocol message and is prefixed with a time-tag, log entry type and direction identifier. Timetag represents the internal time when the message was received/sent. Log entry type may contain values listed in the table below:

Table 14.8 Logfile entry types
Entry Type Description
COMM Successfully decoded protocol message
INFO Additional status information e.g. ONLINE, OFFLINE, etc
ERR Failed protocol messages and timeouts
Direction identifier shows incoming/outgoing direction of a message as follows:
<- Outgoing message (sent by leandc application)
-> Incoming message (received by leandc application)
Directions are the same for Slave/Master communication protocol instances.

Contents of a typical event logfile is shown below:

    Time             Info    Type    CAA     InfAddr Value   QualHex Quality TimeTag                 Description
12:00:09.470 SU      SPNTAI  36      400     2101    63.88   0x00    GOOD    2015-07-31 09:00:09.470
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTAI  36      400     39      8.45    0x00    GOOD    2015-07-31 09:00:12.942
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTAI  34      400     57      24      0x81    IV OV   2015-07-31 09:00:12.942
12:00:12.943 SU      SPNTDI  31      400     1002    OFF     0x41    NT      2015-07-31 09:00:14.873
12:02:59.720         >CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05    SHORT                           Direct execute command received, validated and forwarded to Master protocol
12:02:59.846         <CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05    SHORT                           Execute Confirmation sent successfully
12:02:01.347         <CMD    45      400     6001    5       0x05    SHORT                           Termination sent successfully

Decoded information is arranged in a tab separated columns. The layout of the file is aimed to present a decoded information readable without additional tools, yet tab separated columns make importing event file into a spreadsheet an easy task. List of columns of the event logfile is shown in the table below:

Table 14.9 Event logfile columns
Column Description
Time Internal time when the event was received. Summer Time [SU] flag may be added to the time stamp.
Info Type of the event. See Table 14.10 for description.
Type ASDU typeID of the message.
CAA Common Address of ASDU [CAA].
InfAddr Information object address [IOA].
Value Value of the event. Decoded Floating point and Integer analog values can be easily distinguished by presence of a decimal point. Decimal point is only used for Floating point values, Integers doesn’t have it. Status information has 4 or 2 states (i.e. ON, OFF, INTER, INDET) which are shown depending on single or double message type. In case of control command decimal value of command qualifier including additional information (e.g. [Short Pulse]) is shown in this column.
QualHex Hexadecimal value of the object qualifier.
Quality
Quality flags of the DI/AI objects and [Qualifier Of Command] values. This column can have the follwing values:
GOOD - No quality flags are set
IV - [INVALID]
NT - [NOT TOPICAL]
SB - [SUBSTITUTED]
BL - [BLOCKED]
OV - [OVERFLOW] (AI only)
NODEF - [No additional definition] (DO only)
SHORT - [Short Pulse Duration] (DO only)
LONG - [Long Pulse Duration] (DO only)
PERS - [Persistent Output] (DO only)
TimeTag Time-tag of the event as received/sent to peer station. This column is populated only if event message has a time-tag. Summer Time [SU] flag may be added to the time tag.
Description Additional information on the command execution progress.
Table 14.10 Event logfile Info types
Info Description
>CMD Received control or setpoint command in the context of Slave protocol instance. Received confirmation or termination in the context of Master protocol instance.
<CMD Sent control or setpoint command in the context of Master protocol instance. Sent confirmation or termination in the context of Slave protocol instance.
>CMDN Received negative confirmation or termination, only applies to Master protocol instances.
<CMDN Sent negative confirmation or termination, only applies to Slave protocol instances.
>CMDERR Received control or setpoint command validation failed, command is immediately rejected, only applies to Slave protocol instances.
CMD Additional information on command execution progress.
CMDERR Internal error occurred while command being processed. Please contact vendor if this type of error appears.
SPNTDI Spontaneous status information (DI Event).
DI Static status information (e.g. as a response to General Interrogation).
SPNTAI Spontaneous analog information (AI Event).
AI Static analog information (e.g. as a response to General Interrogation).
AICYC Cyclic/periodic analog information.
AIBSCN Background scan analog information.
ERR Internal error. Please contact vendor if this type of error appears.

15. Configuration version control

All XML configuration files must contain version control element node where user can enter a unique number to control configuration file version along with file creation date and time. Each configuration file has its own version number and it is not related to any other XML files. If particular XML file is being modified by web configuration tool, the version number is automatically incremented by 1 and modification date and time is recorded.

Version control node must have 3 attributes conf; date; time please see the sample below.

<VersionControl conf="4" date="2014-01-18" time="10:08:09"/>

VersionControl attributes

Table 15.1 VersionControl attributes
Attribute Values or range Description
conf 0.01…65535 User assigned version number of the particular XML file. Number will be automatically incremented by 1 when particular XML file is being modified by web configuration tool.
date date notation YYYY-MM-DD Date when particular configuration file was created or modified.
time time notation HH:MM:SS Time when particular configuration file was created or modified.

Important

All attributes are mandatory.

16. Annexes

Analog value processing

This annex contains information about analog value processing, scaling options and application examples. All analog values are converted to Short Floating-point (32bit) numbers internally before scaling takes place. All AI scaling attributes used in this document: Coeff, Deadband, Percent, StartOffset, ZeroDeadband, Offset, OffsetDeadband, NonZeroOffset are Short Floating-point numbers. The value range is given for each of these attributes and values have to be specified either in decimal or scientific notation. Sample values are shown in the table below.

Table 16.1 Analog value notations
Decimal Scientific
1520.3 1.5203e3
-11 -1.1e1
0.00152 1.52e-3
-0.0456 -4.56e-2

Important

Precision of the Short Floating-point number is 7 decimal digits regardless of position of the decimal point. This applies to decimal and scientific notations. For example there are 7 decimal digits in numbers ‘1234567’ ‘1234.567’ ‘1.234567e3’ which is the maximum accuracy. Numbers with more decimal digits will be rounded.

Analog value scaling

Analog value scaling attributes Coeff, StartOffset, ZeroDeadband, Offset, OffsetDeadband, NonZeroOffset exist in Master and Slave protocol instances and scaling processes are independent of each other. This means analog value received from an outstation will be scaled at Master protocol instance first and then by a Slave protocol instance before sending the value out. It is recommended to enable scaling at Master protocol instances that receive analog values from outstations, but there are no restrictions that would prevent using scaling at Slave protocol instances. Analog value scaling sequence in shown in the flowchart below.

Figure 16.1 AI scaling sequence

Tip

StartOffset attribute automatically sets Invalid [IV] quality flag when forcing analog value to zero ‘0’. This is designed to detect failure of a 4-20mA tranducer (or similar) connected to an Analog Input. 4mA current is expecet when transducer is connected even if it is not measuring anything. If the current drops below 4mA Invalid [IV] quality flag is used to indicate a transducer failure or disconnect. ZeroDeadband attribute works alongside StartOffset in order to suppress noise around 4mA value and its use is receommended.

Scaling calculator below shows how leandc application analog scaling actually works. Enter a numeric value in the box ‘Start value’ and the ‘Result’ box will show the value after scaling has been applied. Scaling attributes are arranged in the order they are applied as shown in the sequence flowchart above. Calculator shows intermediate values after each attribute as well as basic math that was applied in each step. Any changes to scaling attributes are applied instantly and the result will be updated accordingly. The ‘Copy’ button on the top left corner can be used to copy scaling attributes and their entered values to clipboard. They will be formated in XML syntax and can be pasted directly into XML file.

StartOffset ZeroDeadband Offset OffsetDeadband NonZeroOffset Coeff
Start value Result
 

AI scaling calculator

Range calculator shown below enables to calculate Offset and Coeff attribute values based on ranges of analog values before and after scaling. The range of values before scaling takes place (e.g. range of values expected to be received from outstation) have to be entered into ‘Input Range’ boxes and the range of resulting values (e.g. expected from leandc application) have to be entered into ‘Output Range’ boxes. ‘Calculate’ button will update Offset and Coeff attributes of the scaling calculator above. Updated attributes will be highlighted yellow.

Its input range in milliamps and output integer range (based on ADC bit count) can be selected. AI application example

Received AI processing

Flowchart below shows AI value processing when IEC60870-5-101/103/104 Master protocol instance receives AI object from outstation. This processing takes place after AI scaling has been completed, refer to previous annexes for additional information on AI scaling.

Figure 16.2 Received AI processing flowchart

The figure below shows how a real time value received from outstation will be processed if AI.Deadband attribute is enabled. Internal database will be updated and AI event will get generated every time a real time value exceeds ‘static deadband’. Thresholds of the ‘static deadband’ are calculated based on previous value stored in the database. Attribute AI.Deadband = 2 is used as an example.

Figure 16.3 Deadband processing sample

The figure below shows how a real time value received from outstation will be processed if AI.Percent attribute is enabled. Internal database will be updated and AI event will get generated every time a real time value exceeds ‘dynamic deadband’. Thresholds of the ‘dynamic deadband’ are calculated based on previous value stored in the database. Attribute AI.Percent = 20 is used as an example.

Figure 16.4 Percent processing sample

Time Zone specification

It is possible to adjust incoming and outgoing message timestamps in case leandc application communicates to a station that uses a different time zone. Conventionally timezone and Daylight Saving Time (DST) information is kept in the so-called ‘Time Zone Database’ that consists of a set of TZ format files. These files are published and maintained by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA), please refer to their website (http://www.iana.org/time-zones) for more information. In general there is a TZ file for each country in the world where information related to DST and other time adjustments is recorded. These files can be found in the Linux Operating System directory:

/usr/share/zoneinfo

leandc application will attempt to locate a TZ file matching the name specified in a TimeZone attribute in this system directory. If a matching file is not found, leandc application will use System default time zone which means timestamps of a particular communication protocol instance will not be adjusted. Please find the list of most commonly used time zones below:

<TimeZone>UTC</TimeZone>
<TimeZone>Europe/London</TimeZone>
<TimeZone>Europe/Riga</TimeZone>

System default time zone can be changed as described in Leandc SSH manual section ‘Change Leandc operating system time zone’. The System default time zone is used for maintaining internal time of the Operating System. Internal time is used for time synchronization, time-stamping logfile records, creating logfile names, etc.

Table 17.3 Document version control
Version Date By Comments
V44 12/07/2024 AK
IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave:
> CmdForward attribute created which allows to queue incoming commands for a short period of time if destination station is busy executing previous command;
IEC60870-5-103 Master:
> Bit[5] added to ASDUSettings.Flags which allows to generate DI position change event when positive command confirmation is received from outstation;
Modbus Master:
> ForwardGI attribute created which uses General Interrogation command received from upstream station (e.g. SCADA) to poll DI/AI values by sending all defined Poll Messages one after another without checking message priorities;
> CmdRetries attribute created which allows to retry control command sending if Exception is received from outstation;
Basic PLC:
> PLC commands created, see CommandTable
> Scaling node created which allows to scale (multiply, offset) received analog value;
> Timeouts node created in Settings group which allows to adjust PLC command timeouts;
> Deadband and Percent attributes created for analog PLC point conditioning;
> ExcludeMask attribute created which allows to exclude source DI/AI values based on their quality;
> CmdIndex attribute created to generate PLC commands automatically based on PLC point value. DstDevice and DstIndex attributes removed;
> NextCondId attribute created which allows to chain mutliple conditions so that they are applied in sequence;
V43 28/05/2024 AK
IEC60870-5-101/4 Master:
> Bit[5] added to ASDUSettings.Flags which enables Originator Address [OA] check of the received command response;
IEC60870-5-103 Master:
> Flags attribute created in ASDUSettings node;
Modbus Master:
> Bit[1] added to AO.Qualifier which allows to multiply AO command value to the register contents received from outstation;
V42 12/05/2024 AK
Basic PLC:
> Substitution node created which allows to substitute received analog value with a specific value;
> Analog value addition and multiplication options added to PlcType attribute;
Modbus Master:
> Device address 0 can now be used for Modbus TCP stations;
V41 14/11/2023 AK
IEC60870-5-101/4 Slave:
> orCat attribute added to ASDUSettings node. Only used for sending control commands to IEC61850 Client instances;
IEC61850 Client:
> orCat and orIdent attributes removed from AcsiSettings node;
Logger:
> BufferSize attribute created to select size of the pcap captured data buffer in bytes;
V40 11/07/2023 AK
Basic PLC:
> PLC point position can trigger continuous sending of commands, PLC point Action attribute values 3 and 4;
V39 27/06/2023 AK
Modbus Master:
> Modbus Read/Write File Record functions (20 and 21) supported in Initialization MSG.Func attribute;
> File attribute created to specify file number for Read/Write File Record functions;
V38 08/06/2023 AK

> DI.OnDelay and DI.OffDelay attributes created allowing to delay DI position change events;
Spabus Master:
> Bit[5] added to DI.Qualifier, select First or Last time tag for DPI reporting if Intermediate state is delayed;
Modbus Master:
> LEIODC-P32-3100; LEIODC-P32-4000; LEIODC-P32-0400; LEIODC-P32-2200 types added to Hardcoded.Type attribute;
ConditionTable group created for basic PLC allowing to convert AI values to DI positions;

Spabus Master communication protocol implemented Spabusma;
Basic PLC functionality implemented, section Internal PLC;

> ACDAlways and ACDLinkStatusResp attributes migrated to Bit[3] and Bit[4] in LinkSettings.Flags respectively;

> IgnoreWhileLinkcnt attribute migrated to Bit[4] in LinkSettings.Flags;

> Bit[4] of the LinkSettings.Flags that enables use of ‘Reset FCB’ message for checking if station is online changed to Bit[2];
IEC60870-5-104 Master:
> GIAfterRecovery attribute migrated to Bit[3] in CommsSettings.Flags;

> Bit[5] added to AI.qualifier, option to ignore analog values received from outstation in General Interrogation;
IEC61850 Client:
> Flags attribute removed from AppSettings and split into AcsiSettings.Flags; RCBFlags; DSFlags;
> Most bits migrated from ScsmSettings.Flags attribute and split between AcsiSettings.Flags; RCBFlags; DSFlags;
> Bdyndsname; Udyndsname; BOptFlds; UOptFlds attributes moved from ScsmSettings to AcsiSettings;
> orCat; orIdent; bufTime attributes moved from AppSettings to AcsiSettings;
> Most bits of AARQfields attribute changed, all fields of AARQ APDU can be Included/Excluded now;
> MMSSettings node created and MMSversion attribute migrated to MMSSettings.ASN;
> PDUsize, TS1timeout and LogFlags attributes added to TransportSettings;
> TIMtimeout and LogFlags attributes added to SessionSettings;
> Bit[2] added to SessionSettings.Flags attribute which allows to keep transport connection when sending [ABORT (AB) SPDU];
> LogFlags attribute added to PresentationSettings;
> CallingAPinvokeID, CallingAEinvokeID and LogFlags attributes added to AssociationSettings;
> Bit[4] added to ScsmSettings.Flags attribute to control the manner in which Array elements are addressed;
> Bit[11] added to ScsmSettings.Flags attribute to enable [AlternateAccess] addressing of all elements;
> AcsiSettings node created and new Maxdynds attribute created to limit maximal number of Dynamic datasets that can be created;
> Bit[2] added to AcsiSettings.Flags attribute to enable reading Basic Types of elements required for DI/AI data acquisition if IED doesn’t support Dynamic datasets;
> DSnum attribute migrated to DI.DSref and AI.DSref where full dataset reference can be specified;
> Bit[6] removed from DI.Qualifier and AI.Qualifier, non-persistent dynamic dataset name can be specified in DI.DSref and AI.DSref attributes;
